{"title_page": "Tasimeter", "text_new": "[[Image:Tasimetro-Tasimeter 1 Edison.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Tasimeter]]\n[[File:PSM V14 D153 Cutaway view of the aerophone.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Tasimeter (partial cross section)]]\n[[File:PSM V17 D031 Microtasimeter measuring carbon sensitivity.jpg|thumb|right|Tasimeter electrical circuit for measuring carbon sensitivity]] \nThe '''tasimeter''', or '''microtasimeter''', or ''measurer of infinitesimal pressure'', is a device designed by [[Thomas Edison]] to measure [[infrared radiation]]. In 1878, [[Samuel Langley]], [[Henry Draper]], and other American scientists needed a highly sensitive instrument that could be used to measure minute temperature changes in heat emitted from the Sun's [[solar corona|corona]] during the [[Solar eclipse of July 29, 1878|July 29 solar eclipse]], due to occur along the [[Rocky Mountains]]. To satisfy those needs Edison devised a ''microtasimeter'' employing a [[carbon]] button.<ref name=PMM>{{cite web|url=http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Popular_Science_Monthly/Volume_14/December_1878/Edison%27s_Telephonic_and_Acoustic_Inventions?uselang=en-gb |title=Popular Science Monthly, Volume 14, December 1878|access-date=31 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Description of operation==\nThe value of the instrument lies in its ability to detect small variations of temperature. This is accomplished indirectly. The change of temperature causes expansion or contraction of a rod of [[vulcanite]], which changes the resistance of an electric circuit by varying the pressure it exerts upon a carbon-button included in the circuit. During the total eclipse of the sun in 1878, it successfully demonstrated the existence of heat in the corona. It is also of service in ascertaining the relative expansion of substances due to a rise of temperature.<ref name=PMM />\n\nThe functional parts are represented in the partial cross section, which shows its construction and mode of operation. The substance whose expansion is to be measured is shown at ''A''. It is firmly clamped at ''B'', its lower end fitting into a slot in the metal\nplate, ''M'', which rests upon the carbon-button. The latter is in an electric circuit, which includes also a delicate [[galvanometer]]. Any variation in the length of the rod changes the pressure upon the carbon, and alters the resistance of the circuit. This causes a deflection of the galvanometer-needle\u2014a movement in one direction denoting expansion of ''A'', while an opposite motion signifies contraction. To avoid any deflection which might arise from change in strength of battery, the tasimeter is inserted in an arm of a [[Wheatstone bridge]].<ref name=PMM />\n\nIn order to ascertain the exact amount of expansion in decimals of an inch, the screw ''S'', seen in front of the dial, is turned until the deflection previously caused by the change of temperature is reproduced. The screw works a second screw, causing the rod to ascend or descend, and the exact distance through which the rod moves is indicated by the needle, ''N'', on the dial.<ref name=PMM />\n\nThe instrument can also be advantageously used to measure changes in the humidity of the atmosphere. In this case the strip of vulcanite is replaced by one of [[gelatine]], which changes its volume by absorbing moisture.<ref name=PMM />\n\n==Other uses==\n1878 was a time when great advances were being made in electric arc lighting, and during the solar eclipse expedition, which Edison accompanied, the men discussed the practicality of ''subdividing'' the intense arc lights so that electricity could be used for lighting in the same fashion as with small, individual gas burners. The basic problem seemed to be to keep the burner, or bulb, from being consumed by preventing it from overheating. Edison thought he would be able to solve this by fashioning a microtasimeter-like device to control the current. He boldly announced that he would invent a safe, mild, and inexpensive electric light that would replace the gaslight.<ref name=PMM />\n\n==Abandonment==\nEdison declined to patent the device, saying it was only of interest to scientists, and allowed companies in London and Philadelphia to manufacture tasimeters royalty-free. The scientists who tested it found it too erratic to be of use for quantitative measurement purposes, and it was soon abandoned.<ref>{{cite book |last=Baron |first=David |date=June 6, 2017 |title=American Eclipse: A Nation's Epic Race to Catch the Shadow of the Moon and Win the Glory of the World |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kNpDDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT218&dq=american+eclipse+Tasimeter+not+patented&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjlvt3Ej9_nAhURWN8KHfdJD-0Q6AEwAHoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=american%20eclipse%20Tasimeter%20not%20patented&f=false |publisher=Liveright |page=223 |isbn=1631490168}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bolometer]]\n* [[Infrared telescope]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/id.3373,y.0,no.,content.true,page.3,css.print/issue.aspx Eclipse Vicissitudes:Thomas Edison and the Chickens], J. Donald Fernie, [[American Scientist]].\n* [http://www.opticsinfobase.org/abstract.cfm?URI=ao-18-22-3737 Edison the scientist], John A. Eddy, [[Applied Optics]] (may require subscription).\n\n{{Thomas Edison}}\n\n[[Category:Observational astronomy]]\n[[Category:American inventions]]\n[[Category:19th-century inventions]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Tasimetro-Tasimeter 1 Edison.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Tasimeter]]\n[[File:PSM V14 D153 Cutaway view of the aerophone.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Tasimeter (partial cross section)]]\n[[File:PSM V17 D031 Microtasimeter measuring carbon sensitivity.jpg|thumb|right|Tasimeter electrical circuit for measuring carbon sensitivity]] \nThe '''tasimeter''', or '''microtasimeter''', or ''measurer of infinitesimal pressure'', is a device designed by [[Thomas Edison]] to measure [[infrared radiation]]. In 1878, [[Samuel Langley]], [[Henry Draper]], and other American scientists needed a highly sensitive instrument that could be used to measure minute temperature changes in heat emitted from the Sun's [[corona]] during the [[Solar eclipse of July 29, 1878|July 29 solar eclipse]], due to occur along the [[Rocky Mountains]]. To satisfy those needs Edison devised a ''microtasimeter'' employing a [[carbon]] button.<ref name=PMM>{{cite web|url=http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Popular_Science_Monthly/Volume_14/December_1878/Edison%27s_Telephonic_and_Acoustic_Inventions?uselang=en-gb |title=Popular Science Monthly, Volume 14, December 1878|access-date=31 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Description of operation==\nThe value of the instrument lies in its ability to detect small variations of temperature. This is accomplished indirectly. The change of temperature causes expansion or contraction of a rod of [[vulcanite]], which changes the resistance of an electric circuit by varying the pressure it exerts upon a carbon-button included in the circuit. During the total eclipse of the sun in 1878, it successfully demonstrated the existence of heat in the corona. It is also of service in ascertaining the relative expansion of substances due to a rise of temperature.<ref name=PMM />\n\nThe functional parts are represented in the partial cross section, which shows its construction and mode of operation. The substance whose expansion is to be measured is shown at ''A''. It is firmly clamped at ''B'', its lower end fitting into a slot in the metal\nplate, ''M'', which rests upon the carbon-button. The latter is in an electric circuit, which includes also a delicate [[galvanometer]]. Any variation in the length of the rod changes the pressure upon the carbon, and alters the resistance of the circuit. This causes a deflection of the galvanometer-needle\u2014a movement in one direction denoting expansion of ''A'', while an opposite motion signifies contraction. To avoid any deflection which might arise from change in strength of battery, the tasimeter is inserted in an arm of a [[Wheatstone bridge]].<ref name=PMM />\n\nIn order to ascertain the exact amount of expansion in decimals of an inch, the screw ''S'', seen in front of the dial, is turned until the deflection previously caused by the change of temperature is reproduced. The screw works a second screw, causing the rod to ascend or descend, and the exact distance through which the rod moves is indicated by the needle, ''N'', on the dial.<ref name=PMM />\n\nThe instrument can also be advantageously used to measure changes in the humidity of the atmosphere. In this case the strip of vulcanite is replaced by one of [[gelatine]], which changes its volume by absorbing moisture.<ref name=PMM />\n\n==Other uses==\n1878 was a time when great advances were being made in electric arc lighting, and during the solar eclipse expedition, which Edison accompanied, the men discussed the practicality of ''subdividing'' the intense arc lights so that electricity could be used for lighting in the same fashion as with small, individual gas burners. The basic problem seemed to be to keep the burner, or bulb, from being consumed by preventing it from overheating. Edison thought he would be able to solve this by fashioning a microtasimeter-like device to control the current. He boldly announced that he would invent a safe, mild, and inexpensive electric light that would replace the gaslight.<ref name=PMM />\n\n==Abandonment==\nEdison declined to patent the device, saying it was only of interest to scientists, and allowed companies in London and Philadelphia to manufacture tasimeters royalty-free. The scientists who tested it found it too erratic to be of use for quantitative measurement purposes, and it was soon abandoned.<ref>{{cite book |last=Baron |first=David |date=June 6, 2017 |title=American Eclipse: A Nation's Epic Race to Catch the Shadow of the Moon and Win the Glory of the World |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kNpDDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT218&dq=american+eclipse+Tasimeter+not+patented&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjlvt3Ej9_nAhURWN8KHfdJD-0Q6AEwAHoECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=american%20eclipse%20Tasimeter%20not%20patented&f=false |publisher=Liveright |page=223 |isbn=1631490168}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bolometer]]\n* [[Infrared telescope]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/id.3373,y.0,no.,content.true,page.3,css.print/issue.aspx Eclipse Vicissitudes:Thomas Edison and the Chickens], J. Donald Fernie, [[American Scientist]].\n* [http://www.opticsinfobase.org/abstract.cfm?URI=ao-18-22-3737 Edison the scientist], John A. Eddy, [[Applied Optics]] (may require subscription).\n\n{{Thomas Edison}}\n\n[[Category:Observational astronomy]]\n[[Category:American inventions]]\n[[Category:19th-century inventions]]\n", "name_user": "Netoholic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:post-move link fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tasimeter"}
{"title_page": "Astronomical Institute of Slovak Academy of Sciences", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n[[Image:Asusav2.jpg|right|thumb|220px|Headquarters of the astronomical institute.]]\n\n'''The Astronomical Institute of Slovak Academy of Sciences''' was founded in 1953, when the state observatory on Skalnat\u00e9 Pleso (founded in 1943 by Dr.\nBe\u010dv\u00e1\u0159) got a status of astronomical institute and became one of the founding institutes of the newly born Slovakian Academy of Sciences. In memories of past and current employees, the institute and the observatory on Skalnat\u00e9 Pleso were always blended in one and therefore one could consider for the year of the institute foundation already the 1943. Currently, it has its headquarters at [[Tatransk\u00e1 Lomnica]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Pre\u010do sme, pre\u010do sme tu a kto sme?\n| url = http://www.ta3.sk/public_relation/60SP50AsU/8/8.html\n|date= 12 September 2009\n| accessdate = 12 September 2009}}\n</ref>\n\n==Field of research and organization of the institute==\n[[Image:Lomnicky Stit.jpg|right|thumb|Astronomical and meteorological station on the [[Lomnick\u00fd \u0161t\u00edt]] (working since 1960), which is the third highest summit of Slovakia.]]\n\nThe institute focuses its research on the Sun, interplanetary matter (comets, meteoroids, asteroids) and on astrophysical research of variable and chemically peculiar stars. It has about 65 permanent employees of which roughly 50 are active researchers. It is divided into 3 departments:\n<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = V\u0161eobecne o astronomickom \u00fastave\n| url = http://www.ta3.sk/l2_sk.php?part=general&cont=descr\n|date= 8 September 2009\n| accessdate = 8 September 2009}}\n</ref>\n\n===Department of Solar Physics===\nInterest in solar atmospheric activity led the department to focus on many processes in the solar [[photosphere]], [[chromosphere]] and [[solar corona|corona]] based on spectral line analysis using observational data from the\nVacuum Tower Telescope ([[Vacuum Tower Telescope|VTT]]) on [[Tenerife]] and utilization of data from [[Solar and Heliospheric Observatory]] (SOHO), including their own coronal observations. The head of the department is Ale\u0161 Ku\u010dera.\n\n===Department of Interplanetary Matter===\nResearch employs [[Photometry (astronomy)|photometry]] and [[astrometry]] of [[asteroid]]s and [[comet]]s using the main [[telescope]] of Skalnat\u00e9 Pleso observatory. Furthermore, [[fish-eye cameras]] are used to detect [[bolide]]s on the sky. The head of the department is J\u00e1n Svore\u0148.\n\n===Stellar Physics Department===\nThis department is focused on [[Binary star|binary]] and [[Star system|multiple stellar systems]]. Its research employs [[spectroscopy]] and utilization of synthetic spectra and stellar databases from space-based observatories like [[Hubble Space Telescope|HST]], [[Hipparcos]] and the TYCHO catalogues. The head of the department is Drahom\u00edr Chochol.\n\n===Facilities of the Institute===\nThe institute has mountain [[observatory|observatories]] at [[Skalnat\u00e9 Pleso Observatory|Skalnat\u00e9 Pleso]], [[Lomnick\u00fd \u0161t\u00edt]] and a theoretical department in [[Bratislava]] (founded in 1955), which is a statewide coordinating body for research of interplanetary matter. Moreover, it runs several full-sky photographic chambers (bolide cameras) which are part of European bolide network.\n\nThe astronomical observatory at Skalnat\u00e9 Pleso (1783 m) was founded in 1943. It is equipped with a 61&nbsp;cm astrometrical and photometric reflector with a [[Charge-coupled device|CCD camera]] and a 60&nbsp;cm photometric reflector. The astronomical station on Lomnick\u00fd \u0161t\u00edt (2632 m) has been active since 1960. It is equipped with a 20&nbsp;cm [[coronograph]] and a [[Spectrometer|spectrograph]]. In the headquarters of the astronomical institute at Tatransk\u00e1 Lomnica a 60&nbsp;cm reflector and a solar horizontal spectrograph are located.\n\n== Directors of the institute <ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Directors of the Astronomical Institute\n| url = http://www.ta3.sk/l3.php?p3=dirs\n|date= 8 September 2009\n| accessdate = 8 September 2009}}\n</ref> ==\n\n* [[Anton\u00edn Be\u010dv\u00e1\u0159]] (1943\u20131950)\n* V. Guth (1951\u20131956)\n* [[Z\u00e1vi\u0161 Bochn\u00ed\u010dek]] (1956\u20131958)\n* [[\u013dudmila Pajdu\u0161\u00e1kov\u00e1]] (1958\u20131979)\n* J\u00falius S\u00fdkora (1979\u20131989)\n* J\u00e1n \u0160tohl (1989\u20131993)\n* Juraj Zverko (1993\u20132001)\n* J\u00e1n Svore\u0148 (2001\u20132009)\n* Ale\u0161 Ku\u010dera (2009\u2013)\n\n==Highlights of the institute==\nThe astronomical institute participated on discoveries of the following comets:\n<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Objavy a fyzika kom\u00e9t\n| url = http://www.ta3.sk/public_relation/60SP50AsU/4/4.html\n|date= 9 September 2009\n| accessdate = 9 September 2009}}\n</ref>\n\n[[Image:Observat\u00f3rium Skalnat\u00e9 pleso 1.jpg|right|thumb]]\n[[Image:Observat\u00f3rium Skalnat\u00e9 pleso 3.JPG|right|thumb]]\n[[Image:Observat\u00f3rium Skalnat\u00e9 pleso 2.jpg|right|thumb|Observatory on the Skalnat\u00e9 Pleso (founded in 1943).]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n|'''Name''' ||'''Label''' ||'''Date of the discovery''' || '''Brightness at the discovery (mag)'''\n|-\n|Pajdu\u0161\u00e1kov\u00e1-Rotbar-Weber ||C/1946 K1 ||30. 05. 1946 || 7\n|-\n|Be\u010dv\u00e1\u0159 ||C/1947 F2 ||27. 03. 1947 || 9\n|-\n|Mrkos            ||C/1947 Y1 ||20. 12. 1947 || 9,5\n|-\n|Pajdu\u0161\u00e1kov\u00e1-Mrkos ||C/1948 E1 ||15. 02. 1948 || 10\n|-\n|P/Honda-Mrkos-Pajdu\u0161\u00e1kov\u00e1 ||45P ||03. 12. 1948 || 9\n|-\n|Pajdu\u0161\u00e1kov\u00e1 ||C/1951 C1 ||04. 02. 1951 || 8,5\n|-\n|P/Tuttle-Giacobini-Kres\u00e1k ||41P ||24. 04. 1951 || 10,5\n|-\n|Mrkos ||C/1952 H1 ||27. 04. 1952 || 10\n|-\n|Mrkos ||C/1952 W1 ||28. 11. 1952 || 10\n|-\n|Mrkos-Honda ||C/1953 G1 ||12. 04. 1953 || 9\n|-\n|Pajdu\u0161\u00e1kov\u00e1 ||C/1953 X1 ||03. 12. 1953 || 11\n|-\n|Voz\u00e1rov\u00e1 ||C/1954 O1 ||28. 07. 1954 || 9\n|-\n|Kres\u00e1k-Peltier ||C/1954 M2 ||26. 06. 1954 || 10\n|-\n|Mrkos ||C/1955 L1 ||12. 06. 1955 || 3,5\n|-\n|P/Perrine-Mrkos ||18D ||19. 10. 1955 || 9\n|-\n|Mrkos ||C/1956 E1 ||12. 03. 1956 || 9\n|-\n|Mrkos ||C/1957 P1 ||29. 07. 1957 ||  3\n|-\n|Mrkos ||C/1959 X1 ||03. 12. 1959 || 8\n|}\n\nFive astronomers participated in the discoveries: [[Anton\u00edn Mrkos]], [[\u013dudmila Pajdu\u0161\u00e1kov\u00e1]], [[\u013dubor Kres\u00e1k]], [[Anton\u00edn Be\u010dv\u00e1\u0159]] and [[Margita Kres\u00e1kov\u00e1]]. From 70 comets discovered worldwide between 1946\u20131959, 18 were discovered from the observatories at Skalnat\u00e9 Pleso and Lomnick\u00fd \u0161t\u00edt.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Astronomical Institute of Czech Academy of Sciences]]\n* [[Ond\u0159ejov Observatory]]\n* [[Institute of physics of the University of Pavol Jozef \u0160af\u00e1rik]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ta3.sk Official webpage of the astronomical institute]\n\n{{coord missing|Slovakia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Astronomical Institute Of Slovak Academy Of Sciences}}\n[[Category:Astronomical observatories in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Education in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in Slovakia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n[[Image:Asusav2.jpg|right|thumb|220px|Headquarters of the astronomical institute.]]\n\n'''The Astronomical Institute of Slovak Academy of Sciences''' was founded in 1953, when the state observatory on Skalnat\u00e9 Pleso (founded in 1943 by Dr.\nBe\u010dv\u00e1\u0159) got a status of astronomical institute and became one of the founding institutes of the newly born Slovakian Academy of Sciences. In memories of past and current employees, the institute and the observatory on Skalnat\u00e9 Pleso were always blended in one and therefore one could consider for the year of the institute foundation already the 1943. Currently, it has its headquarters at [[Tatransk\u00e1 Lomnica]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Pre\u010do sme, pre\u010do sme tu a kto sme?\n| url = http://www.ta3.sk/public_relation/60SP50AsU/8/8.html\n|date= 12 September 2009\n| accessdate = 12 September 2009}}\n</ref>\n\n==Field of research and organization of the institute==\n[[Image:Lomnicky Stit.jpg|right|thumb|Astronomical and meteorological station on the [[Lomnick\u00fd \u0161t\u00edt]] (working since 1960), which is the third highest summit of Slovakia.]]\n\nThe institute focuses its research on the Sun, interplanetary matter (comets, meteoroids, asteroids) and on astrophysical research of variable and chemically peculiar stars. It has about 65 permanent employees of which roughly 50 are active researchers. It is divided into 3 departments:\n<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = V\u0161eobecne o astronomickom \u00fastave\n| url = http://www.ta3.sk/l2_sk.php?part=general&cont=descr\n|date= 8 September 2009\n| accessdate = 8 September 2009}}\n</ref>\n\n===Department of Solar Physics===\nInterest in solar atmospheric activity led the department to focus on many processes in the solar [[photosphere]], [[chromosphere]] and [[corona]] based on spectral line analysis using observational data from the\nVacuum Tower Telescope ([[Vacuum Tower Telescope|VTT]]) on [[Tenerife]] and utilization of data from [[Solar and Heliospheric Observatory]] (SOHO), including their own coronal observations. The head of the department is Ale\u0161 Ku\u010dera.\n\n===Department of Interplanetary Matter===\nResearch employs [[Photometry (astronomy)|photometry]] and [[astrometry]] of [[asteroid]]s and [[comet]]s using the main [[telescope]] of Skalnat\u00e9 Pleso observatory. Furthermore, [[fish-eye cameras]] are used to detect [[bolide]]s on the sky. The head of the department is J\u00e1n Svore\u0148.\n\n===Stellar Physics Department===\nThis department is focused on [[Binary star|binary]] and [[Star system|multiple stellar systems]]. Its research employs [[spectroscopy]] and utilization of synthetic spectra and stellar databases from space-based observatories like [[Hubble Space Telescope|HST]], [[Hipparcos]] and the TYCHO catalogues. The head of the department is Drahom\u00edr Chochol.\n\n===Facilities of the Institute===\nThe institute has mountain [[observatory|observatories]] at [[Skalnat\u00e9 Pleso Observatory|Skalnat\u00e9 Pleso]], [[Lomnick\u00fd \u0161t\u00edt]] and a theoretical department in [[Bratislava]] (founded in 1955), which is a statewide coordinating body for research of interplanetary matter. Moreover, it runs several full-sky photographic chambers (bolide cameras) which are part of European bolide network.\n\nThe astronomical observatory at Skalnat\u00e9 Pleso (1783 m) was founded in 1943. It is equipped with a 61&nbsp;cm astrometrical and photometric reflector with a [[Charge-coupled device|CCD camera]] and a 60&nbsp;cm photometric reflector. The astronomical station on Lomnick\u00fd \u0161t\u00edt (2632 m) has been active since 1960. It is equipped with a 20&nbsp;cm [[coronograph]] and a [[Spectrometer|spectrograph]]. In the headquarters of the astronomical institute at Tatransk\u00e1 Lomnica a 60&nbsp;cm reflector and a solar horizontal spectrograph are located.\n\n== Directors of the institute <ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Directors of the Astronomical Institute\n| url = http://www.ta3.sk/l3.php?p3=dirs\n|date= 8 September 2009\n| accessdate = 8 September 2009}}\n</ref> ==\n\n* [[Anton\u00edn Be\u010dv\u00e1\u0159]] (1943\u20131950)\n* V. Guth (1951\u20131956)\n* [[Z\u00e1vi\u0161 Bochn\u00ed\u010dek]] (1956\u20131958)\n* [[\u013dudmila Pajdu\u0161\u00e1kov\u00e1]] (1958\u20131979)\n* J\u00falius S\u00fdkora (1979\u20131989)\n* J\u00e1n \u0160tohl (1989\u20131993)\n* Juraj Zverko (1993\u20132001)\n* J\u00e1n Svore\u0148 (2001\u20132009)\n* Ale\u0161 Ku\u010dera (2009\u2013)\n\n==Highlights of the institute==\nThe astronomical institute participated on discoveries of the following comets:\n<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Objavy a fyzika kom\u00e9t\n| url = http://www.ta3.sk/public_relation/60SP50AsU/4/4.html\n|date= 9 September 2009\n| accessdate = 9 September 2009}}\n</ref>\n\n[[Image:Observat\u00f3rium Skalnat\u00e9 pleso 1.jpg|right|thumb]]\n[[Image:Observat\u00f3rium Skalnat\u00e9 pleso 3.JPG|right|thumb]]\n[[Image:Observat\u00f3rium Skalnat\u00e9 pleso 2.jpg|right|thumb|Observatory on the Skalnat\u00e9 Pleso (founded in 1943).]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n|'''Name''' ||'''Label''' ||'''Date of the discovery''' || '''Brightness at the discovery (mag)'''\n|-\n|Pajdu\u0161\u00e1kov\u00e1-Rotbar-Weber ||C/1946 K1 ||30. 05. 1946 || 7\n|-\n|Be\u010dv\u00e1\u0159 ||C/1947 F2 ||27. 03. 1947 || 9\n|-\n|Mrkos            ||C/1947 Y1 ||20. 12. 1947 || 9,5\n|-\n|Pajdu\u0161\u00e1kov\u00e1-Mrkos ||C/1948 E1 ||15. 02. 1948 || 10\n|-\n|P/Honda-Mrkos-Pajdu\u0161\u00e1kov\u00e1 ||45P ||03. 12. 1948 || 9\n|-\n|Pajdu\u0161\u00e1kov\u00e1 ||C/1951 C1 ||04. 02. 1951 || 8,5\n|-\n|P/Tuttle-Giacobini-Kres\u00e1k ||41P ||24. 04. 1951 || 10,5\n|-\n|Mrkos ||C/1952 H1 ||27. 04. 1952 || 10\n|-\n|Mrkos ||C/1952 W1 ||28. 11. 1952 || 10\n|-\n|Mrkos-Honda ||C/1953 G1 ||12. 04. 1953 || 9\n|-\n|Pajdu\u0161\u00e1kov\u00e1 ||C/1953 X1 ||03. 12. 1953 || 11\n|-\n|Voz\u00e1rov\u00e1 ||C/1954 O1 ||28. 07. 1954 || 9\n|-\n|Kres\u00e1k-Peltier ||C/1954 M2 ||26. 06. 1954 || 10\n|-\n|Mrkos ||C/1955 L1 ||12. 06. 1955 || 3,5\n|-\n|P/Perrine-Mrkos ||18D ||19. 10. 1955 || 9\n|-\n|Mrkos ||C/1956 E1 ||12. 03. 1956 || 9\n|-\n|Mrkos ||C/1957 P1 ||29. 07. 1957 ||  3\n|-\n|Mrkos ||C/1959 X1 ||03. 12. 1959 || 8\n|}\n\nFive astronomers participated in the discoveries: [[Anton\u00edn Mrkos]], [[\u013dudmila Pajdu\u0161\u00e1kov\u00e1]], [[\u013dubor Kres\u00e1k]], [[Anton\u00edn Be\u010dv\u00e1\u0159]] and [[Margita Kres\u00e1kov\u00e1]]. From 70 comets discovered worldwide between 1946\u20131959, 18 were discovered from the observatories at Skalnat\u00e9 Pleso and Lomnick\u00fd \u0161t\u00edt.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Astronomical Institute of Czech Academy of Sciences]]\n* [[Ond\u0159ejov Observatory]]\n* [[Institute of physics of the University of Pavol Jozef \u0160af\u00e1rik]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ta3.sk Official webpage of the astronomical institute]\n\n{{coord missing|Slovakia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Astronomical Institute Of Slovak Academy Of Sciences}}\n[[Category:Astronomical observatories in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Education in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in Slovakia]]\n", "name_user": "Netoholic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDepartment of Solar Physics:post-move link fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astronomical_Institute_of_Slovak_Academy_of_Sciences"}
{"title_page": "2011 Super Outbreak", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Super Outbreak (disambiguation)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = 2011 Super Outbreak\n| image = Apr 27 2011 tornado outbreak Southern USA.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = The storm system responsible for the historic tornado outbreak on April 27\n| type = [[Tornado outbreak]]<br/>[[Extratropical cyclone]]<br/>[[Flood]]\n| active = April 25\u201328, 2011 \n| lowest pressure = \n| lowest temperature =\n| tornadoes = [[List of tornadoes in the 2011 Super Outbreak|360 confirmed]]<br />{{small|(Record for a continuous outbreak)}}\n| fujitascale = EF5\n| tornado duration = 3 days, 7 hours, 18 minutes\n| highest winds = {{convert|210|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}<br/><small>([[Hackleburg, Alabama|Hackleburg]]/[[Phil Campbell, Alabama|Phil Campbell, AL]] EF5 on April 27)</small>\n| hail = {{convert|4.5|in|cm|}} in diameter in [[Saltville, Virginia]], on April 27\n| gusts =\n| maximum snow = \n| power outages =\n| total fatalities = 324 (+24 non-tornadic) fatalities, 3,100+ injuries<ref name=\"spc fatal\"/><ref name=\"cbs342\">{{cite news|publisher=[[CBS News]]|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2011/05/01/national/main20058765.shtml?tag=cbsContent;cbsCarousel|title=Tornado victims seek comfort in Sunday services|date=May 1, 2011|accessdate=May 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Vilonia\">{{cite web|work=[[National Weather Service]] in Little Rock, Arkansas|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=April 28, 2011|title=Heavy Rain/Severe Weather on April 23\u201327, 2011|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/lzk/?n=hydro0411.htm}}</ref><ref name=cnn>{{cite news|publisher=CNN|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/US/05/01/severe.weather/index.html?hpt=T2/|title=Top federal officials tour, promise help to tornado-ravaged South|accessdate=May 1, 2011|date=May 1, 2011}}</ref>\n| damages = ~$11 billion (2011 USD)<ref name=InsuranceNewsnet/><br/><small>(Costliest on record for a tornado outbreak)</small>\n| affected = [[Southern United States]], [[Midwestern United States]], [[Eastern United States]]\n| current advisories =\n| enhanced = yes\n| partof = the '''[[Tornadoes of 2011|tornado outbreaks of 2011]]'''\n}}\n\nThe '''2011 Super Outbreak''' was the largest, costliest, and one of the deadliest [[tornado outbreak]]s ever recorded, taking place along the [[Southern United States|Southern]], [[Midwest]]ern, and [[Northeastern United States|Northeastern]] [[United States]] and leaving catastrophic destruction in its wake.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Tornado Debris Characteristics and Trajectories During the 27 April 2011 Super Outbreak as Determined Using Social Media Data|journal=Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society|volume=94|issue=9|pages=1371\u20131380|doi=10.1175/BAMS-D-12-00036.1|year = 2013|last1 = Knox|first1 = John A.|last2=Rackley|first2=Jared A.|last3=Black|first3=Alan W.|last4=Gensini|first4=Vittorio A.|last5=Butler|first5=Michael|last6=Dunn|first6=Corey|last7=Gallo|first7=Taylor|last8=Hunter|first8=Melyssa R.|last9=Lindsey|first9=Lauren|last10=Phan|first10=Minh|last11=Scroggs|first11=Robert|last12=Brustad|first12=Synne}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ams.confex.com/ams/93Annual/webprogram/Paper223690.html|title=Abstract: Comparative Analysis of Multiple Tornado Tracks During Severe Weather Outbreaks: 2011 Super Outbreak, Alabama (93rd American Meteorological Society Annual Meeting)|work=confex.com|date=2013-01-08}}</ref><ref name=\"noaanews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.noaanews.noaa.gov/april_2011_tornado_information.html|title=April 2011 tornado information|date=May 9, 2011|work=[[USA.gov]]|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=May 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/bmx/?n=climo_2011torstats|title=New Tornado Records Set for Alabama|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Birmingham, Alabama|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref> The event not only affected [[Alabama]] and [[Mississippi]] the most severely, but also produced destructive [[tornado]]es in [[Arkansas]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Tennessee]] and [[Virginia]], and affected many other areas throughout the Southern and Eastern United States. In total, 360 tornadoes were confirmed by [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|NOAA]]'s [[National Weather Service]] (NWS) and [[Government of Canada]]'s [[Environment Canada]] in 21 states from [[Texas]] to [[New York State|New York]] to southern [[Canada]]. Widespread and destructive tornadoes occurred on each day of the outbreak, with April 27 being the most active day with a record of 216 tornadoes touching down that day from midnight to midnight [[Central Time Zone|CDT]] (0500 \u2013 0500 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]). Four of the tornadoes were destructive enough to be rated EF5, which is the highest ranking possible on the [[Enhanced Fujita scale]]; typically these tornadoes are only recorded about once each year or less.<ref name=\"noaanews\"/>\n\nIn total, 348 people were killed as a result of the outbreak, which includes 324 tornado-related deaths across six states and an additional 24 fatalities caused by other [[thunderstorm]]-related events such as [[downbursts|straight-line winds]], [[hail]], [[flash flooding]] or [[lightning]].<ref name=\"alemapressrelease1\"/><ref name=\"tuscaloosa missing\">{{cite web|author=Jason Morton|publisher=[[The Tuscaloosa News|Tuscaloosa News]]|date=May 5, 2011|accessdate=May 5, 2011|title=List of missing at 25|url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20110505/NEWS/110509813/1291/dateline?Title=List-of-missing-at-25}}</ref> In Alabama alone, 238 tornado-related deaths were confirmed by the [[Storm Prediction Center]] (SPC) and the state's [[Emergency management|Emergency Management Agency]].<ref name=\"spc fatal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/torn/fataltorn.html|title=Annual Fatal Tornado Summaries|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|work=[[Storm Prediction Center]]|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"alemapressrelease1\">{{cite web|url=http://ema.alabama.gov/filelibrary/PressRelease/NR%20Latest%20Fatalites%20249_043011.pdf |title=Number of weather related fatalities 236 |date=April 30, 2011 |work=Alabama Emergency Management Agency |publisher=State of Alabama |accessdate=April 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224082245/http://ema.alabama.gov/filelibrary/PressRelease/NR%20Latest%20Fatalites%20249_043011.pdf |archivedate=December 24, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nApril 27's 316 fatalities were the most tornado-related fatalities in the United States in a single day since the \"[[Tri-State Tornado|Tri-State]]\" outbreak on March 18, 1925 (when at least 747 people were killed).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crh.noaa.gov/mkx/?n=torout|title=Famous Large Tornado Outbreaks In The U.S |work=National Weather Service in Milwaukee/Sullivan, Wisconsin|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=cnn1925outbreak>{{cite news|publisher=CNN|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/US/04/30/severe.weather/index.html?hpt=T2/|title=Harrowing stories emerge from storm's aftermath|accessdate=April 30, 2011|date=April 30, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"cbsSouth\">{{cite news|publisher=CBS News|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2011/05/01/national/main20058748.shtml?tag=strip|title=South mourns victims of deadly tornadoes|date=April 30, 2011|accessdate=May 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"second deadliest\">{{cite news|publisher=[[NBC News]]/[[Associated Press|AP News and Reuters]] (jointly produced article)|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/42834400|title=Twister Outbreak is Second Deadliest in History|accessdate=April 30, 2011|date=April 30, 2011}}</ref> Nearly 500 preliminary [[local storm report]]s were received for tornadoes over four days, including 292 in 16 states on April 27 alone.<ref name=\"Storm Reports April 27\"/> This event was the costliest tornado outbreak and one of the costliest natural disasters in United States history (even after adjustments for [[inflation]]), with total damages of approximately $11 billion (2011 USD).<ref name=InsuranceNewsnet>{{cite web|author=Diana Rosenberg|publisher=[[A. M. Best|A.M. Best Company Inc.]]|date=May 18, 2011|accessdate=May 20, 2011|title=RMS: Insured Losses From Late April Tornadoes Could Reach $6 Billion|url=http://www.insurancenewsnet.com/article.aspx?id=261515&type=propertycasualty}}</ref>\n\n==Meteorological synopsis==\n[[File:Severe Tornado Outbreak in the Southern United States.ogv|thumb|This animation of satellite images from April 26 through the morning of April 28 shows the development of the storm system which spawned the tornadoes.]]\nThe outbreak was caused by a vigorous upper-level [[Trough (meteorology)|trough]] that moved into the Southern Plains states on April 25. An [[extratropical cyclone]] developed ahead of this upper-level trough between northeastern [[Oklahoma]] and western [[Missouri]], and moved northeastward.<ref name=\"SS11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/winter_storm_summaries/2011/storm11/stormsum_11.html|title=Storm Summary Number 11 For Central U.S. Heavy Rain Event|author=Mike Soltow|publisher=[[Weather Prediction Center]]|date=April 25, 2011|accessdate=April 30, 2011}}</ref> Conditions were similar on April 26, with a predicted likelihood of [[severe thunderstorm]]s, including an extended threat of strong to violent long-track tornadoes throughout the afternoon and evening hours; mixed-layer [[Convective available potential energy|CAPE]] values were forecast to be around 3000\u20134000 J/kg, around east [[Texas]], [[Louisiana]], and [[Arkansas]]. The storm mode on April 26 was predicted to include mostly discrete tornadic [[supercell]]s during both the afternoon and the early evening, shifting over to a [[Mesoscale Convective Complex|mesoscale convective complex]], with more of a threat of damaging winds and hail during the nighttime hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2011/day1otlk_20110426_1630.html|title=April 26, 2011 1630 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 26, 2011|accessdate=April 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs the storm system moved eastward toward the Ohio, Mississippi, and Tennessee Valleys on April 27, a very powerful 80\u2013100 [[knot (unit)|knot]] mid-level [[jet stream]] moved into the [[Ohio Valley|Ohio]] and [[Tennessee Valley]]s behind the trough and created strong [[wind shear]], along with a low pressure center moving quickly northeastward across those areas on April 27. During the afternoon of April 27, CAPE values were estimated to be in the range of 2000\u20133000 J/kg across Louisiana and southern Mississippi, with the moderate instability moving northeastward across the southern Tennessee Valley; additionally, temperatures across the southeastern United States ranged from the 70s\u00b0F (mid-20s\u00b0C) to the lower 90s\u00b0F (near 35&nbsp;\u00b0C). [[Hydrodynamical helicity|Helicity]] levels ranged from 450\u2013600 m<sup>2</sup>/s<sup>2</sup>, which supported some significant tornadic activity and strong to violent long-track tornadoes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2011/day1otlk_20110427_1630.html|title=April 27, 2011 1630 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=April 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nA total of 56 severe weather watches were issued by the [[Storm Prediction Center]] (SPC) over those four days in the outbreak area. This included 41 [[tornado watch]]es\u201410 of which were [[Particularly Dangerous Situation]] (PDS) watches\u2014and 15 [[severe thunderstorm watch]]es.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/2011/ww0199.html|title=Severe Thunderstorm Watch 199|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 25, 2011|accessdate=May 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/2011/ww0256.html|title=Tornado Watch 256|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=May 13, 2011}}</ref> The SPC assigns numbers to each severe weather watch issued starting at the beginning of each year; the organization unsuccessfully used two of their allocated watch numbers during this outbreak (numbers 208 and 209).<ref name=\"review\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/exper/archive/event.php?date=20110425|title=SPC Severe Weather Event Review for Monday April 25, 2011|date=25 April 2011|work=Storm Prediction Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===April 25===\nA large area of possible severe storms for April 25\u201327 was forecast as the [[Storm Prediction Center]] (SPC) issued a moderate risk of severe weather for three consecutive days, centered over Arkansas through Tennessee. At 3:25&nbsp;p.m. [[Central Time Zone|CDT]] (2025 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]), the SPC issued a [[Particularly Dangerous Situation]] (PDS) [[tornado watch]] for much of Arkansas and parts of Missouri, Oklahoma, Texas, and [[Louisiana]].<ref name=\"Apr25SPC\">{{cite web|work=Storm Prediction Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=April 25, 2011|accessdate=April 25, 2011|title=Storm Prediction Center 110425's Storm Reports|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/110425_rpts.html}}</ref>  By the evening hours of April 25, tornadoes had been reported across a few states, some of which caused significant damage in [[Arkansas]]. An intense [[supercell]] thunderstorm tracked near the [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]] area and a [[tornado emergency]] was declared for the city of [[Vilonia, Arkansas|Vilonia]]. A large [[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF2]] [[Wedge tornado|wedge]] tornado struck the town, subsequently causing severe damage and killing four people.<ref name=\"MSNBC Arkansas\">{{cite web|title='The town's gone': Seven dead as storm slams Ark. |url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/42760079/ns/weather/ |publisher=[[MSNBC]] |accessdate=April 26, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yEZAH8MQ?url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/42760079/ns/weather/ |archivedate=April 26, 2011 |date=April 26, 2011 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref><ref name=\"New York Times AR Tornado\">{{cite news|author=Timothy Williams |title=Deadly Storm Hits Arkansas Town |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/27/us/27arkansas.html |work=[[The New York Times|New York Times]] |accessdate=April 26, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yEa9DclI?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/27/us/27arkansas.html?_r=1 |archivedate=April 26, 2011 |date=April 26, 2011 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref> A strong EF3 tornado had also struck the [[Hot Springs Village, Arkansas|Hot Springs Village]] area earlier that evening; that tornado caused severe damage and resulted in one death. Later that evening, another EF2 tornado caused extensive damage to both a school building and [[Little Rock Air Force Base]] as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littlerock.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123253582 |title=Aerial photography shows damage at Little Rock Air Force Base following tornado |publisher=[[Little Rock Air Force Base|Little Rock Air Force Base Public Affairs]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430133118/http://www.littlerock.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123253582 |archivedate=April 30, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref> Severe [[flood]]ing continued across a large area from the [[Red River of the South|Red River]] valley to the [[Great Lakes]].<ref>{{cite web|work=National Weather Service in Tulsa, Oklahoma|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=May 10, 2011|accessdate=July 19, 2013|title=Event Summary \u2013 April 21\u201327, 2011 Heavy Rain, Record Flooding, and Severe Weather|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/tsa/?n=weather-event_2011apr25}}</ref> A total of 42 tornadoes and five tornado-related deaths were confirmed on the 25th.\n\n===April 26===\nA [[List of SPC high-risk days|high risk]] of severe weather was issued for April 26 for portions of Louisiana, Arkansas, Oklahoma, and Texas along and near the [[Interstate 30]] corridor as conditions became even more favorable for extreme weather.<ref name=\"HighRisk0426\">{{cite web|work=Storm Prediction Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=April 26, 2011|accessdate=April 26, 2011|title=April 26, 2011 1300 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/day1otlk_1300.html}}</ref> A large PDS tornado watch with very high possibilities for tornadoes was issued for that same area that afternoon.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hart|first=John|title=Particularly Dangerous Situation (PDS) Tornado Watch 215|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/2011/ww0215.html|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|accessdate=April 28, 2011|date=April 26, 2011}}</ref> Widespread [[tornado warning]]s were then issued in that area later that evening.<ref>{{cite web|title=Particularly Dangerous Situation (PDS) Tornado Watch 215|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/2011/ww0215_warnings.gif|date=April 26, 2011|accessdate=July 13, 2013|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Particularly Dangerous Situation (PDS) Tornado Watch 217|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/2011/ww0217_warnings.gif|date=April 26, 2011|accessdate=July 13, 2013|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Particularly Dangerous Situation (PDS) Tornado Watch 222|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/2011/ww0222_warnings.gif|date=April 26, 2011|accessdate=July 13, 2013|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref>\n\nAn upper-level negatively-tilted trough with two embedded shortwaves generated two surface lows that propagated generally east. One of the surface lows tracked northeast along the [[Mississippi River]] into [[Wisconsin]] as it occluded. Tornado watches were issued for the Lower Great Lakes during the afternoon hours as supercell thunderstorms developed along the warm front lifting north across central [[Michigan]]. Two tornadoes touched down in Michigan and caused damage to farm structures. Further east, severe thunderstorms caused scattered wind damage and large hail across Pennsylvania and New York. Two-inch-diameter hail was reported in [[Lock Haven, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"Storm Reports April 26\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/110426_rpts.html|title=20110426's Storm Report (1200 UTC \u2013 1159 UTC)|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref> An isolated supercell moved across Central New York throughout much of the afternoon, producing golf ball-sized hail in [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]] and spawning a very brief EF1 tornado in [[Verona Mills, New York|Verona Mills]], which primarily caused damage to trees. Another tornado \u2014 this one being in [[Gilbertsville, New York|Gilbertsville]] \u2014 caused significant damage to a school's athletic field.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tornado confirmed near Gilbertsville in Otsego County|url=http://www.erh.noaa.gov/bgm/WeatherEvents/Severe/april25-282011/ef1_gilbertsville.shtml|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Binghamton, New York|accessdate=January 22, 2011|date=April 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe second surface low corresponded to an area of strong upper level divergence ahead of the downstream shortwave. As the low formed across Texas and deepened while moving east, a tightening pressure gradient force further strengthened the low-level jet, therefore creating a broad warm sector across the southeastern states. This also generated stronger wind shear, providing better organization for the supercell storms as a result. Numerous tornadoes touched down across several states, including Texas, Louisiana, Arkansas. Most of those tornadoes were weak, but a few of them caused considerable damage. A long-tracked wedge tornado caused EF2 damage in rural portions of Texas and Louisiana.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Tornado Outbreak of April 25\u201327, 2011 |url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/shv/events/select.php?date=04262011_1 |publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |work=National Weather Service in Shreveport, Louisiana |accessdate=July 11, 2011 |date=April 26, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303205221/http://www.srh.noaa.gov/shv/events/select.php?date=04262011_1 |archivedate=March 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> An EF3 tornado destroyed structures and caused severe damage at [[Fort Campbell, Kentucky]] as well.<ref>{{cite web|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=290471|publisher=[[National Climatic Data Center]]|accessdate=May 9, 2011|year=2011}}</ref> A total of 55 tornadoes were confirmed the 26th, although no fatalities occurred.\n\n===April 27===\nSignificant severe weather was ongoing early on April 27 (in the overnight hours) and continued for the entire calendar day virtually unbroken. For the second day in a row, the SPC issued a high risk of severe weather for the Southern United States. Later that morning, the SPC even increased the probability for tornadoes to 45 percent along a corridor from [[Meridian, Mississippi]], to [[Huntsville, Alabama]], an extremely rare issuance exceeding the high risk standards. Conditions became increasingly favorable for tornadoes during such an extreme tornado outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2011/day1otlk_20110427_1630.html |title=April 27, 2011 1630 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|work=Storm Prediction Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=April 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Morning squall lines====\nDuring the early morning hours, a cold front with several embedded low pressure areas extended from east [[Texas]] northeastward into the [[Ohio River Valley]]. An upper-level disturbance that had moved across the frontal boundary the previous evening sparked an area of thunderstorms that morphed into a [[squall line]]. This line of severe thunderstorms would produce tornadic activity from the evening on April 26 into the late morning of April 27. Early in the morning the squall line, packing straight-line winds and numerous embedded tornadoes, moved through [[Louisiana]] and [[Mississippi]] before proceeding to affect [[North Alabama|North]] and [[Central Alabama]] and parts of [[Middle Tennessee|Middle]] and [[East Tennessee]]. The line strengthened as it moved through [[Alabama]], partially due to a high amount of low-level moisture from the [[Gulf of Mexico]] and increasing [[wind shear]].\n\nA majority of the tornadoes embedded in this initial squall line were weak, though several were strong and as such caused significant damage. An EF3 tornado caused major damage to homes in [[Coaling, Alabama]], an EF2 and an EF3 tornado produced severe damage and a fatality near [[Eupora, Mississippi]]. Another EF3 tornado resulted in heavy damage in downtown [[Cordova, Alabama]], which was struck by a violent EF4 tornado later that afternoon. One embedded cell that began in [[Cullman County, Alabama]] produced a long-tracked EF2 tornado that struck the town of [[Hanceville, Alabama|Hanceville]], killing one person. That cell would then produce over ten tornadoes (most rated EF1) to the northeast in [[Marshall County, Alabama|Marshall County]] and another EF1 tornado in [[Dade County, Georgia]]. The initial storms caused widespread [[power line|power]] and [[telephone line]] outages across Alabama and Tennessee. This line of storms also caused some [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|NOAA]] [[NOAA Weather Radio|weather radio]] transmitter sites to stop functioning for the remainder of the outbreak. Because of this, more than one million customers were without power and had no warning of any approaching tornadoes later that day.<ref name=\"April 27 Conditions HUN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=hunsur2011-04-27_setup|title=April 27th 2011 Severe Weather Setup|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nFrom the late morning to the early afternoon, another squall line moved through northern parts of Mississippi and Alabama as high wind shear and low-level moisture persisted. However, this time several discrete [[supercell]]s developed along and in front of the line, spawning seven weak tornadoes across [[Morgan County, Alabama|Morgan]], [[Limestone County, Alabama|Limestone]], and [[Madison County, Alabama|Madison]] Counties in northern Alabama around noon that day.<ref name=\"April 27 Conditions HUN\"/>\n\n====Afternoon supercells====\n[[File:Philadelphia, MS ground scouring.jpg|thumb|Extremely deep ground scouring near [[Philadelphia, Mississippi]] caused by a fast-moving EF5 tornado that killed three people.]]\nThe most intense supercells of the outbreak developed around midday in central Mississippi and began tracking eastward. During the early afternoon, as wind shear and low-level moisture continued to dramatically increase, a [[tornado emergency]] was declared for [[Neshoba County, Mississippi]], as a large tornado was reported on the ground by both storm spotters and a camera atop a television tower from [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] affiliate [[WTOK-TV]] (channel 11) in [[Meridian, Mississippi]]. This powerful EF5 tornado caused incredible damage northeast of [[Philadelphia, Mississippi]], where pavement was torn off from roads, vehicles were thrown, and the ground was scoured out to a depth of {{convert|2|ft|m}} by the tornado. Three people died when a mobile home was thrown {{convert|300|yd|m|}} into a wooded area, obliterating it in the process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/jan/?n=2011_04_25_27_neshoba_kemper_winston_noxubee|title=Neshoba/Kemper/Winston/Noxubee Counties Tornado|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Jackson, Mississippi|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=September 8, 2011}}</ref> Another very long-tracked EF4 tornado passed near the town of [[Enterprise, Clarke County, Mississippi|Enterprise, Mississippi]], killing seven people before crossing into Alabama and eventually dissipating. Responding to the high risk issued by the SPC and the already unstable atmosphere expected to become even more unstable throughout the afternoon hours, a [[Particularly Dangerous Situation|PDS]] [[tornado watch]] was issued at 1:45&nbsp;p.m. CDT (1845 UTC) for much of Alabama and portions of Mississippi, Tennessee, and Georgia. A widespread complex of supercell storms overspread the states of Mississippi and Alabama and violent tornadoes began rapidly touching down as the evening progressed.<ref name=\"April 27 Conditions HUN\"/> Four tornadoes were officially rated EF5 on the [[Enhanced Fujita scale]] that day. One of those EF5 tornadoes struck the town of [[Smithville, Mississippi]], where many well-built brick homes were reduced to bare slabs, numerous hardwood trees were completely debarked, and an SUV was hurled half a mile into the top of the town's water tower, subsequently leaving behind a visible dent. Another long-tracked EF5 wedge tornado passed through rural portions of Alabama and Tennessee, becoming the deadliest tornado of the outbreak as it completely devastated the towns of [[Hackleburg, Alabama|Hackleburg]], [[Phil Campbell, Alabama|Phil Campbell]], [[Mount Hope, Lawrence County, Alabama|Mount Hope]], [[Tanner, Alabama|Tanner]], and [[Harvest, Alabama|Harvest]], killing 72 people. This marks only the second day in history (after [[1974 Super Outbreak|April 3, 1974]]) that there were more than two F5/EF5 tornadoes reported.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/faq/tornado/f5torns.html|title=F5 and EF5 Tornadoes of the United States|work=Storm Prediction Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe tornadoes continued tracking through central Alabama that afternoon and into the early evening hours. A dangerous and destructive tornado struck the city of [[Cullman, Alabama]] at around 3:00&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2000 UTC). This large, multiple-vortex tornado was captured on several tower cameras from [[television station]]s, such as [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] affiliate [[WBRC]] (channel 6) and ABC affiliate [[WBMA-LD]]/[[WSES|WCFT-TV]]/[[WGWW|WJSU-TV]] (channels 58, 33, and 40) both out of [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]]. The tornado caused extensive destruction in the city's downtown area; it was ultimately rated EF4. The final damage count was 867 residences and 94 businesses in Cullman, and six people died.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=4272011_cullman_county|title=National Weather Service Huntsville, AL \u2013 Cullman County Survey Information|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=October 2, 2011|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref> The town of [[Cordova, Alabama]], which had already been damaged by an EF3 tornado from the initial round of storms, was struck by an EF4 tornado that killed 13 people. Two violent EF4 tornadoes also ripped through [[Jackson County, Alabama]], one of which caused a fatality near [[Bridgeport, Alabama|Bridgeport]] while the other passed near [[Pisgah, Alabama|Pisgah]] and into Georgia where it caused major damage in [[Trenton, Georgia|Trenton]] and killed 14 people. At around 5:10&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2210 UTC), a very large and exceptionally destructive tornado struck [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama]] and about 40 minutes later, that same tornado struck the northern suburbs of nearby Birmingham.<ref name=\"massive\"/> A tornado emergency was issued for both cities, along with many other cities that day. Many local television stations, including WBRC and WBMA-LD/WCFT/WJSU, as well as [[CBS]] affiliate [[WIAT]] (channel 42), broadcast live footage of this long-tracked tornado in both Tuscaloosa and Birmingham. A debris ball was observed by the Birmingham [[NEXRAD]], indicating that the tornado was causing extreme damage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://supercellweather.com/Debris%20Ball2.png |title=Birmingham Radar |publisher=Supercell Weather.com |date=April 27, 2011 |accessdate=December 1, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120819115842/http://supercellweather.com/Debris%20Ball2.png |archivedate=August 19, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref> This tornado killed 64 people and caused extensive devastation in densely populated areas, and the tornado struck several of the same small communities as the [[April 1956 Birmingham tornado|April 1956 F4]], the [[April 1977 Birmingham tornado|April 1977 F5]] and the [[April 1998 Birmingham tornado|April 1998 F5 tornadoes]] that hit portions of the Birmingham area. The supercell that produced the Tuscaloosa/Birmingham EF4 tornado originated in [[Newton County, Mississippi]]. The supercell also produced an EF4 tornado later that evening that killed 22 people and struck the [[Ohatchee, Alabama]] area and eventually crossed into Georgia, causing additional damage near [[Cave Spring, Georgia|Cave Spring]] before dissipating. Further to the south, a mile-wide EF3 tornado killed 7 people in mostly rural areas and caused major damage in the small town of [[Eoline, Alabama|Eoline]]. The final EF5 tornado of the day caused remarkable damage in and around the town of [[Rainsville, Alabama]], killing 25 people before crossing into Georgia and dissipating. Tornadoes continued touching down further to the northeast as the sun set, particularly in Georgia. This included a long-tracked EF4 tornado that caused major damage in [[Ringgold, Georgia]], [[Apison, Tennessee]], and [[Cleveland, Tennessee]], killing 20 people along the path. After dark, violent tornadoes continued to touch down, and a nighttime EF4 tornado destroyed many lakeside homes at [[Lake Martin]] in eastern Alabama, killing seven people. Additional strong nighttime tornadoes occurred in Georgia, including an EF3 that killed two people in [[Barnesville, Georgia|Barnesville]], and another EF3 that destroyed homes and killed one person at [[Lake Burton (Georgia)|Lake Burton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jayzeetee.wordpress.com/2011/06/20/supercell-tracks-on-april-27th-2011/|title=Supercell Tracks on April 27th, 2011|publisher=jayzeetee.wordpress.com|date=June 20, 2011|accessdate=December 1, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"2011-super-outbreak\">{{cite web |title=Historic Outbreak of April 27, 2011 |url=https://www.weather.gov/bmx/event_04272011 |website=NWS Birmingham |publisher=National Weather Service |accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Continued activity farther east====\nPowerful tornadoes touched down across [[Tennessee]] as well that evening. A violent EF4 struck the community of [[New Harmony, Tennessee]], where homes were leveled, vehicles were tossed, and four people were killed.<ref>{{cite web|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=300460|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref> Two EF3 tornadoes crossed paths in [[Greene County, Tennessee|Greene]] and [[Washington County, Tennessee|Washington]] counties (coming a couple hours apart), resulting in eight fatalities. The rural communities of [[Horse Creek, Tennessee|Horse Creek]] and [[Camp Creek, Tennessee|Camp Creek]] suffered major damage from those tornadoes late that evening.<ref>{{cite web|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/listevents.jsp?beginDate_mm=04&beginDate_dd=27&beginDate_yyyy=2011&endDate_mm=04&endDate_dd=27&endDate_yyyy=2011&eventType=Tornado&county=GREENE&zone=NONE&submitbutton=Search&statefips=47%2CTENNESSEE|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=305738|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref> A very large EF4 wedge tornado leveled a mile-wide swath of forest through {{convert|14|mi|km}} of [[Great Smoky Mountains National Park]].<ref>{{cite web|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=300456|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref> At [[Chilhowee Dam|Chilhowee Lake]], large metal power line truss towers were torn and thrown from their concrete supports that they were anchored to.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/mrx/?n=blountsmokiesef3|title=Blount County Smoky Mountains EF4 Tornado Track and Photos |publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Morristown, Tennessee|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=January 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nA secondary area of severe weather also developed that afternoon and evening along a corridor extending from central and northern [[Virginia]] northward through [[Maryland]], [[Pennsylvania]], and [[New York (state)|New York]], continuing into early April 28. Many tornadoes touched down in this area as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.erh.noaa.gov/bgm/WeatherEvents/Severe/april25-282011/ef1_campbell.shtml |title=EF1 Tornado confirmed near Campbell in Steuben County New York|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Binghamton, New York|date=May 5, 2011|accessdate=December 1, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.erh.noaa.gov/ctp/features/2011/04_2728/index.php|title=Severe Weather of April 27th and 28th, 2011|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in State College, Pennsylvania|date=June 17, 2011|accessdate=December 1, 2012}}</ref> Most of these tornadoes were weak, though an EF2 tornado touched down near the town of [[Halifax, Virginia]], and caused severe damage to homes in the area, resulting in one death.<ref>{{cite web|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=303871|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref> Tornado alerts were issued for [[Southern Ontario]] as far north as [[Ottawa]] as well; one tornado was later confirmed in [[Fergus, Ontario]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guelphmercury.com/news/local/article/529400--environment-canada-confirms-tornado-hit-fergus-area-on-april-27|title=Environment Canada confirms tornado hit Fergus area on April 27|publisher=[[Guelph Mercury]]|date=May 9, 2011|accessdate=December 1, 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:April 27, 2011 severe weather warnings.JPG|thumb|left|Map of all tornado (red), severe thunderstorm (yellow), and flood (green) warnings issued on April 27.]]\n\n====Overview====\nA statewide review by emergency management officials recorded 249 fatalities in Alabama, 23 of which were not tornado-related.<ref name=\"alemapressrelease1\"/> Damage and power outages in the [[Huntsville, Alabama|Huntsville]] area were so widespread that at one point over 650,000 people were out of power in the [[Tennessee Valley Authority]] system. The EF5 tornado that struck Hackleburg and Phil Campbell eventually damaged main power lines coming from [[Browns Ferry Nuclear Plant]] further to the northeast. These towers were the main supply of electrical power to much of North Alabama and some were without power for two weeks. The tornado just missed the Limestone Correctional Facility, which less than a year later would be struck by another tornado.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weather.gov/ffc/20110427_svrstorms|title=Tornado Tracks: April 24th through the 29th, 2011|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Peachtree City, Georgia|date=May 10, 2011|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Storm Prediction Center received 292 reports of tornadoes in the preceding 24 hours.<ref name=\"Storm Reports April 27\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/110427_rpts.html|title=20110427's Storm Reports (1200 UTC \u2013 1159 UTC)|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=April 29, 2011}}</ref> It broke the record for the most tornado touchdowns in 24 hours with 219 in the United States from midnight to midnight CDT (0500 \u2013 0500 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]) breaking the 24-hour record of 147 (in both totals, excluding confirmed tornadoes outside the United States that were part of the outbreak) set by the [[1974 Super Outbreak]]. Of those 219 tornadoes, 59 touched down in Alabama and 79 hit the ground in Tennessee, accounting for well over half of the tornadoes that touched down on April 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/05/02/2011-tornadoes-record-most-in-day_n_856542.html |title=April 2011 Tornadoes Break Record For Most Twisters Ever In A Day |publisher=[[The Huffington Post|Huffington Post]] |date=May 2, 2011 |accessdate=December 1, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006024251/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/05/02/2011-tornadoes-record-most-in-day_n_856542.html |archivedate=October 6, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref> On April 27 alone, the National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama issued 92 tornado warnings, 31 [[severe thunderstorm warning]]s, and seven [[flash flood warning]]s.<ref name=\"SWDJW-04272011-WarningSummaries\">{{cite web|url=http://www.weather.gov/hun/hunsur_2011-04-27_statistics|title=Severe Thunderstorm and Tornado Warning Overview|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=April 25, 2012|accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===April 28===\nTornado watches were issued for the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] coast from [[Pennsylvania]] to [[Florida]] at the start of the day and continued through the morning and early afternoon, but tornadoes were forecasted to generally be weaker and more isolated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2011/day1otlk_20110428_1200.html|title=April 28, 2011 0600 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=April 29, 2011}}</ref> Despite this, the secondary portion of the outbreak that had begun producing scattered tornadoes throughout the [[Mid-Atlantic states|Mid-Atlantic]] and [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]] regions the previous evening intensified during the early hours of the morning, producing numerous tornadoes. A particularly active region, in which there were some strong tornadoes,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/capital-weather-gang/post/april-27-2011-tornado-outbreak-numerous-tornadic-storms-impacted-the-dc-region-as-well/2011/04/28/AFU3DlDF_blog.html|title=April 27-28, 2011 tornado outbreak: Numerous tornadic storms impacted the D.C. region as well|author=Ian Livingston|work=Washington Post|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> was the [[Interstate 81]] corridor extending from southwest [[Virginia]],<ref name=\"washingtonpost1\">{{cite news|author1=Justin Jouvenal|author2=Michael E. Ruane|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/funnel-clouds-reported-throughout-region/2011/04/27/AFZoy01E_story.html|title=Funnel clouds reported across area; 5 killed in southwest Va.|work=[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref>  northward through the [[Shenandoah Valley]]<ref>http://www.whsv.com/content/news/NWS-report-from-the-April-28th-2011-local-tornado-outbreak-481098871.html</ref> and into [[Pennsylvania]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wgal.com/Day-Of-Twisters-NWS-Confirms-4-Tornadoes-On-Thursday/-/9361174/6647180/-/v15p5sz/-/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231001841/http://www.wgal.com/Day-Of-Twisters-NWS-Confirms-4-Tornadoes-On-Thursday/-/9361174/6647180/-/v15p5sz/-/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 31, 2013|title=Day Of Twisters \u2013 NWS Confirms 4 Tornadoes On Thursday|publisher=[[WGAL]]|date=April 30, 2011|accessdate=July 13, 2013}}</ref> and [[New York (state)|New York]]. This included the deadly EF3 tornado that struck the town of [[Glade Spring, Virginia]] very early in the morning, where three people died.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=298380|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=December 1, 2012}}</ref> Tornadoes were also reported in [[Florida]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wltx.com/news/article/134507/2/Midlands-Wakes-Up-to-Rain-Lightning-Hail-|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120527084926/http://www.wltx.com/news/article/134507/2/Midlands-Wakes-Up-to-Rain-Lightning-Hail-|url-status=dead|archive-date=May 27, 2012|title=Midlands Wakes Up to Rain, Lightning, Hail|publisher=[[WLTX]]|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=April 29, 2011}}</ref> [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[South Carolina]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wistv.com/Global/story.asp?S=14528993|title=NWS confirms tornado touchdowns in Calhoun, Sumter counties \u2013 WIS News 10 \u2013 Columbia, South Carolina &#124;|publisher=[[WIS (TV)|WIS-TV]]|date=April 25, 2011|accessdate=April 29, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430073051/http://www.wistv.com/Global/story.asp?S=14528993|archive-date=April 30, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[North Carolina]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wral.com/weather/story/9511896|title=Storms leave isolated damage|publisher=[[WRAL-TV|WRAL]]|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=April 29, 2011}}</ref> and [[Maryland]].  Most of these tornadoes were weak. Although tornado watches were issued, no tornadoes were spotted in [[New Jersey]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/04/nj_tornado_warnings_expire.html|title=Storms bring heavy downpour to N.J. but no damage|publisher=[[New Jersey On-Line|NJ.com]]|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=April 29, 2011}}</ref> or [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"washingtonpost1\"/> In the wake of the tornadoes and severe thunderstorms, widespread flooding hit the Midwest, South, and Eastern Seaboard, with extensive flood and flash flood warnings issued.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.intellicast.com/Storm/Severe/WatchesWarnings.aspx|title=Watches & Warnings in United States|publisher=Intellicast|accessdate=April 29, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522071222/http://www.intellicast.com/Storm/Severe/WatchesWarnings.aspx|archivedate= May 22, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> The last tornadoes of the outbreak touched down that afternoon in eastern [[North Carolina]], which was hard hit in the [[Tornado outbreak of April 14\u201316, 2011|April 16 outbreak]], though the tornadoes that impacted the area this time around were weak.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=292059|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref> The system moved out into the [[Atlantic Ocean]] that evening, with the exception of isolated thunderstorms over central Florida that night into April 29, although there were no tornadoes then.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/2011/md0668.html|title=Mesoscale Discussion 668|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notable tornadoes==\n{{see also|List of tornadoes in the 2011 Super Outbreak}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n|+ Daily statistics<ref>{{cite report|title=April 2011 Storm Data|url=http://www1.ncdc.noaa.gov/pub/orders/IPS/IPS-365AE391-42D1-432E-86E8-60949C642469.pdf|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=[[National Climatic Data Center]]|year=2011|accessdate=May 21, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Pgz1a6Xa?url=http://www1.ncdc.noaa.gov/pub/orders/IPS/IPS-365AE391-42D1-432E-86E8-60949C642469.pdf|archivedate=May 19, 2014}}</ref>\n|- \n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|Total\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|&nbsp;EF0&nbsp; \n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|&nbsp;EF1&nbsp;\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|&nbsp;EF2&nbsp;\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|&nbsp;EF3&nbsp;\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|&nbsp;EF4&nbsp;\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|&nbsp;EF5&nbsp;\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|Deaths\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|Injuries\n|-\n|April&nbsp;25\n|align=\"right\"|42\n|align=\"right\"|17\n|align=\"right\"|20\n|align=\"right\"|4\n|align=\"right\"|1\n|align=\"right\"|0\n|align=\"right\"|0\n|align=\"right\"|5\n|align=\"right\"|59\n|-\n|April&nbsp;26\n|align=\"right\"|55\n|align=\"right\"|31\n|align=\"right\"|19\n|align=\"right\"|4\n|align=\"right\"|1\n|align=\"right\"|0\n|align=\"right\"|0\n|align=\"right\"|0\n|align=\"right\"|4\n|-\n|April&nbsp;27\n|align=\"right\"|216\n|align=\"right\"|68*\n|align=\"right\"|78\n|align=\"right\"|36\n|align=\"right\"|19\n|align=\"right\"|11\n|align=\"right\"|4\n|align=\"right\"|316\n|align=\"right\"|2,986+\n|-\n|April&nbsp;28\n|align=\"right\"|47\n|align=\"right\"|18\n|align=\"right\"|23\n|align=\"right\"|5\n|align=\"right\"|1\n|align=\"right\"|0\n|align=\"right\"|0\n|align=\"right\"|3\n|align=\"right\"|51\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"'''\n\n| Total\n\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=#{{storm colour|unk}}  |'''360\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=#{{storm colour|storm}}|'''134'''*\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat1}} |'''140'''\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat2}} |'''49'''\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat3}} |'''22'''\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat4}} |'''11'''\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat5}} |'''4'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''324'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''3,100+'''\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> One tornado touched down in [[Ontario, Canada]], on April 27 and was rated as an [[Fujita scale|F0]]. It is counted as an EF0 in this table.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0 0 0.5em 1em;float:right;\"\n|+ Outbreak death toll\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| State/Province\n! scope=\"col\"| Fatalities\n|-\n|[[Alabama]]\n|238\n|-\n|[[Arkansas]]\n|5\n|-\n|[[Georgia (U.S. State)|Georgia]]\n|14\n|-\n|[[Mississippi]]\n|31\n|-\n|[[Tennessee]]\n|32\n|-\n|[[Virginia]]\n|4\n|- style=\"background:#e6e9ff;\" \n||'''Totals'''\n||'''324'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{small|Only tornado-related deaths are included<br />(24 deaths were not caused by tornadoes)}}\n|}\n\n===Vilonia, Arkansas===\n[[File:Vilonia2011.jpg|thumb|left|255px|Remains of a mobile home that was destroyed by the Vilonia tornado.]] \n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF2\n| total fatalities = 4 fatalities, 16 injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nThe first tornado of the outbreak to cause more than one death was a long-tracked, high-end EF2 wedge tornado that struck the small town of [[Vilonia, Arkansas|Vilonia]] in [[Faulkner County, Arkansas]], around 7:30&nbsp;p.m. [[Central Time Zone|CDT]] (00:30 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]) on April 25.<ref name=\"NWSLittleRockApril27\">{{cite web|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Little Rock, Arkansas|date=June 7, 2011|accessdate=December 2, 2012|title=Heavy Rain/Severe Weather on April 23\u201327, 2011|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/lzk/?n=rain0411yr.htm}}</ref> A [[tornado warning]] was issued for the area roughly 30 minutes prior to the tornado's arrival, and the relatively low loss of life was attributed to this lead time.<ref name=\"TheCabin426\">{{cite web|author=Linda Hicks|publisher=[[Log Cabin Democrat]]|date=April 26, 2011|accessdate=April 27, 2011|title=Vilonia firefighter keep busy in cleanup efforts after storm|url=http://thecabin.net/news/local/2011-04-26/vilonia-firefighter-keep-busy-cleanup-efforts-after-storm}}</ref> A [[tornado emergency]] was declared at 7:24&nbsp;p.m. CDT (00:24 UTC) for the city shortly before the tornado struck.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Little Rock, Arkansas|date=April 25, 2011|accessdate=April 27, 2011|title=Tornado Emergency for Vilonia, Arkansas|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/vtec/#2011-O-NEW-KLZK-TO-W-0102|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110419050352/http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/vtec/|archivedate=April 19, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> Four people were killed in the town and many more were injured. The tornado touched down northwest of [[Ferndale, Arkansas|Ferndale]] in [[Pulaski County, Arkansas|Pulaski County]] at 6:48&nbsp;p.m. CDT (23:48 UTC), downing trees and transmission towers at EF1 intensity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=289605|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> It continued northeast of [[Natural Steps, Arkansas|Natural Steps]], severely damaging a small church and downing numerous trees, one of which landed on a house.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=289609|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> The tornado continued to knock down trees as it passed near [[Roland, Arkansas|Roland]], several of which landed on homes. The tornado reached EF2 strength as it crossed into Faulkner County and passed southeast of [[Mayflower, Arkansas|Mayflower]], downing numerous trees and power lines and damaging homes and outbuildings. Past Mayflower, it continued towards Vilonia and struck a mobile home park, where numerous mobile homes were destroyed and the four fatalities occurred. Two of the fatalities occurred when a couple attempted to take shelter in a cargo container, which was thrown {{convert|150|yd|m|}} and deposited near a pond. Several other people were injured in this area as well. The tornado maintained EF2 intensity as it moved directly through Vilonia, damaging numerous homes and businesses and flipping several semi-trucks. The [[American Red Cross]] indicated that approximately 34 site-built houses and 62 mobile homes were destroyed, 91 site-built homes and 41 mobile homes suffered major damage, 145 site-built houses and 43 mobile homes had minor damage, and 53 site-built houses and 38 mobile homes were affected in some other way in the Vilonia area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=289645|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> One of the mobile homes was picked up and flipped, and the home's two bathtubs were found over a hill about {{convert|40|yd|m|}} away. The lone occupant of the mobile home sustained major injuries.<ref>{{cite web|author=Linda Hicks|publisher=[[Arkansas Democrat-Gazette|ArkansasOnline]]|date=May 22, 2014|accessdate=June 20, 2014|title=Vilonia couple continue to recover from 2011 tornado|url=http://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2014/may/22/vilonia-couple-continue-recover-2011-tornado/}}</ref> After moving through Vilonia, the tornado weakened to EF1 strength as it moved into [[White County, Arkansas|White County]] and passed west of [[El Paso, Arkansas|El Paso]], where trees were blown over onto houses (damaging several roofs), barns and outbuildings were destroyed, an [[Recreational vehicle|RV]] and the trailer portion of a tractor-trailer were overturned, and hundreds of trees were downed. The tornado finally dissipated north of [[Joy, Arkansas|Joy]] at 7:59&nbsp;p.m. CDT (00:59 UTC), after having travelled just over {{convert|51|mi|km|}}. At its widest point, the tornado was {{convert|1.64|mi|km|}} wide.<ref name=\"TheCabin426\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=289615|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> Following the tornado, 85 members of the [[National Guard of the United States|U.S. National Guard]] were deployed to assist in search and rescue, debris clearing, security and traffic control.<ref>{{cite web|author=Lindsey Tugman |publisher=[[KTHV]] |date=April 26, 2011 |accessdate=April 27, 2011 |title=120 Guardsmen called to assist in Vilonia, Hot Springs Village |url=http://www.todaysthv.com/news/article/154941/2/120-Guardsmen-called-to-assist-in-Vilonia-Hot-Springs-Village |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429052340/http://www.todaysthv.com/news/article/154941/2/120-Guardsmen-called-to-assist-in-Vilonia-Hot-Springs-Village |archivedate=April 29, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nOn April 27, 2014, three years and two days after this tornado, [[April 27\u201330, 2014 tornado outbreak|a violent EF4 tornado]] touched down west of Ferndale and moved along almost the same path as this tornado, causing 16 fatalities and many injuries. However, it affected more of Mayflower than this tornado did and caused greater damage all along the path, especially in Vilonia, before lifting near El Paso.<ref name=\"NWSLittleRockApril27Vilonia\">{{cite web|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |work=National Weather Service in Little Rock, Arkansas |date=May 29, 2014 |accessdate=June 20, 2014 |title=Tornadoes/Flooding on April 27-28, 2014 |url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/lzk/?n=svr0414c.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502002121/http://www.srh.noaa.gov/lzk/?n=svr0414c.htm |archivedate=May 2, 2014 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Philadelphia\u2013Kemper County, Mississippi===\n{{Main|2011 Philadelphia, Mississippi tornado}}\n{{Infobox storm \n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF5\n| total fatalities = 3 fatalities, 8+ injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\n[[File:April 27, 2011 Mississippi tornado damage.jpg|thumb|right|A car that was thrown against a stand of trees by the Philadelphia tornado.]]\nThe first EF5 tornado of the outbreak touched down near the city of [[Philadelphia, Mississippi]], on April 27. The tornado touched down at 2:30&nbsp;p.m. CDT (19:30 UTC) and traveled for nearly {{convert|29|mi|km|}} through [[Neshoba County, Mississippi|Neshoba]], [[Kemper County, Mississippi|Kemper]], [[Winston County, Mississippi|Winston]], and [[Noxubee County, Mississippi|Noxubee Counties]], reaching a maximum width of a {{convert|1/2|mi|km|adj=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/mrx/?n=tor_outbreak_map|title=One Storm Amongst Many|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Morristown, Tennessee|date=April 27, 2012|accessdate=December 2, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Philadelphia, MS EF5 Survey\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/jan/?n=2011_04_25_27_neshoba_kemper_winston_noxubee|title=Neshoba/Kemper/Winston/Noxubee Counties Tornado|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Jackson, Mississippi|date=September 8, 2011|accessdate=December 2, 2012}}</ref> The tornado killed three people, injured eight others, and caused $1.1&nbsp;million in damage across its path.<ref name=\"Philadelphia, MS EF5 Survey\"/><ref>{{cite report|work=[[National Weather Service]] Office in Jackson, Mississippi|publisher=[[National Centers for Environmental Information]]|year=2011|accessdate=May 14, 2016|title=Mississippi Event Report: EF5 Tornado|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=309257}}\n*{{cite report|work=[[National Weather Service]] Office in Jackson, Mississippi|publisher=[[National Centers for Environmental Information]]|year=2011|accessdate=May 14, 2016|title=Mississippi Event Report: EF5 Tornado|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=309261}}\n*{{cite report|work=[[National Weather Service]] Office in Jackson, Mississippi|publisher=[[National Centers for Environmental Information]]|year=2011|accessdate=May 14, 2016|title=Mississippi Event Report: EF5 Tornado|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=309265}}\n*{{cite report|work=[[National Weather Service]] Office in Jackson, Mississippi|publisher=[[National Centers for Environmental Information]]|year=2011|accessdate=May 14, 2016|title=Mississippi Event Report: EF3 Tornado|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=309267}}</ref>\n\nThe supercell thunderstorm that produced this tornado formed around 1:00&nbsp;p.m. CDT south of [[Jackson, Mississippi]].<ref name=\"PhiladelphiaEF5_1\">{{cite report|author1=Eric Carpenter |author2=Greg Garrett |author3=Jared Allen |publisher=[[National Weather Service]] Office in Jackson, Mississippi |date=February 29, 2012 |accessdate=May 14, 2016 |title=A Storm-scale and Damage Survey Analysis of the East-Central Mississippi Violent Tornado of 27 April 2011 |url=http://www.nwas.org/committees/professionaldevelopment/NWAPD-2012-029_Carpenter_et_al.pdf |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130320054100/http://www.nwas.org/committees/professionaldevelopment/NWAPD-2012-029_Carpenter_et_al.pdf |archivedate=March 20, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Traveling briskly to the northeast, it warranted a severe thunderstorm warning within 25 minutes and was deemed potentially tornadic by 1:36&nbsp;p.m. CDT.<ref name=\"PhiladelphiaEF5_1\"/><ref>{{cite report|work=[[National Weather Service]] Office in Jackson, Mississippi|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet National Weather Service|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=May 14, 2016|title=Tornado Warning|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/vtec/#2011-O-NEW-KJAN-TO-W-0140/USCOMP-N0Q-201104271840}}</ref> A tornado finally touched down at 2:30&nbsp;p.m. CDT just east of the [[Philadelphia Municipal Airport]]. It quickly intensified and began producing EF5 damage by 2:38&nbsp;p.m. CDT; extreme ground scouring, up to {{convert|2|ft|m|}} deep in places, occurred in northeastern Neshoba County. After crossing into Kemper County, the tornado obliterated a mobile home, killing all three inside.<ref name=\"Philadelphia, MS EF5 Survey\"/> It reached EF5 strength a second time near the Kemper\u2013Winston county line where extreme ground scouring again took place and pavement was scoured.<ref name=\"Philadelphia, MS EF5 Survey\"/><ref name=\"PhiladelphiaEF5_1\"/> Extreme tree damage took place along the track and it ultimately dissipated at 3:00&nbsp;p.m. CDT about {{convert|6|mi|km|}} north of [[Mashulaville, Mississippi|Mashulaville]].<ref name=\"Philadelphia, MS EF5 Survey\"/>\n\nThis was the first tornado to cause F5/EF5 damage in [[Mississippi]] since the [[Candlestick Park tornado]] on March 3, 1966. Additionally, the formation of the [[Smithville, Mississippi|Smithville]] tornado later that day marked the first time since statistics have been kept that two EF5 tornadoes have been recorded in Mississippi on the same day. Prior to this, the last confirmed EF5 tornado was the [[Parkersburg Tornado|Parkersburg, Iowa tornado]] on May 25, 2008.<ref name=\"Philadelphia, MS EF5 Survey\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Cullman/Arab, Alabama===\n[[File:Cullman Alabama First Methodist Church Damage.jpg|thumb|left|255px|Damage to the First Methodist Church in downtown [[Cullman, Alabama]].]]\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF4\n| total fatalities = 6 fatalities, 48+ injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nRated EF4, this highly visible multiple-vortex tornado tracked directly through downtown Cullman.<ref name=\"Long Track Tornado Hits Cullman, Alabama\">{{cite news|url=http://okcstormwatcher.wordpress.com/2011/04/27/tornado-emergency-for-cullman-alabama/|publisher=OKC Storm Watcher|title=Long Track Tornado Hits Cullman, Alabama (4/27/2011)|accessdate=April 30, 2011|date=April 30, 2011}}</ref> The tornado touched down at 2:40&nbsp;p.m. CDT (19:40 UTC) on April 27 and tracked a {{convert|47|mi|km|adj=on}} damage path through [[Cullman County, Alabama|Cullman]], [[Morgan County, Alabama|Morgan]], and [[Marshall County, Alabama|Marshall Counties]], causing six deaths.<ref name=\"April 27, 2011 Cullman, Alabama EF4 Tornado\">{{cite news|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=4272011_cullman_county|title=Cullman (AL)/Morgan (AL)/Marshall (AL) EF4 Tornado|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service Huntsville, Alabama|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=March 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Cullman tornado first touched down on the north side of [[Lewis Smith Lake]] and caused light structural damage near [[Crane Hill, Alabama|Crane Hill]] before intensifying and tracking directly towards Cullman, snapping numerous trees and heavily damaging several homes.\n\nThe tornado became violent as it entered Cullman, being tracked and broadcast live via several tower cameras, including one operated by [[WBMA-LD|''ABC 33/40'']] for several minutes; that camera captured the destruction of a communications tower belonging to Cullman area [[Low-power broadcasting|low-power]] television station [[WCQT-LP]] as the tornado ripped through the city. Radio stations in downtown Cullman also reported on the tornado and some even captured it passing over until power was knocked out.<ref name=\"Long Track Tornado Hits Cullman, Alabama\"/> Downtown Cullman was badly damaged by the tornado, with the major damage being along a two-block area through the center of the downtown business district. Numerous well-built brick buildings and storefronts in downtown Cullman were heavily damaged or completely destroyed, along with churches. The courthouse and nearby emergency management building took a direct hit from the tornado, sustaining considerable damage, and two school buildings were heavily damaged as well. Many well-known businesses, such as Vincent's Furniture, ''[[The Cullman Times]]'', and the Busy Bee Cafe, were also severely damaged/destroyed. Many homes were damaged or destroyed in residential areas of the city, with extensive tree and power line damage noted as well. In all, a total of 867 residences and 94 businesses within the city of Cullman were damaged or destroyed.<ref name=\"Long Track Tornado Hits Cullman, Alabama\"/>\n\n[[File:Cullman2011EF4.JPG|thumb|Major structural damage to businesses in downtown Cullman.]]\nThe tornado, more or less, followed [[U.S. Route 278|U.S. Highway 278]] through the city, in which it created extensive damage along many major intersections, including those with [[Interstate 65 in Alabama|Interstate 65]], [[U.S. Route 31 in Alabama|U.S. Highway 31]], and [[Alabama State Route 157|Alabama State Routes 157]] and [[Alabama State Route 69|69]].<ref name=\"April 27, 2011 Cullman, Alabama EF4 Tornado\"/>\n\nThe tornado continued northeast, becoming large and wedge-shaped. It then passed just north of [[Fairview, Alabama|Fairview]], completely destroying homes and debarking numerous hardwood trees. Pieces of debris were found speared through vehicles in this area.<ref name=\"April 27, 2011 Cullman, Alabama EF4 Tornado\"/> The tornado then briefly passed through a section of [[Morgan County, Alabama|Morgan County]] near the town of [[Hulaco, Alabama|Hulaco]], destroying several older block-foundation homes and snapping numerous large trees off at the base. The tornado then crossed into [[Marshall County, Alabama|Marshall County]] and impacted the rural community of [[Ruth, Alabama|Ruth]], just north of [[Arab, Alabama|Arab]]. A large but poorly-anchored brick home was swept completely away in this area, with the debris scattered 100 yards from the foundation. Several large trees on the property were ripped out of the ground and missing, along with a trailer that was unable to be located at the time of the survey. Other homes and structures were impacted in the Ruth area, and a gas station was completely destroyed. A shed was destroyed with pieces of large farm machinery stored inside thrown up to 20 yards away, a storage trailer was tossed 100 yards and found impaled by planks of wood, and steel power poles in the area were bent over. Arab's power grid was completely crippled by the tornado's effects, and many roads in the area were obstructed by downed trees and power lines. The tornado damaged and destroyed several other homes, garages, and sheds north of [[Union Grove, Alabama|Union Grove]] before it crossed the [[Tennessee River]], snapping numerous trees in a forested area before dissipating.<ref name=\"April 27, 2011 Cullman, Alabama EF4 Tornado\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Hackleburg\u2013Phil Campbell\u2013Tanner\u2013Harvest, Alabama/Huntland, Tennessee===\n{{Main|2011 Hackleburg\u2013Phil Campbell tornado}}\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF5\n| total fatalities = 72 fatalities, 145+ injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\n[[File:Phil Campbell tornado damage2.jpg|thumb|EF5 damage in Phil Campbell, with homes swept away and grass scoured from hillsides.]]\nThis devastating, long-tracked, violent EF5 wedge tornado was the deadliest of the outbreak. It first touched down in [[Marion County, Alabama]] about {{convert|5|mi|km}} west-southwest of [[Hamilton, Alabama|Hamilton]] around 3:00&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2100 UTC) on April 27, leaving massive damage along its track. The storm would eventually reach the [[Hackleburg, Alabama|Hackleburg]] area, completely leveling many homes and businesses, including a large [[Wrangler (Jeans)|Wrangler, Inc.]] factory. Most of the structures in downtown Hackleburg were badly damaged and Hackleburg High School was destroyed. Well-built homes were wiped cleanly from their foundations, extensive wind-rowing of debris occurred, trees were completely debarked, and cars were thrown hundreds of yards. According to the [[American Red Cross]], 75 percent of the town was destroyed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2011/05/03/135936478/in-small-towns-hit-by-twisters-you-feel-ignored|title=In Small Towns Hit By Twisters, 'You Feel Ignored'|work=[[NPR|National Public Radio]]|publisher=[[Corporation for Public Broadcasting]]|date=May 3, 2011|accessdate=May 25, 2011|author=Tayna Ott}}</ref> While initially rated as an EF3, the rating was increased to EF5 after further analysis of the damage, making it the first F5/EF5 tornado in Alabama since the [[April 1998 Birmingham tornado|Birmingham tornado of April 8, 1998]].<ref name=\"Marion survey\">{{cite web|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=201104302306|title=Updated For Increase In Hackleburg Tornado Rating To EF-5|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Birmingham, Alabama|date=April 30, 2011|accessdate=May 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Waff Tower Cam.jpg|thumb|left|Hackleburg/Phil Campbell EF5 tornado capture on [[WAFF (TV)|WAFF]]'s tower cam before it crossed [[US-72]] in [[Limestone County, Alabama]].]]\nSoon after crossing into [[Franklin County, Alabama|Franklin County]],  the town of [[Phil Campbell, Alabama|Phil Campbell]] experienced significant devastation of the same magnitude as Hackleburg. Numerous homes, some of which were well-constructed, were swept away as the tornado tore through town. At least three churches along the path sustained significant damage, with one church in the town being completely destroyed and having only the foundation slab remaining. Mobile homes throughout the path were completely destroyed, and their mangled frames were tossed at least {{convert|25|to|50|yd|m}}. Cars were tossed and destroyed throughout the path of the tornado, with one car wrapped around a debarked tree. A {{convert|25|ft|m|adj=on}} section of pavement was torn from a road in this area as well. The most intense damage along the path occurred northeast of Phil Campbell in the rural community of Oak Grove, where vehicles were carried long distances and mangled beyond recognition, large trees were completely debarked, and large brick homes with extensive anchoring were obliterated with the debris wind-rowed hundreds of yards away. The tornado continued into [[Lawrence County, Alabama|Lawrence County]], impacting the [[Mount Hope, Lawrence County, Alabama|Mount Hope]] community, where significant devastation was incurred to single-family homes and a restaurant. Nothing but the foundation and a pile of debris remained at the restaurant site, and a small portion of the restaurant's foundation slab buckled.<ref name=\"Huntsville EF5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=franklin-al_lawrence_limestone_madison_franklin-tn_counties|title=Franklin (AL) / Lawrence / Morgan / Limestone / Madison / Franklin (TN) EF-5|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=May 1, 2011|accessdate=May 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:PhilCampbellPavementScouring.JPG|thumb|left|255px|Large area of pavement scoured from a road in Phil Campbell.]]\nThe tornado moved northeast, producing EF3 damage in and around [[Langtown, Alabama|Langtown]]. The tornado re-intensified to EF4 strength as it passed near [[Moulton, Alabama|Moulton]] and [[Trinity, Alabama|Trinity]], debarking trees, mangling, and leveling homes. It then continued through the northwest corner of [[Morgan County, Alabama|Morgan County]], crossed Wheeler Lake, and moved into [[Limestone County, Alabama|Limestone County]], coming within {{convert|2|mi|km}} of [[Browns Ferry Nuclear Power Plant]]. The tornado caused power outages in the area, and the plant had to be shut down. The tornado continued towards the small community of Tanner.<ref name=\"NWS-HUN-SWS-04282141\">{{cite web|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSHUN&e=201104290231|title=Preliminary Storm Survey Information From Limestone And Madison Counties|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"TFP-nuke\">{{cite news|author=Pam Sohn|title=TVA loses all power transmission lines in Alabama and Mississippi, Browns Ferry Nuclear plant forced into emergency shutdow|url=http://timesfreepress.com/news/2011/apr/28/tva-losses-all-power-transmission-lines-alabama-an/|accessdate=April 28, 2011|publisher=[[Chattanooga Times Free Press]]|date=April 28, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521065159/http://timesfreepress.com/news/2011/apr/28/tva-losses-all-power-transmission-lines-alabama-an/|archivedate=May 21, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref><ref name=\"HUN-132.1mi\">{{cite web|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSHUN&e=201105020259|title=Long Track EF-5 Tornado Confirmed Across The Tennessee Valley|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=May 2, 2011|accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref> [[Tanner, Alabama|Tanner]]  experienced a large swath of EF4 damage and a narrow corridor of \"high-end EF4 to near-EF5 damage\". The storm \"completely wiped clean\" several well constructed homes with anchor bolting.<ref name=\"NWS-HUN-SWS-04282141\"/> As the storm crossed [[U.S. Route 72|U.S. Highway 72]] in eastern Limestone County, the tornado destroyed a [[Doppler weather radar|Doppler radar]] operated by [[NBC]] affiliate [[WAFF (TV)|WAFF]] (channel 48) and continued into East Limestone, a heavily populated area of Limestone County where homes in subdivisions were damaged or destroyed at high-end EF3 strength. As the storm crossed into Madison County, it approached the densely populated suburban communities of [[Harvest, Alabama|Harvest]] and [[Toney, Alabama|Toney]], where it either damaged or destroyed hundreds of homes, especially in the Anderson Hills and Carter's Gin subdivisions. Many homes were reduced to rubble, and the damage in this area was rated mainly EF3 with a small pocket of EF4 damage in Harvest. The tornado completely destroyed a [[Piggly Wiggly]] grocery store in Harvest and severely damaged a convenience store and local bank, which was shut down for months following the event.<ref name=\"SWDJW-04272011ToneyHarvestDestruction\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.al.com/breaking/2011/04/at_least_7_dead_scores_injured.html|title=Harvest & Toney, AL Destruction|publisher=[[The Birmingham News|AL.com]]|date=July 9, 2011|accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> The storm progressed across Pulaski Pike in northwest Madison County, damaging many homes. In all, hundreds of homes received moderate to major damage along the path from Limestone to Madison County with many of these being total losses.<ref name=\"NWS-HUN-SWS-04282141\"/>\n\nThe tornado then moved into [[Tennessee]] and continued south of [[Huntland, Tennessee|Huntland]]. Isolated and minor EF0 to EF1 damage was noted through most of its path in Tennessee. Widespread damage to trees and outbuildings occurred in this area. The worst damage, however, was to a cinder block utility building and was rated lower-end EF3. Most of its roof was removed, with over half of its downwind wall pushed outward. The tornado eventually dissipated east of Huntland.<ref name=\"HUN-132.1mi\"/>\n\nIn total, this tornado killed 72 people, all in Alabama.<ref name=\"spc fatal\"/> This made it the deadliest single tornado ever to strike the state of Alabama as well as (at the time) the deadliest in the United States since the 1955 [[Udall, Kansas]] tornado that killed 80 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crh.noaa.gov/ict/udall/udall.php|title=The Udall Kansas Tornado: May 25, 1955|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=August 31, 2010|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/faq/tornado/killers.html|title=The 25 Deadliest U.S. Tornadoes|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref> In addition to being the deadliest, this tornado also had the longest track of any tornado in the outbreak, with its path extending {{convert|132.1|mi|km}} across Northern Alabama and into Tennessee.<ref name=\"HUN-132.1mi\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Reform\u2013Oakman\u2013Cordova\u2013Blountsville, Alabama===\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF4\n| total fatalities = 13 fatalities, 54+ injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\n[[File:Cordovafromwest.jpg|thumb|right|Aerial view of the damage path through Cordova from the west (looking east).]]\nThe tornado touched down at 3:40 PM CDT in northeastern [[Pickens County, Alabama]], damaging a few chicken homes at EF1 strength. The tornado caused roof damage to houses and destroyed a few outbuildings before moving into [[Tuscaloosa County, Alabama|Tuscaloosa County]] and briefly into [[Fayette County, Alabama|Fayette County]], causing major EF2 tree damage and minor structural damage. The tornado then moved back into Tuscaloosa County, causing mostly minor tree and structural damage at EF1 strength before rapidly intensifying and crossing into Fayette County once again. There, it completely destroyed at least one mobile home, with the frame being separated and the remaining debris being thrown a considerable distance. The tornado appeared to strengthen even further and several mobile homes were completely obliterated with debris thrown a considerable distance and frames twisted and thrown. Damage was rated EF3 in this area. Many trees were downed as well before the tornado moved into [[Walker County, Alabama|Walker County]]. It then weakened to EF1 strength and caused mostly minor damage to trees and mobile homes. South of [[Oakman, Alabama|Oakman]], numerous trees were snapped and uprooted, a cell phone tower was knocked down, and mobile homes were destroyed at EF2 intensity. It then rolled vehicles and destroyed a cinder block house to the southeast of Oakman, with damage rated EF3 at that location. The tornado weakened considerably as it approached [[Interstate 22|Corridor X]] of the [[Appalachian Development Highway System]], with only minor EF0 tree damage, before it strengthened significantly as it entered the town of [[Cordova, Alabama|Cordova]] as a {{convert|0.5|mi|km|adj=on}} wide EF3.<ref name=\"Cordova tornado\">{{cite web|title=Cordova (Pickens, Tuscaloosa, Fayette, Walker and Blount Counties) EF-4 Tornado April 27, 2011|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/bmx/?n=event_04272011cordova|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Birmingham, Alabama|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:CordovaDamagefromGround.jpg|thumb|right|Major damage in a residential area of Cordova.]]\nIn Cordova, numerous homes and manufactured houses were either damaged or destroyed in this area along with many trees being downed. Some unanchored homes in town were swept from their foundations. Buildings in downtown Cordova had already been damaged by an EF3 tornado earlier that morning and received further damage from this tornado. East of Cordova, the tornado crossed the [[Mulberry Fork of the Black Warrior River]] three times (along with the [[Sipsey Fork of the Black Warrior River|Sipsey Fork]] once, just north of its confluence with the Mulberry Fork). It intensified further into a violent EF4 in northeastern Walker County, as it completely leveled a site-built home and obliterated two nearby mobile homes. One of the mobile home undercarriages was tossed at least {{convert|500|yd|m|}}. A 5-ton bulldozer was flipped over, a pickup truck was tossed {{convert|200|yd|m|}}, and a dump truck was tossed {{convert|50|yd|m|}} and destroyed. A two-ton trailer was thrown {{convert|1|mi|km|}} and left a {{convert|2.5|ft|m|adj=on}} deep crater where it impacted the ground. Two double-wide mobile homes were tossed at least {{convert|100|yd|m|}}, and a third mobile home was tossed {{convert|100|yd|m|}} up a {{convert|50|foot|m|}} embankment and destroyed along this segment of the path as well. South of [[Sipsey, Alabama|Sipsey]], additional homes and mobile homes were destroyed at EF2 to EF3 strength and numerous trees were snapped.<ref name=\"Cordova tornado\"/>\n\nThe tornado then crossed the Mulberry Fork for the fourth time and moved into [[Cullman County, Alabama|Cullman County]]. South of [[Arkadelphia, Alabama|Arkadelphia]], a second area of EF4 damage was observed, as a cinder block construction home was leveled and a car was thrown {{convert|130|yd|m|}}. Nearby, an underground storm shelter collapsed onto the occupants sheltering inside as the tornado passed overhead.<ref name=\"Cordova tornado\"/> The tornado then crossed the Mulberry Fork again, moving into [[Blount County, Alabama|Blount County]], where it caused EF1 roof damage to a home and snapped hundreds of trees. It then crossed [[Interstate 65 in Alabama|Interstate 65]] before crossing the Mulberry Fork into Cullman County southwest of [[Garden City, Alabama|Garden City]], snapping numerous additional trees at EF1 strength. It quickly crossed the river again (the seventh crossing), moving back into Blount County. As it continued to the south-southwest of Garden City, it straddled the Mulberry Fork before finally moving solidly into Blount County and toward [[Blountsville, Alabama|Blountsville]]. On the southeast side of Blountsville, the tornado downed many trees and caused high-end EF2 damage to well-built brick and slab foundation homes, one of which had some exterior walls collapse. The storm continued to the northeast and out of Blountsville, where two additional homes sustained high-end EF3 damage. A large portion of one of the homes was wiped off of its foundation; however, its garage sustained only minor roof damage. At the second of these two homes, a dump truck was thrown {{convert|30|ft|m|}}.<ref name=\"Cordova tornado\"/> The tornado then moved into [[Marshall County, Alabama|Marshall County]], causing significant damage to a house and downing numerous trees. A shed suffered roof damage and an industrial plant was completely destroyed at EF2 strength as well. The tornado then moved into a wooded area, weakened, and eventually lifted south-southwest of [[Guntersville, Alabama|Guntersville]] at 5:56&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2256 UTC). Thousands of trees were downed along the tornado's path.<ref name=\"Marshall County survey\">{{cite web|title=Marshall County (The End of the Long Track Tornado \u2013 Ending East of Hwy 79 and South of Hwy 431) EF-2|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=4272011_marshall_longtrackend|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=October 2, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThis tornado was on the ground for two hours and sixteen minutes, tracking for {{convert|127.8|mi|km}} across seven counties. It was rated as a low-end EF4 with winds of {{convert|170|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}. In total, 13 people were killed and 54 others were injured.<ref name=\"Cordova tornado\"/><ref name=\"Marshall County survey\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Smithville, Mississippi/Shottsville, Alabama===\n{{Main|2011 Smithville, Mississippi tornado}}\n\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF5\n| total fatalities = 23 fatalities, 137 injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nThis extremely violent EF5 wedge tornado, with estimated winds of up to {{convert|205|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, struck the town of [[Smithville, Mississippi]], at 3:47&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2047 UTC) on April 27, resulting in catastrophic damage and numerous fatalities.<ref name=\"NWSMemphisSmithvilleEF5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/meg/?n=apr2011toroutbreaksmithville|title=Smithville, MS EF-5 Tornado|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Memphis, Tennessee|date=May 30, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> The tornado began {{convert|3|mi|km|}} west-southwest of Smithville along the [[Tennessee\u2013Tombigbee Waterway]] near the [[Glover Wilkins Lock]] at 3:42&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2042 UTC), snapping numerous trees near the Smithville Recreation Area. The tornado then rapidly intensified as it approached town, reaching EF5 intensity. As the storm crossed Davis Road South, the ground was deeply scoured in a nearby field.<ref name=\"Smith. Damage Imagery\">{{cite web|url=http://ngs.woc.noaa.gov/storms/apr11_tornado/|title=April 2011 Tornado Response Imagery|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Geodetic Survey|year=2011|accessdate=June 20, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131229064349/http://ngs.woc.noaa.gov/storms/apr11_tornado/|archive-date=December 29, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The tornado swept away numerous homes and structures as it moved northeast, following [[Mississippi Highway 25|Highway 25]]. A semi-truck was thrown a considerable distance and destroyed in this area, and at one residence that was swept away, part of the concrete foundation slab was pulled up and dislodged slightly.<ref name=\"NWSMemphisSmithvilleEF5\"/><ref name=\"Smith. Damage Imagery\"/> Multiple well-anchored brick homes were completely swept away, and a large brick funeral home was reduced to a bare slab as the tornado exited at the northeast side of town, with the debris scattered and wind-rowed into an adjacent wooded area. Nearby granite tombstones were blown over in the opposite direction of the tornado's passage. Overall, the tornado destroyed 117 structures in Smithville and damaged 50 others, killing 16 people.<ref name=\"Smithville NCDC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=303562|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|author=National Climatic Data Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|year=2011|accessdate=June 13, 2014}}</ref> The tornado weakened as it continued through rural areas northeast of town and moved into [[Itawamba County, Mississippi|Itawamba County]], where it downed numerous trees and power lines and caused roof damage to a house before exiting the county.<ref name=\"Smith. Damage Imagery\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=303563|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|author=National Climatic Data Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|year=2011|accessdate=June 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe tornado continued across the [[Alabama]] state line into [[Marion County, Alabama|Marion County]], where it caused EF1-strength damage near [[Bexar, Alabama|Bexar]]. Continuing northeast, the tornado re-intensified as it struck the rural community of [[Shottsville, Alabama|Shottsville]] at high-end EF3 intensity, where homes and mobile homes were destroyed and seven people were killed, and it produced additional high-end EF3 damage as it continued north of [[Hamilton, Alabama|Hamilton]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=4272011_franklin_county_hodges|title=Franklin County Alabama (Hodges Area) EF-2|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=June 5, 2012|accessdate=July 20, 2014}}</ref> More structures were impacted as the tornado approached and crossed into [[Franklin County, Alabama|Franklin County]]. The tornado then dissipated near the town of [[Hodges, Alabama|Hodges]] at 4:23&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2123 UTC). The damage path was {{convert|37.3|mi|km}} long and {{convert|3/4|mi|km|}} wide at its widest point, and it killed a total of 23 people along its path. 137 other people were injured.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/bmx/?n=event_04272011shotsville|title=Shottsville (Marion County) EF-3 Tornado April 27, 2011|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Birmingham, Alabama|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Pisgah\u2013Flat Rock\u2013Higdon, Alabama/Trenton, Georgia===\n[[File:Trenton2011.JPG|thumb|left|255px|Aerial view of damage in Trenton.]]\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF4\n| total fatalities = 14 fatalities, 50+ injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nThis multiple-vortex EF4 tornado devastated portions of [[Jackson County, Alabama|Jackson]] and [[DeKalb County, Alabama|DeKalb]] counties in Alabama, as well as [[Dade County, Georgia|Dade]] and [[Walker County, Georgia|Walker]] counties in Georgia along a {{convert|47|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} path, killing 14 people and injuring at least 50 others.<ref name=\"NOAA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=04272011_jackson_northern-dekalb |title=Eastern Jackson (AL) / Northern De kalb (AL) - EF-4 (Section to Flat Rock to GA) |date=February 15, 2012 |website=NWS Huntsville, AL |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=June 15, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Storm Events Database\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=304631 |title=Storm Events Database |website=NCDC |publisher=NCDC |accessdate=June 15, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ncdc.noaa.gov\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=304667 |title=Storm Events Database |website=NCDC |publisher=NCDC |accessdate=June 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe tornado touched down north of [[Section, Alabama|Section]], initially producing EF0 to EF1 tree damage. The tornado rapidly intensified to low-end EF4 strength as it passed northwest of [[Pisgah, Alabama|Pisgah]] and [[Rosalie, Alabama|Rosalie]], destroying numerous mobile homes and block foundation homes, scattering the debris hundreds of yards and killing three people. Thousands of trees were snapped and debarked, vehicles were thrown up to 50 yards in different directions, and barns and chicken houses were heavily damaged, along with the roof of a church.<ref name=\"NOAA\"/> As it passed near [[Flat Rock, Alabama|Flat Rock]] and [[Higdon, Alabama|Higdon]], the tornado reached high-end EF4 strength, mowing down thousands of trees in this rural area. As the tornado struck a farm, a home and two chicken houses were completely obliterated and swept away. A heavy propane tank was lofted and thrown 100 yards from one of the chicken houses, and 19 cattle on the property were killed. Remarkably, a family of four taking shelter inside the house were completely unharmed.<ref name=\"NOAA\"/> The tornado maintained EF4 strength as it tore through the rural community of Shiloh, sweeping away numerous mobile homes and block foundation homes and killing 5 people at that location. Thousands of trees were snapped, a log cabin was destroyed, livestock was killed, chicken houses were flattened, and a van was lofted and dropped into a field 400 yards away from where it originated.<ref name=\"NOAA\"/> The tornado then crossed into Georgia and struck [[Trenton, Georgia|Trenton]] as an EF3, killing two people. Dozens of homes in Trenton were completely destroyed, 18 others sustained major damage, and tens of thousands of trees were downed in the area. A grocery store, two apartment complexes, and a funeral home were destroyed as well.<ref name=\"Storm Events Database\"/>\n\nThe tornado weakened to EF2 strength as it struck [[Flintstone, Georgia|Flintstone]] further to the northeast, but still resulted in major damage. Numerous trees and power lines were downed, 7 homes were destroyed, 26 sustained major damage, and 35 sustained minor damage in the Flintstone area. The tornado continued northeast, weakening to EF0 strength before finally dissipating near [[Fort Oglethorpe, Georgia|Fort Oglethorpe]].<ref name=\"ncdc.noaa.gov\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Tuscaloosa/Birmingham, Alabama===\n{{Main|2011 Tuscaloosa\u2013Birmingham tornado}}\n[[File:Tornado Track in Tuscaloosa, Alabama.jpg|thumb|left|170px|Satellite image of the tornado's track through Tuscaloosa.]]\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF4\n| total fatalities = 64 fatalities, ~1,500 injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nA large multiple-vortex [[wedge tornado]] touched down in rural [[Greene County, Alabama]], and tracked across neighboring [[Tuscaloosa County, Alabama|Tuscaloosa County]], including the southern and eastern portions of [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]] at around 5:10&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2210 UTC) on April 27.<ref name=\"massive\">{{cite news|first1=Enjoli|last1=Francis|first2=Jeremy|last2=Hubbard|first3=Leezel|last3=Tanglao|publisher=[[ABC News]]|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/massive-tornado-hits-alabama-storms-leave-16-dead/story?id=13465028|title=Storms, Tornadoes Leave Dozens Dead in Alabama, Mississippi, Georgia and Tennessee|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=April 28, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110428040702/http://abcnews.go.com/US/massive-tornado-hits-alabama-storms-leave-16-dead/story?id=13465028|archivedate=April 28, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref><ref name=\"NWSBir.Tusc.Survey\">{{cite web|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Birmingham, Alabama|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/bmx/?n=event_04272011tuscbirm|title=Tuscaloosa-Birmingham EF-4 Tornado April 27, 2011|year=2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> Debris from the tornado was reported to be falling from the sky across [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]] over {{convert|20|mi|km}} away in [[Jefferson County, Alabama|Jefferson County]]. Skycams operated by Tuscaloosa television station [[WVUA-CD|WVUA-CA]] (channel 7) as well as Birmingham [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] affiliate [[WBRC]] (channel 6), [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] affiliate [[WBMA-LD]]/[[WCFT-TV]]/[[WJSU-TV]] (channels 58, 33, and 40), and [[CBS]] affiliate [[WIAT]] (channel 42) captured live footage of the tornado as it struck Tuscaloosa; WIAT received awards, including a regional [[Edward R. Murrow Award (Radio Television Digital News Association)|Edward R. Murrow Award]] for \"Outstanding Live Coverage\" of the event).<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[WOFL]] |url=http://www.myfoxorlando.com/video?clipId=7236537&autostart=true |title=VIDEO: Alabama tornado |date=April 28, 2011 |accessdate=July 15, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225183242/http://www.myfoxorlando.com/video?clipId=7236537&autostart=true |archivedate=December 25, 2013 |df= }}</ref> As the tornado traveled east to 35th Street and Kauloosa Avenue, the Tuscaloosa Environmental Services and [[Cintas]] facilities suffered severe damage. Numerous homes and apartment buildings in the Rosedale and Forest Lake neighborhoods, as well as a P&P Grocery store in Rosedale, were devastated. Several stores and restaurants in a business district at the intersection of McFarland Boulevard and 15th Street, near the DCH Regional Medical Center, were reduced to rubble. Buildings on 35th Street, between [[Interstate 359]] and Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard, were also completely destroyed. The Alberta City neighborhood in eastern Tuscaloosa sustained catastrophic damage as numerous homes, apartment buildings, and a shopping center were completely leveled. Additional high-end EF4 damage occurred in the Tuscaloosa suburb of [[Holt, Alabama|Holt]] further to the northeast, as several homes were leveled or swept away in that area. The tornado then exited the Tuscaloosa area and moved through dense forest towards Birmingham, downing and debarking thousands of trees.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Tuscaloosa News|url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20110427/NEWS/110429711?Title=AFTERMATH--Accounts-of-the-Tuscaloosa-tornado|title=THE AFTERMATH: Staff accounts of the tornado|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[University of Alabama]] shut down its campus briefly during the course of the storm itself, resuming regular activities within minutes. Upon realizing the extent of the storm damage immediately off-campus, including areas of off-campus student housing, the university shut down all academic and extracurricular activities for the remainder of the day, and then, still later, for the remaining ten days of the academic semester. All final exams were cancelled, with all registered students receiving a final grade based on their grade as of the day of the storm. Spring commencement ceremonies were postponed until August 6. The University itself was undamaged by the storm, though six students enrolled at the University were later discovered to have perished.<ref>{{cite web|title=Closings|url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20110428/NEWS/110429643|publisher=Tuscaloosa News|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Radar image of the 2011 Tuscaloosa tornado April 27, 2011 2210Z.png|thumb|250px|Radar and velocity image of the supercell that produced the tornado at 22:10&nbsp;UTC (5:12&nbsp;p.m. CDT) as it struck Tuscaloosa, with a [[debris ball]] clearly visible.]]\n[[File:Tuscaloosa Apartment Complex.JPG|thumb|left|The demolished Chastain Manor apartment complex in Tuscaloosa.]]\nMany stations, including WIAT, WBMA/WCFT/WJSU, [[WTVY (TV)|WTVY]] (channel 4) in [[Dothan, Alabama|Dothan]] and [[WSFA]] (channel 12) in [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], showed television cameras capturing the event as the tornado moved east-northeast across the western and northern suburbs of Birmingham around 6:00&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2300 UTC). Several suburbs in the area were severely damaged by the massive tornado as it tore through the west side of Birmingham, resulting in fatalities. The suburbs of [[Concord, Alabama|Concord]], [[Pleasant Grove, Alabama|Pleasant Grove]], and [[McDonald Chapel, Alabama|McDonald Chapel]] were devastated by the tornado as it moved northeast, flattening entire neighborhoods. As the tornado entered the Birmingham city limits, it devastated the [[Pratt City, Alabama|Pratt City]] neighborhood, destroying numerous homes and apartment buildings. The tornado then struck the suburb of [[Fultondale, Alabama|Fultondale]], causing EF2 damage to homes and businesses before dissipating east of Fultondale.<ref name=\"NWSBir.Tusc.Survey\"/><ref>{{cite web|first1=Tim|last1=Ballisty|first2=Chris|last2=Dolce|first3=Jonathan|last3=Erdman|publisher=[[Weather Channel|Weather.com]]|url=http://www.weather.com/outlook/weather-news/news/articles/severe-weather-tracker-april22-26_2011-04-22|title=Severe Weather: Track the Storms|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=April 27, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110510131036/http://www.weather.com/outlook/weather-news/news/articles/severe-weather-tracker-april22-26_2011-04-22|archivedate=May 10, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> Surveys indicated high-end EF4 damage from the tornado in Birmingham's western suburbs.<ref name=\"NWSBir.Tusc.Survey\"/>\n\nThe [[National Weather Service]] determined the path length of this violent tornado to be {{convert|80.7|mi|km}} with a maximum damage path width of {{convert|1.5|mi|km}}. The tornado's most intense damage indicated peak winds of around {{convert|190|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}; therefore, it was given a final rating of EF4. Reports from Tuscaloosa indicated 44 people were killed, with an additional 20 deaths in Birmingham.<ref name=\"NWSBir.Tusc.Survey\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=City says 44 deaths attributed to tornado|url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20110708/NEWS/110709754|publisher=Tuscaloosa News|date=June 8, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> Overall this tornado killed 64 people and injured more than 1500.<ref name=\"spc fatal\"/><ref name=\"NWSBir.Tusc.Survey\"/> [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] and [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Michelle Obama]] visited Tuscaloosa on April 29, taking a ground tour of some of the affected areas. Obama was quoted as saying that he had \"never seen devastation like this.\" He stated further that he had already declared a federal state of emergency in Alabama.<ref name=\"nprttown\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2011/04/29/135842102/obama-in-tuscaloosa-ive-never-seen-devastation-like-this|title=Obama In Tuscaloosa: 'I've Never Seen Devastation Like This'|author=Eyder Peralta|date=April 29, 2011|work=National Public Radio|publisher=Corporation for Public Broadcasting|accessdate=April 29, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110502172806/http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2011/04/29/135842102/obama-in-tuscaloosa-ive-never-seen-devastation-like-this|archivedate= May 2, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Fackler\u2013Stevenson\u2013Bridgeport, Alabama/Haletown, Tennessee===\n[[File:Bridgeport, AL April 27 tornado damage.jpg|thumb|left|Concrete steps that were ripped from the foundation of a house, with a small concrete porch slab pulled up in the background.]]\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF4\n| total fatalities = 1 fatality\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nThis EF4 tornado, with winds of up to {{convert|180|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, touched down just northeast of the community of [[Fackler, Alabama|Fackler]] at 5:05&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2205 UTC) on April 27, initially causing minor damage to mobile homes and downing trees. The tornado then moved northeast toward [[Stevenson, Alabama|Stevenson]], where large trees were downed, several roofs were damaged, a trailer was tipped over, and a shed was partially destroyed. It then reached EF3 intensity, and 24 metal high-tension truss towers were twisted and flattened northeast of [[Stevenson Airport]]. In this area, a mobile home was obliterated and a site-built house was collapsed. Two other homes sustained structural damage, two mobile homes were rolled on their side, and a metal barn was destroyed as well. The tornado then continued to the northeast and reached EF4 strength, with the most significant damage being located near the intersection of County Roads 255 and 256. Here, a home was reduced to its foundation, a concrete slab at the front of the home was pulled up, and a set of concrete stairs was ripped from the foundation. A compact car was thrown about {{convert|50|yd|m|}} as well.<ref name=\"Fackler tornado\">{{cite web|title=Jackson County (Bridgeport Area) EF-4|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=04272011_jackson|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=June 26, 2012|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"FacklerNCDC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=301882|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nContinuing, the tornado reduced two more well-built and well-anchored homes to their block foundations and threw another car approximately {{convert|50|yd|m|}}. Several large trees were snapped off just above the ground, a third home was left with no walls standing, and a mobile home was completely demolished and strewn along County Road 256 as well. The tornado continued northeastward, destroying a cinder block garage and damaging a mobile home along 6th Street, just southeast of [[Bridgeport, Alabama|Bridgeport]]. It then crossed the [[Tennessee River]], producing significant tree damage before moving into [[Marion County, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"Fackler tornado\"/><ref name=\"FacklerNCDC\"/> The tornado entered [[Tennessee]] along Lakeview Drive near [[Moore Crossing, Tennessee|Moore Crossing]] and [[Nickajack Dam]]. It then proceeded to cross [[Nickajack Lake]] three times near [[Interstate 24]] at EF2 strength, downing numerous trees before dissipating in a bend of the Tennessee River northeast of [[Haletown, Tennessee|Haletown]] at 5:31&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2231 UTC). The tornado travelled {{convert|30.24|mi|km|}} through Jackson and Marion Counties and had a peak width of {{convert|1320|yd|m|}}. One person was killed by the tornado in Jackson County.<ref name=\"Fackler tornado\"/><ref name=\"FacklerNCDC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=343727|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Sawyerville\u2013Eoline, Alabama===\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF3\n| total fatalities = 7 fatalities, 52+ injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nThis strong, long-tracked EF3 wedge tornado touched down in extreme southwest [[Greene County, Alabama|Greene County]] to the west-southwest of [[Tishabee, Alabama|Tishabee]], near the [[Sumter County, Alabama|Sumter County]] border, at 5:30&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2230 UTC) and moved northeast. After having touched down in a rural area on the east side of the [[Tombigbee River]], the tornado quickly intensified to high-end EF2 strength along County Road 69. Moving northeast, the tornado damaged a barn and destroyed two small churches and at least four mobile homes. While crossing [[U.S. Route 43|U.S. 43]], the tornado destroyed a large metal outbuilding, caused substantial roof and wall damage to several brick buildings and homes. Hundreds of trees were downed in this area as well. Two people sustained minor injuries in Greene County as the tornado continued along a primarily rural path northeast, moving across the [[Black Warrior River]] and into [[Hale County, Alabama|Hale County]].<ref name=\"Sawyerville/Eoline tornado\">{{cite web|title=Sawyerville-Eoline (Greene, Hale and Bibb Counties) EF-3 Tornado April 27, 2011|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/bmx/?n=event_04272011sawyerville|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Birmingham, Alabama|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=April 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"GreeneCo NCDC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=314725|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|author=National Climatic Data Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|year=2011|accessdate=April 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe tornado entered Hale County west of [[Sawyerville, Alabama|Sawyerville]], continuing to move through sparsely populated rural areas. North of Sawyerville, the tornado strengthened to EF3 intensity as it was crossing [[Alabama State Route 14|Alabama State Highway 14]]. Reaching estimated maximum winds of {{convert|145|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, the tornado continued on its northeast track, crossing County Roads 18 and 21, [[Alabama State Route 69|Alabama State Highway 69]], and County Road 29 as it moved south and east of the small communities of [[Harper Hill, Alabama|Harper Hill]] and [[Ingram, Alabama|Ingram]]. The tornado caused extensive structural damage through this area, consisting of many mobile homes and site-built homes being either heavily damaged or destroyed. A church in the area was heavily damaged, vehicles were tossed around and destroyed, and thousands of trees were uprooted as well.<ref name=\"Sawyerville/Eoline tornado\"/><ref name=\"HaleCoEF3 NCDC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=314742|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|author=National Climatic Data Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|year=2011|accessdate=April 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:EolineFireDept.jpg|thumb|The destroyed Eoline Volunteer Fire Department building.]]\nLeaving behind six fatalities and forty more injuries, the tornado maintained its intensity as it moved into the [[Talladega National Forest]]. It downed a significant number of trees before moving into [[Bibb County, Alabama|Bibb County]] north of [[Alabama State Route 25|Alabama State Highway 25]].<ref name=\"Sawyerville/Eoline tornado\"/><ref name=\"HaleCoEF3 NCDC\"/> In Bibb County, the tornado continued moving northeastward through the Talladega National Forest at EF3 intensity, with thousands more trees being knocked down and partially debarked. Almost immediately after exiting the national forest, the tornado directly impacted the small community of [[Eoline, Alabama|Eoline]] along [[U.S. Route 82|U.S. Highway 82]], northwest of [[Brent, Alabama|Brent]] and [[Centerville, Alabama|Centerville]]. Around one dozen mobile homes and single-family site-built homes were destroyed, while many more sustained anywhere from minor to major damage. Additionally, the Eoline Volunteer Fire Department and another business were both destroyed. One fatality occurred in Eoline, in a vehicle near the fire department building, along with ten other injuries.<ref name=\"Sawyerville/Eoline tornado\"/><ref name=\"BibbCoEF3 NCDC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=314799|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|author=National Climatic Data Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|year=2011|accessdate=April 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nNortheast of Eoline, the tornado weakened to EF2 intensity, continuing to cause significant damage as it crossed County Road 9, [[Alabama State Route 5|Alabama State Highway 5]], and County Road 26, south of [[West Blocton, Alabama|West Blocton]]. Several mobile homes and site-built homes were either destroyed or sustained major damage. Along the path, thousands of trees were downed. The tornado continued to weaken as it moved to the east of West Blocton, continuing to knock down trees. More trees were downed as the tornado crossed the [[Cahaba River]] and lifted just northeast of [[Marvel, Alabama|Marvel]] at 6:55&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2355 UTC), not far from the [[Shelby County, Alabama|Shelby County]] border.<ref name=\"Sawyerville/Eoline tornado\"/><ref name=\"BibbCoEF3 NCDC\"/>\n\nThe tornado was rated as an EF3, with maximum sustained winds of {{convert|145|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}. It remained on the ground for almost an hour and a half, traversing {{convert|72.13|mi|km|}}, being, at times, about {{convert|1|mi|km|}} wide. In total, seven people were killed and an additional 52 were injured.<ref name=\"Sawyerville/Eoline tornado\"/><ref name=\"GreeneCo NCDC\"/><ref name=\"HaleCoEF3 NCDC\"/><ref name=\"BibbCoEF3 NCDC\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Raleigh\u2013Rose Hill\u2013Enterprise, Mississippi/Yantley\u2013Uniontown, Alabama===\n{{Infobox storm \n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF4\n| total fatalities = 7 fatalities, 17 injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\n[[File:Smith Jasper Clarke Counties tornado 2011-04-27.jpg|thumb|The EF4 Enterprise tornado, as it was in southeast Mississippi.<ref name=\"Raleigh, MS tornado\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/jan/?n=2011_04_25_27_svr_smith_jasper_clarke|title=Smith/Jasper/Clarke CountiesTornado|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Jackson, Mississippi|date=September 14, 2011|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref>]]\nThis extremely long-tracked, violent EF4 tornado touched down near [[Raleigh, Mississippi]], in [[Smith County, Mississippi|Smith County]] at 5:42&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2242 UTC), and continued into the [[Uniontown, Alabama]] area before dissipating. The tornado initially downed trees, blew skirting from mobile homes, and tore shingles from roofs. The tornado intensified as it moved northeast across Smith County and produced up to EF2 and EF3 damage. One mobile home was picked up, bounced a couple times, and thrown into a tree line, where it was torn apart and debris was scattered up to a mile away, including the frame. The tornado mowed down a stand of pine trees and destroyed two frame houses, with major damage to the interior walls, and the exterior walls completely destroyed. Many power poles were snapped, a mobile home was annihilated, and a large shop building was completely destroyed as well. It then moved into [[Jasper County, Mississippi|Jasper County]] and snapped and debarked many pine trees. The first area of EF4 damage was observed near [[Louin, Mississippi|Louin]] as a frame home and several mobile homes were completely destroyed, with parts of the mobile homes being thrown long distances, and some of the frame home foundation being swept clean. The tornado caused significant damage to a poultry farm and cattle ranch before it weakened briefly. It then destroyed two mobile homes and caused extensive tree and power line damage. The tornado then produced a relatively narrow path of EF1-strength tree and power line damage for several miles, until re-intensifying near to EF3 strength near [[Rose Hill, Jasper County, Mississippi|Rose Hill]].<ref name=\"Raleigh, MS tornado\"/>\n\nSoutheast of Rose Hill, the tornado removed most of the roof of a frame home and caused heavy damage to the exterior walls, took a large section of roof off another frame home, completely destroyed a large mobile home, and caused extensive tree damage. The tornado then weakened again and entered [[Clarke County, Mississippi|Clarke County]] as an EF0 while only downing a few trees. The tornado strengthened again and downed trees and power lines as it crossed [[Interstate 59]]. Several other homes and mobile homes were destroyed as the tornado moved along the south side of [[Enterprise, Clarke County, Mississippi|Enterprise]]. At the same time, [[Sean Casey (filmmaker)|Sean Casey]] of Team TIV shot the tornado with his new 3D camera as it was crossing I-59, making this the first tornado ever shot in 3D. Another area of EF4 damage was observed east of Enterprise as a new home undergoing completion was leveled, with the debris swept off the foundation. Many more frame homes were heavily damaged nearby. Many mobile homes were destroyed and trees were downed in this area as well. It then weakened slightly to EF3 strength and produced heavy damage to more houses and mobile homes near [[Snell, Mississippi|Snell]] and [[Energy, Mississippi|Energy]]. It also downed many more trees and power lines before moving into [[Choctaw County, Alabama]] southwest of [[Yantley, Alabama|Yantley]]. The tornado killed seven people and injured fourteen others on its {{convert|65|mi|km|adj=on}} portion of the path that was in [[Mississippi]].<ref name=\"Raleigh, MS tornado\"/>\n\nIn Choctaw County, the tornado traveled {{convert|27.5|mi|km|}} as it caused extensive damage to homes (one of which was destroyed at EF3 strength), and numerous other structures. Several mobile homes were destroyed and many trees were either snapped or completely uprooted. The tornado then moved into [[Sumter County, Alabama|Sumter County]].<ref name=\"Yantley survey\">{{cite web|title=April 25\u201328, 2011 Tornado Outbreak Information|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/mob/?n=20110427_tor|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Mobile, Alabama|date=January 17, 2013|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> In Sumter County, the tornado caused significant damage to homes and mobile homes before it crossed the [[Tombigbee River]] and moved into [[Marengo County, Alabama|Marengo County]]. It continued causing significant tree damage as well as destroying several homes and outbuildings along a {{convert|26.7|mi|km|adj=on}} path in this county. The tornado then entered [[Perry County, Alabama|Perry County]], the final portion of the path, where it damaged two outbuildings and a grain silo as well as causing significant tree damage before lifting just north of [[Uniontown, Alabama|Uniontown]] at 8:35&nbsp;p.m. CDT (0135 UTC). The damage in Sumter, Marengo, and Perry Counties was rated EF2.<ref name=\"Uniontown tornado\">{{cite web|title=Pin Hook-Faunsdale (Sumter, Marengo and Perry Counties) EF-2 Tornado April 27, 2011|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/bmx/?n=event_04272011pinhook|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Birmingham, Alabama|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThis tornado was on the ground for nearly three hours, having traveled {{convert|122.04|mi|km|}} across seven counties in two states. Seven people were killed and another 17 were injured.<ref name=\"Raleigh, MS tornado\"/><ref name=\"Yantley survey\"/><ref name=\"Uniontown tornado\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Fyffe\u2013Rainsville\u2013Sylvania\u2013Ider, Alabama===\n[[File:Destroyed bus in Rainsville.JPG|thumb|left|School bus stripped down to its chassis in Rainsville.]]\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF5\n| total fatalities = 25 fatalities, unknown injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nThis violent multiple-vortex tornado, rated EF5, began in the Lakeview community northeast of [[Geraldine, Alabama]], at 6:19&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2319 UTC), during the late afternoon of April 27. The tornado tracked northeastward for {{convert|36.63|mi|km|}} generally parallel to and just east of [[Alabama State Route 75|Highway 75]] through [[Fyffe, Alabama|Fyffe]], [[Rainsville, Alabama|Rainsville]], and [[Sylvania, Alabama|Sylvania]] and into [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], killing 25 people.<ref name=\"Rainsville, AL Tornado Survey\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=4272011_dekalb_county|title=Dekalb (AL) \u2013 Lakeview to Rainsville to Cartersville|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=February 15, 2012|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe tornado touched down in the Lakeview community, initially causing structural damage to small buildings and snapping trees. The tornado grew in intensity as it struck [[Fyffe, Alabama|Fyffe]], where more significant damage occurred. Past Fyffe, the tornado became violent, and its width increased from around {{convert|50|yd|m|}} to {{convert|0.5|mi|m|}} as it entered eastern [[Rainsville, Alabama|Rainsville]], reaching EF5 strength and destroying numerous homes and businesses. A [[Huddle House]] restaurant, the Rainsville Civic Center, and a credit union were destroyed. Vehicles were also thrown, including a school bus that was completely stripped down to its chassis.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2011/apr/29/nation/la-na-rainsville-alabama-tornadoes-20110430|title=In Rainsville, tragedy and amazing tales of survival|last1=Bermudez|first1=Esmeralda|date=April 29, 2011|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> Numerous homes in the Rainsville area were swept completely away, with debris strewn up to a mile from the foundations. Some of these homes were connected to their foundations with anchor bolts and foundation straps. Trees were debarked and mobile homes were completely destroyed as well.<ref name=\"Rainsville, AL Tornado Survey\"/> Damage was particularly intense just northeast of Rainsville, and one well-built stone house in this area was completely obliterated, with the debris strewn well away from the structure. A large supporting cement and stone pillar was ripped completely out of the ground at this residence, pulling up a section of concrete foundation in the process. Scouring and pock-marking of the ground was noted in this area. Numerous homes were swept away along Lingerfelt Rd as well. At one house that was swept away in this area, supporting concrete anchors were ripped out of the ground, a concrete porch was ripped off with pieces strewn up to {{convert|150|yd|m|}} away, a pick-up truck from the home was found mangled in pieces over {{convert|250|yd|m|}} away, and a safe weighing {{convert|800|lb|kg|}} was pulled off its anchorage and thrown into a wooded area {{convert|600|ft|m|}} away. When found, the safe's door had been ripped open and completely off.<ref name=\"Rainsville, AL Tornado Survey\"/> An underground storm shelter in this area had much of its dirt covering scoured away, the occupants of which reported that structure heaved upwards slightly as the tornado passed overhead. Pavement was scoured from several roads in the area, and a concrete porch was torn away and broken in half at another residence that was swept away.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ams.confex.com/ams/26SLS/webprogram/Handout/Paper212695/sels12b.pdf|title=Extreme Damage Incidents In The 27 April 2011 Tornado Superoutbreak|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration/[[University of Alabama in Huntsville]]/[[Universities Space Research Association]] (jointly produced article)|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama/Birmingham, Alabama (both offices)|author1=Eugene W. McCaul, Jr.|author2=Kevin R. Knupp|author3=Chris Darden|author4=Kevin Laws|year=2011|accessdate=July 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe tornado continued across the eastern fringes of [[Sylvania, Alabama|Sylvania]], where a church was completely destroyed, a section of sidewalk was pulled up, and additional homes were swept away and scattered, though it was revealed that these homes were pushed off of their foundations with limited anchorage. A high-end EF4 rating was applied in this area as a result.<ref name=\"Rainsville, AL Tornado Survey\"/> The tornado continued to level additional homes as it passed near [[Henagar, Alabama|Henagar]] and [[Ider, Alabama|Ider]]. It crossed into [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] near [[Fox Mountain, Georgia|Fox Mountain]] as an EF1 with winds of {{convert|110|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}. It tracked {{convert|3|mi|km|}} into Georgia before lifting outside of [[Rising Fawn, Georgia|Rising Fawn]] at 6:55&nbsp;p.m. CDT/7:55&nbsp;p.m. EDT (2355 UTC). Damage in Georgia was limited to trees and power lines and minor structural damage to a few homes. This tornado came from the same supercell that produced the EF4 that hit the town of [[Ringgold, Georgia]] about 30 minutes later.<ref name=\"Rainsville, AL Tornado Survey\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=304706|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|author=National Climatic Data Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|year=2011|accessdate=May 22, 2016}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Shoal Creek Valley\u2013Ohatchee\u2013Piedmont, Alabama/Cave Spring, Georgia===\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF4\n| total fatalities = 22 fatalities, 85 injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\n[[File:Shoal Creek Valley Alabama Tornado April 27, 2011.jpg|thumb|The Shoal Creek Valley/Ohatchee EF4 tornado.]]\nAfter the Tuscaloosa/Birmingham tornado lifted, the same supercell produced another tornado, at 6:28&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2328 UTC) near [[Argo, Alabama]], in eastern [[Jefferson County, Alabama|Jefferson County]]. It went on to devastate the rural community of Shoal Creek Valley, located between [[Ashville, Alabama|Ashville]] and [[Ragland, Alabama|Ragland]] in [[St. Clair County, Alabama]].<ref name=\"Shoal Creek-Ohatchee survey\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/bmx/?n=event_04272011ohatchee|title=Argo-Shoal Creek-Ohatchee-Forney (Jefferson, St. Clair, Calhoun, Etowah, and Cherokee Counties) EF-4 Tornado April 27, 2011|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Birmingham, Alabama|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=December 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter touching down southwest of Argo, the tornado continued northeast of [[Odenville, Alabama|Odenville]], producing EF0 to EF1 tree damage. Further east, the tornado intensified to EF3 strength and entered the rural community of Shoal Creek Valley, following along County Road 22/Shoal Creek Road for approximately {{convert|12.5|mi|km}}, with the path and width varying greatly along the road. Many homes were left with only interior walls standing in this area. Some section of this path segment had damage that was much worse on one side of the road than the other, while other areas showed equal devastation on both sides of the road. The tornado reached mid-range EF4 intensity towards the end of the valley as it approached [[Neely Henry Lake]]. Additional homes were destroyed in this area, one was swept away, and thousands of trees were mowed down and debarked. The tornado maintained EF4 strength as it crossed the lake and tore across the north edge of [[Ohatchee, Alabama|Ohatchee]], completely leveling or sweeping away numerous waterfront homes. Damage ranged from downed trees and roof damage to total destruction as the tornado roared through this area at {{convert|50|-|60|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, packing winds of over {{convert|180|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}. The official count of homes destroyed or heavily damaged in Shoal Creek Valley and Ohatchee was 256. Most phone lines, power lines and poles were destroyed, and water lines were severed by uprooted trees. Entire homes were leveled, and in some cases completely removed by the storm, leaving only brick steps, a fireplace and chimney, or a slab behind. Barns, vehicles, tractors and heavy farming equipment were shredded and thrown up to {{convert|0.5|mi|km}} away from where they originated. Livestock were thrown and killed, and the initial human death toll of 13 would eventually rise to 15 in the area.<ref name=\"Shoal Creek-Ohatchee survey\"/> The tornado caused mainly EF3 damage to homes as it passed north of [[Wellington, Alabama|Wellington]], though a small pocket of EF4 damage occurred in the small rural community of [[Webster's Chapel, Alabama|Webster's Chapel]], where a church and several homes were completely leveled or swept away, trees were reduced to stumps, and many other homes were left with only interior walls standing.<ref name=\"Shoal Creek-Ohatchee survey\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/StormDamage/DamageViewer/|title=NWS Damage Assessment Toolkit|work=noaa.gov}}</ref> The Silver Lakes Golf Course also sustained major damage in this area, where at least 50,000 trees were flattened and buildings were damaged or destroyed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gadsdentimes.com/article/20110604/NEWS/110609901?tc=ar|title=Tornado-damaged Silver Lakes faces uncertain future|work=GadsdenTimes.com}}</ref> Continuing northeast, the tornado produced high-end EF3 damage north of [[Piedmont, Alabama|Piedmont]], destroying mobile homes, snapping numerous trees, and leveling a house. Additional homes were leveled at high-end EF3 intensity near [[The Indian Mountain Tract]] before it continued across rural areas into [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref name=\"Shoal Creek-Ohatchee survey\"/> Many outbuildings and homes were destroyed, and many trees were downed across [[Polk County, Georgia|Polk]], [[Floyd County, Georgia|Floyd]], and [[Bartow County, Georgia|Bartow]] counties before the tornado dissipated. Severe damage was noted near [[Cave Spring, Georgia|Cave Spring]] where chicken houses and homes were damaged or destroyed, and several people were injured. The damage in Georgia was rated EF2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/ffc/?n=20110427_svrstorms#polk|title=Polk, Floyd, and Bartow Counties|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Peachtree City, Georgia|date=May 10, 2011|accessdate=December 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThis tornado's final death toll, combining fatalities in both St. Clair and [[Calhoun County, Alabama|Calhoun]] counties in Alabama, would eventually come to 22.<ref name=\"spc fatal\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Ringgold, Georgia/Southeast Tennessee===\n[[File:Ringgold tornado damage.jpg|thumb|left|EF4 damage in a subdivision at the north edge of Ringgold, Georgia. Seven fatalities occurred at this location.]]\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF4\n| total fatalities = 20 fatalities, 335 injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nA violent multiple-vortex tornado struck portions of extreme northern Georgia and southeast Tennessee during the mid-evening hours of April 27. It touched down along Davis Ridge Road in [[Catoosa County, Georgia]], and moved through the town of [[Ringgold, Georgia|Ringgold]] at EF3 strength, destroying numerous homes and businesses.<ref name=\"NWSRinggoldEF4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/ffc/?n=20110427_svrstorms#catoosa|title=Catoosa County|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Peachtree City, Georgia|date=May 10, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> A [[Baymont Inn & Suites]], located near [[Interstate 75]] was partially destroyed by the tornado, along with a [[McDonald's]], a [[Taco Bell]], and several gas stations located on Highway 151 in Ringgold at the Interstate 75 interchange (exit 348). The Catoosa County Department of Family and Children Services and other businesses on Nashville Street in downtown Ringgold were also heavily damaged. The Kellerhals Center for Visual Arts Education at Ringgold High School was destroyed (RHS itself had minor damage), and Ringgold Middle School was heavily damaged.<ref name=\"NWSRinggoldEF4\"/><ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[The Daily Citizen (Dalton)|Dalton Daily Citizen]]|url=http://daltondailycitizen.com/local/x58991204/Ringgold-devastated-after-tornado-touchdown|title=Ringgold devastated after tornado touchdown|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=April 30, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120707190019/http://daltondailycitizen.com/local/x58991204/Ringgold-devastated-after-tornado-touchdown|archivedate=July 7, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Past downtown Ringgold, the tornado reached EF4 intensity as it tore through a subdivision along Cherokee Valley Road at the north edge of town. Twelve homes were completely obliterated and swept away at that location (though they were not well-built). Several trees were denuded and debarked in this area as well. There were 74 destroyed homes and/or businesses, 60 with major damage, and 118 with minor damage for a total of 252 affected structures in the Ringgold area. Eight people were killed, mainly at the subdivision along Cherokee Valley Road.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=305268 |title=Storm Events Databse |website=NCDC |publisher=NCDC |accessdate=June 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Apison, TN tornado damage.PNG|thumb|right|EF4 damage to a brick home in Apison, Tennessee.]]\nThe storm then crossed the Tennessee state line at 8:28&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]] (0028 UTC), and moved into [[Hamilton County, Tennessee]], striking the small town of [[Apison, Tennessee|Apison]] at high-end EF4 strength, where large homes were leveled or swept away, 150 others were damaged, and thousands of trees were snapped and uprooted.<ref name=\"NWSApisonEF4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/mrx/?n=hamiltonbradleycollegedaleef4|title=Hamilton County \u2013 Bradley County \u2013 Collegedale EF4 Tornado Track and Photos|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Morristown, Tennessee|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=296789 |title=Storm Events Databse |website=NCDC |publisher=NCDC |accessdate=June 15, 2014}}</ref> The tornado then crossed into Bradley County at low-end EF4 strength, moving across the southern and eastern fringes of [[Cleveland, Tennessee|Cleveland]] and affecting mainly residential areas, though a few businesses were damaged or destroyed as well. Subdivisions in the southern part of the city sustained major damage, with numerous houses destroyed and a few that were leveled.<ref name=\"NWSApisonEF4\"/> Four people were killed in Cleveland, and many others were injured.<ref name=\"NWSApisonEF4\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=300457 |title=Storm Events Databse |website=NCDC |publisher=NCDC |accessdate=June 15, 2014}}</ref> Several trees were felled in Polk County (as the tornado had weakened to EF1-strength), before the tornado crossed into McMinn County.<ref name=\"NWSApisonEF4\"/> The tornado re-strengthened to an EF2 and destroyed two houses and a mobile home before lifting south of [[Athens, Tennessee|Athens]].<ref>{{cite web|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=353334|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=January 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe tornado killed 20 people and injured hundreds more along its {{convert|57|mi|km|adj=on}} path across Catoosa, Hamilton, Bradley, Polk and McMinn counties. The tornado was given a rating of EF4 with winds ranging from {{convert|175|-|190|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}. The damage path of the tornado was between {{convert|1/3|and|1/2|mi|km}} wide. This tornado was only the eighth in Georgia to be categorized as an F4/EF4 on the ([[Enhanced Fujita scale|Enhanced]]) [[Fujita scale]] since 1950, when official tornado records begin.<ref name=\"NWSRinggoldEF4\"/><ref name=\"NWSApisonEF4\"/><ref name=\"EF4\">{{cite news|publisher=OKC Storm Watcher|url=http://okcstormwatcher.wordpress.com/2011/04/29/ringgold-ga-tornado-confirmed-as-an-ef-4-tornado/|title=Ringgold, GA Tornado Confirmed as an EF-4 Tornado (4/27/2011)|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=April 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAll roads in and out of Ringgold were closed until the morning of April 29; after roads leading to the affected areas were re-opened, residents and business owners were allowed to return, being allowed entry only by providing identification, and informing police a reason why they were entering into the area, in order to curb looting in the storm-damaged areas.<ref name=\"Ringgold\">{{cite news|publisher=[[WXIA-TV]]|url=http://marietta.11alive.com/news/news/ringgold-residents-return-utter-devastation/59674|title=Ringgold residents return to 'utter devastation'|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=April 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Non-tornadic effects==\n{{see also|2011 Mississippi River floods}}\n[[File:Pcpnweekending04292011.jpg|thumb|right|Rainfall totals within the United States for the week ending during the morning of April 29, 2011, which shows the extent of the heavy rain event this cyclone contributed towards.]]\nThis storm system prolonged an ongoing heavy rain event, which began across Arkansas and Missouri on April 22.<ref name=\"SS11\"/> Weekly rainfall totals reached {{convert|19.73|in|mm}} {{convert|6|mi|km|}} east-northeast of [[Springdale, Arkansas]], {{convert|16.20|in|mm}} {{convert|4|mi|km|}} northwest of [[Poplar Bluff, Missouri]], and {{convert|14.96|in|mm}} at [[Westville, Oklahoma]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/winter_storm_summaries/2011/storm11/stormsum_21.html|author=DavidHamrick|publisher=Weather Prediction Center|accessdate=May 1, 2011|date=April 28, 2011|title=Storm Summary 21 for Central and Eastern U.S. Heavy Rain Event}}</ref> On April 25, 2011, thunderstorms with high winds swept through parts of southern and southeastern Ohio. Straight-line winds estimated at {{convert|80|mph|km/h}} uprooted trees, damaged roofs, and downed power lines through [[Perry County, Ohio]], and [[Athens County, Ohio]]. Strong thunderstorms and heavy downpours which led to flooding were also reported in areas across Upstate New York with heavy flooding in the [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]] area. The rain also saturated hundreds of lakes in the [[Adirondack mountains]]. [[Interstate 81]] was briefly shut down in the downtown area at traffic hour and the [[State University of New York Upstate Medical University]] also closed briefly due to flooding in the lobby.<ref>{{cite news|last=McChensey|first=Charles|title=Severe storms, flash floods strike Central New York|url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2011/04/severe_storms_flash_floods_str.html|publisher=[[The Post-Standard|Syracuse.com/The Post-Standard]]|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=April 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nFarther south, flash flooding late on April 26 resulted in two fatalities in [[Monroe, Louisiana]] after an apartment complex was swamped. The flooding there was considered to be worse than the flooding after [[Hurricane Gustav]] in [[2008 Atlantic hurricane season|2008]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |work=National Weather Service in Shreveport, Louisiana |title=The Tornado Outbreak of April 25\u201327, 2011 |url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/shv/events/select.php?date=04262011_1 |date=May 9, 2011 |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303205221/http://www.srh.noaa.gov/shv/events/select.php?date=04262011_1 |archivedate=March 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In central and northern Arkansas, up to {{convert|10.44|in|mm|}} of rain was reported during that week. The resulting flash flooding in central Arkansas also resulted in five people losing their lives. Many roads were closed due to the flooding there. The flooding was mitigated somewhat by a significant [[drought]] that had existed before the storm.<ref>{{cite news|agency=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=Heavy Rain/Severe Weather on April 23\u201327, 2011 (Pg1)|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/lzk/?n=rain0411yr.htm|publisher=National Weather Service|date=May 14, 2011|accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSevere thunderstorms were reported as far north as [[Northern Ontario]] on the evening of April 26. Heavy rains and minor flooding were also reported in Northern Ontario from April 26\u201328.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[Sault Star]]|url=http://www.saultstar.com/2011/04/28/old-hospital-site-floods-updated-at-136-pm|title=Old hospital site floods|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120806190258/http://www.saultstar.com/2011/04/28/old-hospital-site-floods-updated-at-136-pm|archive-date=August 6, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[Sudbury Star]]|url=http://www.thesudburystar.com/2011/04/27/rain-soaks-sudbury|title=Rain soaks Sudbury|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222082441/http://www.thesudburystar.com/2011/04/27/rain-soaks-sudbury|archive-date=December 22, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=Sudbury Star|url=http://www.thesudburystar.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=3100195|title=Keep eye out for possible flooding, city advises|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322094650/http://www.thesudburystar.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=3100195|archive-date=March 22, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[North Bay Nugget]]|url=http://www.nugget.ca/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=3100171|title=Ice is off, and a flood warning issued|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001001921/http://www.nugget.ca/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=3100171|archive-date=October 1, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Windstorms were also reported in [[Southern Ontario]] and Southern [[Quebec]] which resulted in several injuries and one death, damages and power outages.<ref name=\"ottawacitizen.com\">{{cite news|publisher=[[Ottawa Citizen]] |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/Three+women+seriously+hurt+spring+windstorm+whips+through+Ottawa/4691025/story.html |title=Three women seriously hurt as spring wind storm whips through Ottawa |date=April 29, 2011 |accessdate=July 15, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110502213722/http://www.ottawacitizen.com/news/Three%2Bwomen%2Bseriously%2Bhurt%2Bspring%2Bwindstorm%2Bwhips%2Bthrough%2BOttawa/4691025/story.html |archivedate=May 2, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"theweathernetwork.com\">{{cite news|publisher=[[The Weather Network]] ([[Canada]]) |url=http://www.theweathernetwork.com/news/storm_watch_stories3&stormfile=assessing_the_damage_in_onta_280411?ref=ccbox_weather_category1 |title=Wednesday's damage in Ontario being investigated |date=April 29, 2011 |accessdate=April 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402135837/http://www.theweathernetwork.com/news/storm_watch_stories3%26stormfile%3Dassessing_the_damage_in_onta_280411?ref=ccbox_weather_category1 |archivedate=April 2, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref name=\"Fierce winds whip through Ontario\">{{cite news|publisher=The Weather Network (Canada) |url=http://www.theweathernetwork.com/news/storm_watch_stories3&stormfile=winds_whip_through_ontario_280411?ref=ccbox_weather_topstories |title=Fierce winds whip through Ontario |date=April 29, 2011 |accessdate=April 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110502204825/http://www.theweathernetwork.com/news/storm_watch_stories3%26stormfile%3Dwinds_whip_through_ontario_280411?ref=ccbox_weather_topstories |archivedate=May 2, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref name=\"JMontreal\">{{cite web|url=http://lejournaldemontreal.canoe.ca/actualites/faitsdiversetjudiciaires/archives/2011/04/20110428-162908.html|title=Les vents violents font un mort en Ontario|work=Actualit\u00e9s|publisher=[[Journal de Montr\u00e9al]]|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=May 8, 2011|language=fr|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130115090443/http://lejournaldemontreal.canoe.ca/actualites/faitsdiversetjudiciaires/archives/2011/04/20110428-162908.html|archivedate=January 15, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Zone-911\">{{cite web|url=http://zone911.fm93.com/actualites/accidents/item/12689-des-vents-violents-causent-des-d%C3%A9sagr%C3%A9ments-dans-la-r%C3%A9gion-de-montr%C3%A9al |title=Des vents violents causent des d\u00e9sagr\u00e9ments dans la r\u00e9gion de Montr\u00e9al |author=Fran\u00e7ois Houde |date=April 29, 2011 |publisher=Zone911.com |accessdate=May 8, 2011 |language=fr |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323170111/http://zone911.fm93.com/actualites/accidents/item/12689-des-vents-violents-causent-des-d%C3%A9sagr%C3%A9ments-dans-la-r%C3%A9gion-de-montr%C3%A9al |archivedate=March 23, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nOther fatalities due to straight-line winds occurred in [[McComb, Mississippi]] early on April 26<ref name=\"Apr25SPC\"/> and also in [[Moody, Alabama]], [[Vestavia Hills, Alabama]], and [[Franklin, Tennessee]] early on April 27 from the squall line with embedded tornadoes.<ref name=\"Storm Reports April 27\"/><ref name=\"Storm Reports April 26\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\nAlabama Governor [[Robert J. Bentley]] declared a state of emergency in the state of Alabama on April 27, due to storm damage from severe thunderstorms earlier that day as well as forthcoming severe weather later that day. States of emergency were also declared in Arkansas, [[Kentucky]], Mississippi, Missouri, [[Tennessee]], and Oklahoma because of the flooding and tornadoes.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[Travel Weekly]]|url=http://www.travelweekly.co.uk/Articles/2011/04/28/36968/state-of-emergency-declared-in-seven-us-states.html|title=State of emergency declared in seven US states|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> Following the tornado outbreak on the evening of April 27, [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] granted a federal emergency declaration for the state of Alabama, giving federal assistance, including search and rescue assets, to the affected region.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[White House|The White House]]|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2011/04/27/president-obama-signs-alabama-emergency-declaration|title=President Obama Signs Alabama Emergency Declaration|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nMore than 2,000 [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] troops were deployed to Alabama, assisting local and state first responders in search and rescue efforts.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=CNN|url=http://whitehouse.blogs.cnn.com/2011/04/28/white-house-mobilizes-response-in-wake-of-deadly-storms/|title=White House mobilizes response in wake of deadly storms|author=Lesa Jansen|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> President Obama visited the affected areas of Alabama on April 29.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-13233106|title=Barack Obama pledges to help US tornadoes recovery|date=April 29, 2011|work=[[BBC News Online]]|publisher=[[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=April 29, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429033454/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-13233106|archivedate=April 29, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> Also on April 29, he approved a federal disaster declaration for seven Mississippi counties: [[Clarke County, Mississippi|Clarke]], [[Greene County, Mississippi|Greene]], [[Hinds County, Mississippi|Hinds]], [[Jasper County, Mississippi|Jasper]], [[Kemper County, Mississippi|Kemper]], [[Lafayette County, Mississippi|Lafayette]], and [[Monroe County, Mississippi|Monroe]].<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[Hattiesburg American]]|url=http://www.hattiesburgamerican.com/article/20110429/ONLINEONLY/110429017|title=Mississippi receives federal disaster declaration|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}{{Dead link|date=July 2016}}</ref> By the morning of April 30, the Alabama Emergency Management Agency had confirmed at least 45 storm fatalities in Tuscaloosa, but this was later corrected downward to 44. The tornado killed 64 people along its entire path.<ref name=\"alemapressrelease1\"/>\n\n===Electricity outage===\nStorms through the area severely damaged [[Tennessee Valley Authority]] (TVA)'s [[electric power transmission|power grid]] for transmitting electricity throughout the region. More than 300 power transmission towers, {{convert|120|ft|m}} to {{convert|150|ft|m}} tall, were destroyed in the storms, some \"twisted like bow ties\" according to National Weather Service meteorologist Eric Holweg. The towers supported some 90 transmission lines, a mixture of 500[[volt|kV]] and 161kV lines. Those lines provided power from TVA to 128 regional distributors.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesfreepress.com/news/2011/may/03/tva-expects-damaged-transmission-power-lines-repai/|title=TVA expects damaged transmission power lines repaired by end of summer|date=May 3, 2011|accessdate=May 5, 2011|author=Pam Sohn|publisher=[[Chattanooga Times Free Press]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524041741/http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/2011/may/03/tva-expects-damaged-transmission-power-lines-repai/|archivedate=May 24, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref><ref name=\"bowTieTower\">{{cite news|url=http://timesfreepress.com/news/2011/may/03/90-high-voltage-power-towers-twisted-bow-ties/|title=High-voltage power towers 'twisted like bow ties'|date=May 3, 2011|accessdate=May 5, 2011|author=Pam Sohn|publisher=Chattanooga Times Free Press|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524041626/http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/2011/may/03/90-high-voltage-power-towers-twisted-bow-ties/|archivedate=May 24, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Electric line tower.jpg|thumb|Transmission tower bent near [[Huntsville, Alabama]].]]\nTVA lost the ability to transmit power from both [[Browns Ferry Nuclear Power Plant]] and [[Widows Creek Power Plant|Widows Creek Fossil Plant]] after the storms on April 27, requiring both to be shut down. The nuclear plant's [[Shutdown (nuclear reactor)|cold shutdown]] was supported by diesel generators for four days until a second 161kV line could be restored to the plant. The loss of redundant off-site power required a \"notification of unusual event\", the lowest of four levels of concern dictated by the [[Nuclear Regulatory Commission|NRC]]. Some 60 percent of the sirens for warning residents of worse problems around Browns Ferry were disabled by the storms, and the plant had to arrange plans to use cars with loudspeakers to warn residents in case of another problem.<ref name=\"TFP-nuke\"/><ref name=\"bowTieTower\"/> The Nuclear Regulatory Commission stated at a press conference: \"The plants' conditions are stable and are being placed in a cooled-down condition.\"<ref name=UPI-nuke>{{cite news|title=NRC: 'Bama nuke plant shut down safely|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2011/04/28/NRC-Bama-nuke-plant-shut-down-safely/UPI-64291304024604/|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=April 28, 2011|newspaper=[[United Press International|UPI]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesfreepress.com/news/2011/apr/30/nuclear-sirens-conk-out-storm/|title=Nuclear sirens conk out in storm|publisher=Chattanooga Times Free Press|date=April 30, 2011|accessdate=May 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Huntsville, Alabama|Huntsville]] was the largest city with no electricity from TVA.<ref name=\"bowTieTower\"/> All the traffic lights were off, a dusk-to-dawn curfew was imposed, students were sent home from [[United States Space Camp]], and the [[Panoply Arts Festival]] was canceled.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wsoctv.com/news/27722984/detail.html |title=Classmates Recount Terrifying Night Of Tornadoes At Space Camp |publisher=[[WSOC-TV]] |date=April 29, 2011 |accessdate=May 5, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110509034424/http://www.wsoctv.com/news/27722984/detail.html |archivedate=May 9, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.peninsuladailynews.com/article/20110429/news/304299984/port-angeles-man-witnesses-alabama-twister|title=Port Angeles man witnesses Alabama twister|author=Rob Ollikainen|publisher=[[Peninsula Daily News]]|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=May 5, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.al.com/entertainment-times/2011/04/panoply_arts_festival_canceled.html|title=Panoply Arts Festival canceled, food vendors helping city|publisher=[[The Huntsville Times]]|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=May 7, 2011|author=Sarah Cure}}</ref> Power was restored gradually to Huntsville, beginning with 3 percent on the morning of May 1.<ref name=\"3percent\">{{cite news|url=http://www.madisoncountyrecord.com/2011/05/01/some-power-restored-to-huntsville-area/|title=Some power restored to Huntsville area|publisher=Madison County Record|date=May 1, 2011|accessdate=May 5, 2011}}</ref> Only localized outages remained eight days after the storm.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.al.com/breaking/2011/05/huntsville_utilities_has_power.html|title=Huntsville Utilities has power back to most customers, some still waiting|publisher=AL.com|date=May 5, 2011|accessdate=May 5, 2011|author=Brian Lawson}}</ref> In addition to traffic and safety issues, the outage caused difficulties with water treatment and distribution and retail of all kinds, including [[gasoline]] and food purchases.<ref name=\"3percent\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.al.com/spotnews/2011/04/alabama_tornadoes_small_store.html|title=Alabama tornadoes: Small store at Warrior thrives as people search for gas, food and refreshment|publisher=AL.com|work=Birmingham News|date=May 5, 2011|accessdate=April 28, 2011|author=Lisa Osburn}}</ref>\n\nOntario electricity outages were minor, mostly caused by the windstorms of April 28. Although they affected thousands of people at different times throughout the day, all power was restored by the end of the day.<ref name=\"ottawacitizen.com\"/><ref name=\"theweathernetwork.com\"/><ref name=\"Fierce winds whip through Ontario\"/><ref name=\"JMontreal\"/><ref name=\"Zone-911\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Weather}}\n* [[List of North American tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n* [[List of F5 and EF5 tornadoes]]\n* [[Tornadoes of 2011]]\n* [[List of disasters in the United States by death toll]]\n* [[Tornado records]]\n* [[Tri-State Tornado]] \u2013 Deadliest tornado in North America, and made March 18, 1925 the deadliest tornado day recorded in United States.\n* [[1932 Deep South tornado outbreak]] \u2013 Deadliest tornado outbreak in Alabama history, including an F4 tornado that tracked through Tuscaloosa.\n* [[1936 Tupelo\u2013Gainesville tornado outbreak]] \u2013 Infamous tornado outbreak occurring on April 5\u20136, 1936. Deadliest U.S. tornado outbreak since the March 1925 (Tri-State Tornado) outbreak, thus surpassing the March 1932, April 1974, and April 2011 outbreaks in total fatalities.\n* [[April 1956 Birmingham tornado]] \u2013 F4 tornado that hit the northern Birmingham suburbs on April 15, 1956.\n* [[1974 Super Outbreak]] \u2013 Infamous tornado outbreak that occurred on April 3\u20134, 1974, similar in severity to the 2011 Super Outbreak; though the 2011 event surpassed the 1974 Super Outbreak as the largest recorded outbreak.\n* [[April 1977 Birmingham tornado]] \u2013 F5 tornado that hit the northern Birmingham suburbs on April 4, 1977.\n* [[1994 Palm Sunday tornado outbreak]] \u2013 March 27, 1994 outbreak that produced an F4 tornado in St. Clair, Calhoun and Cherokee Counties in north-central Alabama.\n* [[April 1998 Birmingham tornado]] \u2013 F5 tornado that struck western parts of Birmingham on April 8, 1998.\n* [[December 2000 Tuscaloosa tornado]] \u2013 F4 tornado that hit southeast suburbs of Tuscaloosa on December 16, 2000.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal |last = Chiu |first = Samantha |title = Mesoscale and Stormscale Ingredients of Tornadic Supercells Producing Long-track Tornadoes in the 2011 Alabama Super Outbreak |journal = M.S. Thesis |publisher = University of Illinois |location = Urbana-Champaign |year = 2013 |doi = |hdl = 2142/45431 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|April 25\u201328, 2011 tornado outbreak}}\n* [http://hook-echo.com/2011/04/28/april-27-2011-tornado-outbreak-tuscaloosa-and-birmingham-alabama Hook\u2013Echo.com Tornado Outbreak Overview]\n* [http://www.stormtimemachine.com/ Time lapse visualization of the April 25\u201328 tornado outbreak]\n* [http://www.tornadohistoryproject.com/custom/3391989 Interactive map of all the tornado paths during the April 25\u201328 outbreak]\n\n'''Emergency Tornado Aid'''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724043339/http://american.redcross.org/site/PageServer?pagename=ntld_main&gclid=COy-qNqUxagCFcq8KgodHyY8tw National Red Cross]\n* [http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20110428/MULTIMEDIA/110429676 Tuscaloosa News People Finder] \u2013 Set up by local newspaper to aid in finding loved ones and friends missing in the tornado.\n\n'''Memorials'''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110807043225/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/44045587/ns/us_news-life/ University of Alabama Holds Memorial Ceremony Honoring Students who Died in Disaster as well as First Responders]\n\n'''Pictures from Tuscaloosa, Alabama'''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150624015151/http://www.marcokaschuba.com/tuscaloosa_tornado/index.php#001 Tornado Damage in Tuscaloosa, Alabama]\n\n'''Video'''\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hR83MBQNGqw Overhead view of Cullman, Alabama damage]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J8uSIQLftME Detailed Radar loop of Northern Alabama, Eastern Mississippi, and Southern Tennessee]\n\n{{2011 Super Outbreak}}\n{{2011 tornado outbreaks}}\n{{Alabama tornado events}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2011-04-27 Super Outbreak}}\n[[Category:F5 tornadoes by date]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Texas]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes of 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 natural disasters in the United States|Tornado,2011-04-27]]\n[[Category:Tuscaloosa, Alabama]]\n[[Category:History of Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:2011 in Alabama]]\n[[Category:2011 in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:2011 in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:2011 in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:2011 in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:2011 in Maryland]]\n[[Category:2011 in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:2011 in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:2011 in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:2011 in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:2011 in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:2011 in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:2011 in Texas]]\n[[Category:2011 in Virginia]]\n[[Category:2011 disasters in Canada|Tornado,2011-04-27]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Canada by date]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:April 2011 events in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2011 events in the United States|Super Outbreak]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Super Outbreak (disambiguation)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = 2011 Super Outbreak\n| image = Apr 27 2011 tornado outbreak Southern USA.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = The storm system responsible for the historic tornado outbreak on April 27\n| type = [[Tornado outbreak]]<br/>[[Extratropical cyclone]]<br/>[[Flood]]\n| active = April 25\u201328, 2011 \n| lowest pressure = \n| lowest temperature =\n| tornadoes = [[List of tornadoes in the 2011 Super Outbreak|360 confirmed]]<br />{{small|(Record for a continuous outbreak)}}\n| fujitascale = EF5\n| tornado duration = 3 days, 7 hours, 18 minutes\n| highest winds = {{convert|210|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}<br/><small>([[Hackleburg, Alabama|Hackleburg]]/[[Phil Campbell, Alabama|Phil Campbell, AL]] EF5 on April 27)</small>\n| hail = {{convert|4.5|in|cm|}} in diameter in [[Saltville, Virginia]], on April 27\n| gusts =\n| maximum snow = \n| power outages =\n| total fatalities = 324 (+24 non-tornadic) fatalities, 3,100+ injuries<ref name=\"spc fatal\"/><ref name=\"cbs342\">{{cite news|publisher=[[CBS News]]|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2011/05/01/national/main20058765.shtml?tag=cbsContent;cbsCarousel|title=Tornado victims seek comfort in Sunday services|date=May 1, 2011|accessdate=May 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Vilonia\">{{cite web|work=[[National Weather Service]] in Little Rock, Arkansas|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=April 28, 2011|title=Heavy Rain/Severe Weather on April 23\u201327, 2011|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/lzk/?n=hydro0411.htm}}</ref><ref name=cnn>{{cite news|publisher=CNN|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/US/05/01/severe.weather/index.html?hpt=T2/|title=Top federal officials tour, promise help to tornado-ravaged South|accessdate=May 1, 2011|date=May 1, 2011}}</ref>\n| damages = ~$11 billion (2011 USD)<ref name=InsuranceNewsnet/><br/><small>(Costliest on record for a tornado outbreak)</small>\n| affected = [[Southern United States]], [[Midwestern United States]], [[Eastern United States]]\n| current advisories =\n| enhanced = yes\n| partof = the '''[[Tornadoes of 2011|tornado outbreaks of 2011]]'''\n}}\n\nThe '''2011 Super Outbreak''' was the largest, costliest, and one of the deadliest [[tornado outbreak]]s ever recorded, taking place along the [[Southern United States|Southern]], [[Midwest]]ern, and [[Northeastern United States|Northeastern]] [[United States]] and leaving catastrophic destruction in its wake.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Tornado Debris Characteristics and Trajectories During the 27 April 2011 Super Outbreak as Determined Using Social Media Data|journal=Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society|volume=94|issue=9|pages=1371\u20131380|doi=10.1175/BAMS-D-12-00036.1|year = 2013|last1 = Knox|first1 = John A.|last2=Rackley|first2=Jared A.|last3=Black|first3=Alan W.|last4=Gensini|first4=Vittorio A.|last5=Butler|first5=Michael|last6=Dunn|first6=Corey|last7=Gallo|first7=Taylor|last8=Hunter|first8=Melyssa R.|last9=Lindsey|first9=Lauren|last10=Phan|first10=Minh|last11=Scroggs|first11=Robert|last12=Brustad|first12=Synne}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ams.confex.com/ams/93Annual/webprogram/Paper223690.html|title=Abstract: Comparative Analysis of Multiple Tornado Tracks During Severe Weather Outbreaks: 2011 Super Outbreak, Alabama (93rd American Meteorological Society Annual Meeting)|work=confex.com|date=2013-01-08}}</ref><ref name=\"noaanews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.noaanews.noaa.gov/april_2011_tornado_information.html|title=April 2011 tornado information|date=May 9, 2011|work=[[USA.gov]]|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=May 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/bmx/?n=climo_2011torstats|title=New Tornado Records Set for Alabama|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Birmingham, Alabama|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref> The event not only affected [[Alabama]] and [[Mississippi]] the most severely, but also produced destructive [[tornado]]es in [[Arkansas]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Tennessee]] and [[Virginia]], and affected many other areas throughout the Southern and Eastern United States. In total, 360 tornadoes were confirmed by [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|NOAA]]'s [[National Weather Service]] (NWS) and [[Government of Canada]]'s [[Environment Canada]] in 21 states from [[Texas]] to [[New York State|New York]] to southern [[Canada]]. Widespread and destructive tornadoes occurred on each day of the outbreak, with April 27 being the most active day with a record of 216 tornadoes touching down that day from midnight to midnight [[Central Time Zone|CDT]] (0500 \u2013 0500 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]). Four of the tornadoes were destructive enough to be rated EF5, which is the highest ranking possible on the [[Enhanced Fujita scale]]; typically these tornadoes are only recorded about once each year or less.<ref name=\"noaanews\"/>\n\nIn total, 348 people were killed as a result of the outbreak, which includes 324 tornado-related deaths across six states and an additional 24 fatalities caused by other [[thunderstorm]]-related events such as [[downbursts|straight-line winds]], [[hail]], [[flash flooding]] or [[lightning]].<ref name=\"alemapressrelease1\"/><ref name=\"tuscaloosa missing\">{{cite web|author=Jason Morton|publisher=[[The Tuscaloosa News|Tuscaloosa News]]|date=May 5, 2011|accessdate=May 5, 2011|title=List of missing at 25|url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20110505/NEWS/110509813/1291/dateline?Title=List-of-missing-at-25}}</ref> In Alabama alone, 238 tornado-related deaths were confirmed by the [[Storm Prediction Center]] (SPC) and the state's [[Emergency management|Emergency Management Agency]].<ref name=\"spc fatal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/torn/fataltorn.html|title=Annual Fatal Tornado Summaries|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|work=[[Storm Prediction Center]]|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"alemapressrelease1\">{{cite web|url=http://ema.alabama.gov/filelibrary/PressRelease/NR%20Latest%20Fatalites%20249_043011.pdf |title=Number of weather related fatalities 236 |date=April 30, 2011 |work=Alabama Emergency Management Agency |publisher=State of Alabama |accessdate=April 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224082245/http://ema.alabama.gov/filelibrary/PressRelease/NR%20Latest%20Fatalites%20249_043011.pdf |archivedate=December 24, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nApril 27's 316 fatalities were the most tornado-related fatalities in the United States in a single day since the \"[[Tri-State Tornado|Tri-State]]\" outbreak on March 18, 1925 (when at least 747 people were killed).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crh.noaa.gov/mkx/?n=torout|title=Famous Large Tornado Outbreaks In The U.S |work=National Weather Service in Milwaukee/Sullivan, Wisconsin|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=cnn1925outbreak>{{cite news|publisher=CNN|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/US/04/30/severe.weather/index.html?hpt=T2/|title=Harrowing stories emerge from storm's aftermath|accessdate=April 30, 2011|date=April 30, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"cbsSouth\">{{cite news|publisher=CBS News|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2011/05/01/national/main20058748.shtml?tag=strip|title=South mourns victims of deadly tornadoes|date=April 30, 2011|accessdate=May 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"second deadliest\">{{cite news|publisher=[[NBC News]]/[[Associated Press|AP News and Reuters]] (jointly produced article)|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/42834400|title=Twister Outbreak is Second Deadliest in History|accessdate=April 30, 2011|date=April 30, 2011}}</ref> Nearly 500 preliminary [[local storm report]]s were received for tornadoes over four days, including 292 in 16 states on April 27 alone.<ref name=\"Storm Reports April 27\"/> This event was the costliest tornado outbreak and one of the costliest natural disasters in United States history (even after adjustments for [[inflation]]), with total damages of approximately $11 billion (2011 USD).<ref name=InsuranceNewsnet>{{cite web|author=Diana Rosenberg|publisher=[[A. M. Best|A.M. Best Company Inc.]]|date=May 18, 2011|accessdate=May 20, 2011|title=RMS: Insured Losses From Late April Tornadoes Could Reach $6 Billion|url=http://www.insurancenewsnet.com/article.aspx?id=261515&type=propertycasualty}}</ref>\n\n==Meteorological synopsis==\n[[File:Severe Tornado Outbreak in the Southern United States.ogv|thumb|This animation of satellite images from April 26 through the morning of April 28 shows the development of the storm system which spawned the tornadoes.]]\nThe outbreak was caused by a vigorous upper-level [[Trough (meteorology)|trough]] that moved into the Southern Plains states on April 25. An [[extratropical cyclone]] developed ahead of this upper-level trough between northeastern [[Oklahoma]] and western [[Missouri]], and moved northeastward.<ref name=\"SS11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/winter_storm_summaries/2011/storm11/stormsum_11.html|title=Storm Summary Number 11 For Central U.S. Heavy Rain Event|author=Mike Soltow|publisher=[[Weather Prediction Center]]|date=April 25, 2011|accessdate=April 30, 2011}}</ref> Conditions were similar on April 26, with a predicted likelihood of [[severe thunderstorm]]s, including an extended threat of strong to violent long-track tornadoes throughout the afternoon and evening hours; mixed-layer [[Convective available potential energy|CAPE]] values were forecast to be around 3000\u20134000 J/kg, around east [[Texas]], [[Louisiana]], and [[Arkansas]]. The storm mode on April 26 was predicted to include mostly discrete tornadic [[supercell]]s during both the afternoon and the early evening, shifting over to a [[Mesoscale Convective Complex|mesoscale convective complex]], with more of a threat of damaging winds and hail during the nighttime hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2011/day1otlk_20110426_1630.html|title=April 26, 2011 1630 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 26, 2011|accessdate=April 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs the storm system moved eastward toward the Ohio, Mississippi, and Tennessee Valleys on April 27, a very powerful 80\u2013100 [[knot (unit)|knot]] mid-level [[jet stream]] moved into the [[Ohio Valley|Ohio]] and [[Tennessee Valley]]s behind the trough and created strong [[wind shear]], along with a low pressure center moving quickly northeastward across those areas on April 27. During the afternoon of April 27, CAPE values were estimated to be in the range of 2000\u20133000 J/kg across Louisiana and southern Mississippi, with the moderate instability moving northeastward across the southern Tennessee Valley; additionally, temperatures across the southeastern United States ranged from the 70s\u00b0F (mid-20s\u00b0C) to the lower 90s\u00b0F (near 35&nbsp;\u00b0C). [[Hydrodynamical helicity|Helicity]] levels ranged from 450\u2013600 m<sup>2</sup>/s<sup>2</sup>, which supported some significant tornadic activity and strong to violent long-track tornadoes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2011/day1otlk_20110427_1630.html|title=April 27, 2011 1630 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=April 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nA total of 56 severe weather watches were issued by the [[Storm Prediction Center]] (SPC) over those four days in the outbreak area. This included 41 [[tornado watch]]es\u201410 of which were [[Particularly Dangerous Situation]] (PDS) watches\u2014and 15 [[severe thunderstorm watch]]es.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/2011/ww0199.html|title=Severe Thunderstorm Watch 199|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 25, 2011|accessdate=May 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/2011/ww0256.html|title=Tornado Watch 256|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=May 13, 2011}}</ref> The SPC assigns numbers to each severe weather watch issued starting at the beginning of each year; the organization unsuccessfully used two of their allocated watch numbers during this outbreak (numbers 208 and 209).<ref name=\"review\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/exper/archive/event.php?date=20110425|title=SPC Severe Weather Event Review for Monday April 25, 2011|date=25 April 2011|work=Storm Prediction Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===April 25===\nA large area of possible severe storms for April 25\u201327 was forecast as the [[Storm Prediction Center]] (SPC) issued a moderate risk of severe weather for three consecutive days, centered over Arkansas through Tennessee. At 3:25&nbsp;p.m. [[Central Time Zone|CDT]] (2025 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]), the SPC issued a [[Particularly Dangerous Situation]] (PDS) [[tornado watch]] for much of Arkansas and parts of Missouri, Oklahoma, Texas, and [[Louisiana]].<ref name=\"Apr25SPC\">{{cite web|work=Storm Prediction Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=April 25, 2011|accessdate=April 25, 2011|title=Storm Prediction Center 110425's Storm Reports|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/110425_rpts.html}}</ref>  By the evening hours of April 25, tornadoes had been reported across a few states, some of which caused significant damage in [[Arkansas]]. An intense [[supercell]] thunderstorm tracked near the [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]] area and a [[tornado emergency]] was declared for the city of [[Vilonia, Arkansas|Vilonia]]. A large [[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF2]] [[Wedge tornado|wedge]] tornado struck the town, subsequently causing severe damage and killing four people.<ref name=\"MSNBC Arkansas\">{{cite web|title='The town's gone': Seven dead as storm slams Ark. |url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/42760079/ns/weather/ |publisher=[[MSNBC]] |accessdate=April 26, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yEZAH8MQ?url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/42760079/ns/weather/ |archivedate=April 26, 2011 |date=April 26, 2011 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref><ref name=\"New York Times AR Tornado\">{{cite news|author=Timothy Williams |title=Deadly Storm Hits Arkansas Town |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/27/us/27arkansas.html |work=[[The New York Times|New York Times]] |accessdate=April 26, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yEa9DclI?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/27/us/27arkansas.html?_r=1 |archivedate=April 26, 2011 |date=April 26, 2011 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref> A strong EF3 tornado had also struck the [[Hot Springs Village, Arkansas|Hot Springs Village]] area earlier that evening; that tornado caused severe damage and resulted in one death. Later that evening, another EF2 tornado caused extensive damage to both a school building and [[Little Rock Air Force Base]] as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littlerock.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123253582 |title=Aerial photography shows damage at Little Rock Air Force Base following tornado |publisher=[[Little Rock Air Force Base|Little Rock Air Force Base Public Affairs]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430133118/http://www.littlerock.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123253582 |archivedate=April 30, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref> Severe [[flood]]ing continued across a large area from the [[Red River of the South|Red River]] valley to the [[Great Lakes]].<ref>{{cite web|work=National Weather Service in Tulsa, Oklahoma|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=May 10, 2011|accessdate=July 19, 2013|title=Event Summary \u2013 April 21\u201327, 2011 Heavy Rain, Record Flooding, and Severe Weather|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/tsa/?n=weather-event_2011apr25}}</ref> A total of 42 tornadoes and five tornado-related deaths were confirmed on the 25th.\n\n===April 26===\nA [[List of SPC high-risk days|high risk]] of severe weather was issued for April 26 for portions of Louisiana, Arkansas, Oklahoma, and Texas along and near the [[Interstate 30]] corridor as conditions became even more favorable for extreme weather.<ref name=\"HighRisk0426\">{{cite web|work=Storm Prediction Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=April 26, 2011|accessdate=April 26, 2011|title=April 26, 2011 1300 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/day1otlk_1300.html}}</ref> A large PDS tornado watch with very high possibilities for tornadoes was issued for that same area that afternoon.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hart|first=John|title=Particularly Dangerous Situation (PDS) Tornado Watch 215|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/2011/ww0215.html|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|accessdate=April 28, 2011|date=April 26, 2011}}</ref> Widespread [[tornado warning]]s were then issued in that area later that evening.<ref>{{cite web|title=Particularly Dangerous Situation (PDS) Tornado Watch 215|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/2011/ww0215_warnings.gif|date=April 26, 2011|accessdate=July 13, 2013|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Particularly Dangerous Situation (PDS) Tornado Watch 217|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/2011/ww0217_warnings.gif|date=April 26, 2011|accessdate=July 13, 2013|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Particularly Dangerous Situation (PDS) Tornado Watch 222|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/2011/ww0222_warnings.gif|date=April 26, 2011|accessdate=July 13, 2013|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref>\n\nAn upper-level negatively-tilted trough with two embedded shortwaves generated two surface lows that propagated generally east. One of the surface lows tracked northeast along the [[Mississippi River]] into [[Wisconsin]] as it occluded. Tornado watches were issued for the Lower Great Lakes during the afternoon hours as supercell thunderstorms developed along the warm front lifting north across central [[Michigan]]. Two tornadoes touched down in Michigan and caused damage to farm structures. Further east, severe thunderstorms caused scattered wind damage and large hail across Pennsylvania and New York. Two-inch-diameter hail was reported in [[Lock Haven, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"Storm Reports April 26\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/110426_rpts.html|title=20110426's Storm Report (1200 UTC \u2013 1159 UTC)|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center}}</ref> An isolated supercell moved across Central New York throughout much of the afternoon, producing golf ball-sized hail in [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]] and spawning a very brief EF1 tornado in [[Verona Mills, New York|Verona Mills]], which primarily caused damage to trees. Another tornado \u2014 this one being in [[Gilbertsville, New York|Gilbertsville]] \u2014 caused significant damage to a school's athletic field.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tornado confirmed near Gilbertsville in Otsego County|url=http://www.erh.noaa.gov/bgm/WeatherEvents/Severe/april25-282011/ef1_gilbertsville.shtml|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Binghamton, New York|accessdate=January 22, 2011|date=April 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe second surface low corresponded to an area of strong upper level divergence ahead of the downstream shortwave. As the low formed across Texas and deepened while moving east, a tightening pressure gradient force further strengthened the low-level jet, therefore creating a broad warm sector across the southeastern states. This also generated stronger wind shear, providing better organization for the supercell storms as a result. Numerous tornadoes touched down across several states, including Texas, Louisiana, Arkansas. Most of those tornadoes were weak, but a few of them caused considerable damage. A long-tracked wedge tornado caused EF2 damage in rural portions of Texas and Louisiana.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Tornado Outbreak of April 25\u201327, 2011 |url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/shv/events/select.php?date=04262011_1 |publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |work=National Weather Service in Shreveport, Louisiana |accessdate=July 11, 2011 |date=April 26, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303205221/http://www.srh.noaa.gov/shv/events/select.php?date=04262011_1 |archivedate=March 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> An EF3 tornado destroyed structures and caused severe damage at [[Fort Campbell, Kentucky]] as well.<ref>{{cite web|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=290471|publisher=[[National Climatic Data Center]]|accessdate=May 9, 2011|year=2011}}</ref> A total of 55 tornadoes were confirmed the 26th, although no fatalities occurred.\n\n===April 27===\nSignificant severe weather was ongoing early on April 27 (in the overnight hours) and continued for the entire calendar day virtually unbroken. For the second day in a row, the SPC issued a high risk of severe weather for the Southern United States. Later that morning, the SPC even increased the probability for tornadoes to 45 percent along a corridor from [[Meridian, Mississippi]], to [[Huntsville, Alabama]], an extremely rare issuance exceeding the high risk standards. Conditions became increasingly favorable for tornadoes during such an extreme tornado outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2011/day1otlk_20110427_1630.html |title=April 27, 2011 1630 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|work=Storm Prediction Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=April 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Morning squall lines====\nDuring the early morning hours, a cold front with several embedded low pressure areas extended from east [[Texas]] northeastward into the [[Ohio River Valley]]. An upper-level disturbance that had moved across the frontal boundary the previous evening sparked an area of thunderstorms that morphed into a [[squall line]]. This line of severe thunderstorms would produce tornadic activity from the evening on April 26 into the late morning of April 27. Early in the morning the squall line, packing straight-line winds and numerous embedded tornadoes, moved through [[Louisiana]] and [[Mississippi]] before proceeding to affect [[North Alabama|North]] and [[Central Alabama]] and parts of [[Middle Tennessee|Middle]] and [[East Tennessee]]. The line strengthened as it moved through [[Alabama]], partially due to a high amount of low-level moisture from the [[Gulf of Mexico]] and increasing [[wind shear]].\n\nA majority of the tornadoes embedded in this initial squall line were weak, though several were strong and as such caused significant damage. An EF3 tornado caused major damage to homes in [[Coaling, Alabama]], an EF2 and an EF3 tornado produced severe damage and a fatality near [[Eupora, Mississippi]]. Another EF3 tornado resulted in heavy damage in downtown [[Cordova, Alabama]], which was struck by a violent EF4 tornado later that afternoon. One embedded cell that began in [[Cullman County, Alabama]] produced a long-tracked EF2 tornado that struck the town of [[Hanceville, Alabama|Hanceville]], killing one person. That cell would then produce over ten tornadoes (most rated EF1) to the northeast in [[Marshall County, Alabama|Marshall County]] and another EF1 tornado in [[Dade County, Georgia]]. The initial storms caused widespread [[power line|power]] and [[telephone line]] outages across Alabama and Tennessee. This line of storms also caused some [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|NOAA]] [[NOAA Weather Radio|weather radio]] transmitter sites to stop functioning for the remainder of the outbreak. Because of this, more than one million customers were without power and had no warning of any approaching tornadoes later that day.<ref name=\"April 27 Conditions HUN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=hunsur2011-04-27_setup|title=April 27th 2011 Severe Weather Setup|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=April 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nFrom the late morning to the early afternoon, another squall line moved through northern parts of Mississippi and Alabama as high wind shear and low-level moisture persisted. However, this time several discrete [[supercell]]s developed along and in front of the line, spawning seven weak tornadoes across [[Morgan County, Alabama|Morgan]], [[Limestone County, Alabama|Limestone]], and [[Madison County, Alabama|Madison]] Counties in northern Alabama around noon that day.<ref name=\"April 27 Conditions HUN\"/>\n\n====Afternoon supercells====\n[[File:Philadelphia, MS ground scouring.jpg|thumb|Extremely deep ground scouring near [[Philadelphia, Mississippi]] caused by a fast-moving EF5 tornado that killed three people.]]\nThe most intense supercells of the outbreak developed around midday in central Mississippi and began tracking eastward. During the early afternoon, as wind shear and low-level moisture continued to dramatically increase, a [[tornado emergency]] was declared for [[Neshoba County, Mississippi]], as a large tornado was reported on the ground by both storm spotters and a camera atop a television tower from [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] affiliate [[WTOK-TV]] (channel 11) in [[Meridian, Mississippi]]. This powerful EF5 tornado caused incredible damage northeast of [[Philadelphia, Mississippi]], where pavement was torn off from roads, vehicles were thrown, and the ground was scoured out to a depth of {{convert|2|ft|m}} by the tornado. Three people died when a mobile home was thrown {{convert|300|yd|m|}} into a wooded area, obliterating it in the process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/jan/?n=2011_04_25_27_neshoba_kemper_winston_noxubee|title=Neshoba/Kemper/Winston/Noxubee Counties Tornado|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Jackson, Mississippi|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=September 8, 2011}}</ref> Another very long-tracked EF4 tornado passed near the town of [[Enterprise, Clarke County, Mississippi|Enterprise, Mississippi]], killing seven people before crossing into Alabama and eventually dissipating. Responding to the high risk issued by the SPC and the already unstable atmosphere expected to become even more unstable throughout the afternoon hours, a [[Particularly Dangerous Situation|PDS]] [[tornado watch]] was issued at 1:45&nbsp;p.m. CDT (1845 UTC) for much of Alabama and portions of Mississippi, Tennessee, and Georgia. A widespread complex of supercell storms overspread the states of Mississippi and Alabama and violent tornadoes began rapidly touching down as the evening progressed.<ref name=\"April 27 Conditions HUN\"/> Four tornadoes were officially rated EF5 on the [[Enhanced Fujita scale]] that day. One of those EF5 tornadoes struck the town of [[Smithville, Mississippi]], where many well-built brick homes were reduced to bare slabs, numerous hardwood trees were completely debarked, and an SUV was hurled half a mile into the top of the town's water tower, subsequently leaving behind a visible dent. Another long-tracked EF5 wedge tornado passed through rural portions of Alabama and Tennessee, becoming the deadliest tornado of the outbreak as it completely devastated the towns of [[Hackleburg, Alabama|Hackleburg]], [[Phil Campbell, Alabama|Phil Campbell]], [[Mount Hope, Lawrence County, Alabama|Mount Hope]], [[Tanner, Alabama|Tanner]], and [[Harvest, Alabama|Harvest]], killing 72 people. This marks only the second day in history (after [[1974 Super Outbreak|April 3, 1974]]) that there were more than two F5/EF5 tornadoes reported.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/faq/tornado/f5torns.html|title=F5 and EF5 Tornadoes of the United States|work=Storm Prediction Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe tornadoes continued tracking through central Alabama that afternoon and into the early evening hours. A dangerous and destructive tornado struck the city of [[Cullman, Alabama]] at around 3:00&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2000 UTC). This large, multiple-vortex tornado was captured on several tower cameras from [[television station]]s, such as [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] affiliate [[WBRC]] (channel 6) and ABC affiliate [[WBMA-LD]]/[[WSES|WCFT-TV]]/[[WGWW|WJSU-TV]] (channels 58, 33, and 40) both out of [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]]. The tornado caused extensive destruction in the city's downtown area; it was ultimately rated EF4. The final damage count was 867 residences and 94 businesses in Cullman, and six people died.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=4272011_cullman_county|title=National Weather Service Huntsville, AL \u2013 Cullman County Survey Information|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=October 2, 2011|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref> The town of [[Cordova, Alabama]], which had already been damaged by an EF3 tornado from the initial round of storms, was struck by an EF4 tornado that killed 13 people. Two violent EF4 tornadoes also ripped through [[Jackson County, Alabama]], one of which caused a fatality near [[Bridgeport, Alabama|Bridgeport]] while the other passed near [[Pisgah, Alabama|Pisgah]] and into Georgia where it caused major damage in [[Trenton, Georgia|Trenton]] and killed 14 people. At around 5:10&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2210 UTC), a very large and exceptionally destructive tornado struck [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama]] and about 40 minutes later, that same tornado struck the northern suburbs of nearby Birmingham.<ref name=\"massive\"/> A tornado emergency was issued for both cities, along with many other cities that day. Many local television stations, including WBRC and WBMA-LD/WCFT/WJSU, as well as [[CBS]] affiliate [[WIAT]] (channel 42), broadcast live footage of this long-tracked tornado in both Tuscaloosa and Birmingham. A debris ball was observed by the Birmingham [[NEXRAD]], indicating that the tornado was causing extreme damage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://supercellweather.com/Debris%20Ball2.png |title=Birmingham Radar |publisher=Supercell Weather.com |date=April 27, 2011 |accessdate=December 1, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120819115842/http://supercellweather.com/Debris%20Ball2.png |archivedate=August 19, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref> This tornado killed 64 people and caused extensive devastation in densely populated areas, and the tornado struck several of the same small communities as the [[April 1956 Birmingham tornado|April 1956 F4]], the [[April 1977 Birmingham tornado|April 1977 F5]] and the [[April 1998 Birmingham tornado|April 1998 F5 tornadoes]] that hit portions of the Birmingham area. The supercell that produced the Tuscaloosa/Birmingham EF4 tornado originated in [[Newton County, Mississippi]]. The supercell also produced an EF4 tornado later that evening that killed 22 people and struck the [[Ohatchee, Alabama]] area and eventually crossed into Georgia, causing additional damage near [[Cave Spring, Georgia|Cave Spring]] before dissipating. Further to the south, a mile-wide EF3 tornado killed 7 people in mostly rural areas and caused major damage in the small town of [[Eoline, Alabama|Eoline]]. The final EF5 tornado of the day caused remarkable damage in and around the town of [[Rainsville, Alabama]], killing 25 people before crossing into Georgia and dissipating. Tornadoes continued touching down further to the northeast as the sun set, particularly in Georgia. This included a long-tracked EF4 tornado that caused major damage in [[Ringgold, Georgia]], [[Apison, Tennessee]], and [[Cleveland, Tennessee]], killing 20 people along the path. After dark, violent tornadoes continued to touch down, and a nighttime EF4 tornado destroyed many lakeside homes at [[Lake Martin]] in eastern Alabama, killing seven people. Additional strong nighttime tornadoes occurred in Georgia, including an EF3 that killed two people in [[Barnesville, Georgia|Barnesville]], and another EF3 that destroyed homes and killed one person at [[Lake Burton (Georgia)|Lake Burton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jayzeetee.wordpress.com/2011/06/20/supercell-tracks-on-april-27th-2011/|title=Supercell Tracks on April 27th, 2011|publisher=jayzeetee.wordpress.com|date=June 20, 2011|accessdate=December 1, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"2011-super-outbreak\">{{cite web |title=Historic Outbreak of April 27, 2011 |url=https://www.weather.gov/bmx/event_04272011 |website=NWS Birmingham |publisher=National Weather Service |accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Continued activity farther east====\nPowerful tornadoes touched down across [[Tennessee]] as well that evening. A violent EF4 struck the community of [[New Harmony, Tennessee]], where homes were leveled, vehicles were tossed, and four people were killed.<ref>{{cite web|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=300460|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref> Two EF3 tornadoes crossed paths in [[Greene County, Tennessee|Greene]] and [[Washington County, Tennessee|Washington]] counties (coming a couple hours apart), resulting in eight fatalities. The rural communities of [[Horse Creek, Tennessee|Horse Creek]] and [[Camp Creek, Tennessee|Camp Creek]] suffered major damage from those tornadoes late that evening.<ref>{{cite web|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/listevents.jsp?beginDate_mm=04&beginDate_dd=27&beginDate_yyyy=2011&endDate_mm=04&endDate_dd=27&endDate_yyyy=2011&eventType=Tornado&county=GREENE&zone=NONE&submitbutton=Search&statefips=47%2CTENNESSEE|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=305738|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref> A very large EF4 wedge tornado leveled a mile-wide swath of forest through {{convert|14|mi|km}} of [[Great Smoky Mountains National Park]].<ref>{{cite web|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=300456|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref> At [[Chilhowee Dam|Chilhowee Lake]], large metal power line truss towers were torn and thrown from their concrete supports that they were anchored to.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/mrx/?n=blountsmokiesef3|title=Blount County Smoky Mountains EF4 Tornado Track and Photos |publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Morristown, Tennessee|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=January 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nA secondary area of severe weather also developed that afternoon and evening along a corridor extending from central and northern [[Virginia]] northward through [[Maryland]], [[Pennsylvania]], and [[New York (state)|New York]], continuing into early April 28. Many tornadoes touched down in this area as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.erh.noaa.gov/bgm/WeatherEvents/Severe/april25-282011/ef1_campbell.shtml |title=EF1 Tornado confirmed near Campbell in Steuben County New York|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Binghamton, New York|date=May 5, 2011|accessdate=December 1, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.erh.noaa.gov/ctp/features/2011/04_2728/index.php|title=Severe Weather of April 27th and 28th, 2011|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in State College, Pennsylvania|date=June 17, 2011|accessdate=December 1, 2012}}</ref> Most of these tornadoes were weak, though an EF2 tornado touched down near the town of [[Halifax, Virginia]], and caused severe damage to homes in the area, resulting in one death.<ref>{{cite web|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=303871|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref> Tornado alerts were issued for [[Southern Ontario]] as far north as [[Ottawa]] as well; one tornado was later confirmed in [[Fergus, Ontario]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guelphmercury.com/news/local/article/529400--environment-canada-confirms-tornado-hit-fergus-area-on-april-27|title=Environment Canada confirms tornado hit Fergus area on April 27|publisher=[[Guelph Mercury]]|date=May 9, 2011|accessdate=December 1, 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:April 27, 2011 severe weather warnings.JPG|thumb|left|Map of all tornado (red), severe thunderstorm (yellow), and flood (green) warnings issued on April 27.]]\n\n====Overview====\nA statewide review by emergency management officials recorded 249 fatalities in Alabama, 23 of which were not tornado-related.<ref name=\"alemapressrelease1\"/> Damage and power outages in the [[Huntsville, Alabama|Huntsville]] area were so widespread that at one point over 650,000 people were out of power in the [[Tennessee Valley Authority]] system. The EF5 tornado that struck Hackleburg and Phil Campbell eventually damaged main power lines coming from [[Browns Ferry Nuclear Plant]] further to the northeast. These towers were the main supply of electrical power to much of North Alabama and some were without power for two weeks. The tornado just missed the Limestone Correctional Facility, which less than a year later would be struck by another tornado.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weather.gov/ffc/20110427_svrstorms|title=Tornado Tracks: April 24th through the 29th, 2011|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Peachtree City, Georgia|date=May 10, 2011|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Storm Prediction Center received 292 reports of tornadoes in the preceding 24 hours.<ref name=\"Storm Reports April 27\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/110427_rpts.html|title=20110427's Storm Reports (1200 UTC \u2013 1159 UTC)|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=April 29, 2011}}</ref> It broke the record for the most tornado touchdowns in 24 hours with 219 in the United States from midnight to midnight CDT (0500 \u2013 0500 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]) breaking the 24-hour record of 147 (in both totals, excluding confirmed tornadoes outside the United States that were part of the outbreak) set by the [[1974 Super Outbreak]]. Of those 219 tornadoes, 59 touched down in Alabama and 79 hit the ground in Tennessee, accounting for well over half of the tornadoes that touched down on April 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/05/02/2011-tornadoes-record-most-in-day_n_856542.html |title=April 2011 Tornadoes Break Record For Most Twisters Ever In A Day |publisher=[[The Huffington Post|Huffington Post]] |date=May 2, 2011 |accessdate=December 1, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006024251/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/05/02/2011-tornadoes-record-most-in-day_n_856542.html |archivedate=October 6, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref> On April 27 alone, the National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama issued 92 tornado warnings, 31 [[severe thunderstorm warning]]s, and seven [[flash flood warning]]s.<ref name=\"SWDJW-04272011-WarningSummaries\">{{cite web|url=http://www.weather.gov/hun/hunsur_2011-04-27_statistics|title=Severe Thunderstorm and Tornado Warning Overview|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=April 25, 2012|accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===April 28===\nTornado watches were issued for the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] coast from [[Pennsylvania]] to [[Florida]] at the start of the day and continued through the morning and early afternoon, but tornadoes were forecasted to generally be weaker and more isolated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2011/day1otlk_20110428_1200.html|title=April 28, 2011 0600 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=April 29, 2011}}</ref> Despite this, the secondary portion of the outbreak that had begun producing scattered tornadoes throughout the [[Mid-Atlantic states|Mid-Atlantic]] and [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]] regions the previous evening intensified during the early hours of the morning, producing numerous tornadoes. A particularly active region, in which there were some strong tornadoes,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/capital-weather-gang/post/april-27-2011-tornado-outbreak-numerous-tornadic-storms-impacted-the-dc-region-as-well/2011/04/28/AFU3DlDF_blog.html|title=April 27-28, 2011 tornado outbreak: Numerous tornadic storms impacted the D.C. region as well|author=Ian Livingston|work=Washington Post|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> was the [[Interstate 81]] corridor extending from southwest [[Virginia]],<ref name=\"washingtonpost1\">{{cite news|author1=Justin Jouvenal|author2=Michael E. Ruane|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/funnel-clouds-reported-throughout-region/2011/04/27/AFZoy01E_story.html|title=Funnel clouds reported across area; 5 killed in southwest Va.|work=[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref>  northward through the [[Shenandoah Valley]]<ref>http://www.whsv.com/content/news/NWS-report-from-the-April-28th-2011-local-tornado-outbreak-481098871.html</ref> and into [[Pennsylvania]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wgal.com/Day-Of-Twisters-NWS-Confirms-4-Tornadoes-On-Thursday/-/9361174/6647180/-/v15p5sz/-/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231001841/http://www.wgal.com/Day-Of-Twisters-NWS-Confirms-4-Tornadoes-On-Thursday/-/9361174/6647180/-/v15p5sz/-/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 31, 2013|title=Day Of Twisters \u2013 NWS Confirms 4 Tornadoes On Thursday|publisher=[[WGAL]]|date=April 30, 2011|accessdate=July 13, 2013}}</ref> and [[New York (state)|New York]]. This included the deadly EF3 tornado that struck the town of [[Glade Spring, Virginia]] very early in the morning, where three people died.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=298380|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=December 1, 2012}}</ref> Tornadoes were also reported in [[Florida]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wltx.com/news/article/134507/2/Midlands-Wakes-Up-to-Rain-Lightning-Hail-|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120527084926/http://www.wltx.com/news/article/134507/2/Midlands-Wakes-Up-to-Rain-Lightning-Hail-|url-status=dead|archive-date=May 27, 2012|title=Midlands Wakes Up to Rain, Lightning, Hail|publisher=[[WLTX]]|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=April 29, 2011}}</ref> [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[South Carolina]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wistv.com/Global/story.asp?S=14528993|title=NWS confirms tornado touchdowns in Calhoun, Sumter counties \u2013 WIS News 10 \u2013 Columbia, South Carolina &#124;|publisher=[[WIS (TV)|WIS-TV]]|date=April 25, 2011|accessdate=April 29, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430073051/http://www.wistv.com/Global/story.asp?S=14528993|archive-date=April 30, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[North Carolina]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wral.com/weather/story/9511896|title=Storms leave isolated damage|publisher=[[WRAL-TV|WRAL]]|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=April 29, 2011}}</ref> and [[Maryland]].  Most of these tornadoes were weak. Although tornado watches were issued, no tornadoes were spotted in [[New Jersey]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2011/04/nj_tornado_warnings_expire.html|title=Storms bring heavy downpour to N.J. but no damage|publisher=[[New Jersey On-Line|NJ.com]]|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=April 29, 2011}}</ref> or [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"washingtonpost1\"/> In the wake of the tornadoes and severe thunderstorms, widespread flooding hit the Midwest, South, and Eastern Seaboard, with extensive flood and flash flood warnings issued.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.intellicast.com/Storm/Severe/WatchesWarnings.aspx|title=Watches & Warnings in United States|publisher=Intellicast|accessdate=April 29, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522071222/http://www.intellicast.com/Storm/Severe/WatchesWarnings.aspx|archivedate= May 22, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> The last tornadoes of the outbreak touched down that afternoon in eastern [[North Carolina]], which was hard hit in the [[Tornado outbreak of April 14\u201316, 2011|April 16 outbreak]], though the tornadoes that impacted the area this time around were weak.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=292059|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref> The system moved out into the [[Atlantic Ocean]] that evening, with the exception of isolated thunderstorms over central Florida that night into April 29, although there were no tornadoes then.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/2011/md0668.html|title=Mesoscale Discussion 668|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notable tornadoes==\n{{see also|List of tornadoes in the 2011 Super Outbreak}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n|+ Daily statistics<ref>{{cite report|title=April 2011 Storm Data|url=http://www1.ncdc.noaa.gov/pub/orders/IPS/IPS-365AE391-42D1-432E-86E8-60949C642469.pdf|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=[[National Climatic Data Center]]|year=2011|accessdate=May 21, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Pgz1a6Xa?url=http://www1.ncdc.noaa.gov/pub/orders/IPS/IPS-365AE391-42D1-432E-86E8-60949C642469.pdf|archivedate=May 19, 2014}}</ref>\n|- \n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|Total\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|&nbsp;EF0&nbsp; \n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|&nbsp;EF1&nbsp;\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|&nbsp;EF2&nbsp;\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|&nbsp;EF3&nbsp;\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|&nbsp;EF4&nbsp;\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|&nbsp;EF5&nbsp;\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|Deaths\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|Injuries\n|-\n|April&nbsp;25\n|align=\"right\"|42\n|align=\"right\"|17\n|align=\"right\"|20\n|align=\"right\"|4\n|align=\"right\"|1\n|align=\"right\"|0\n|align=\"right\"|0\n|align=\"right\"|5\n|align=\"right\"|59\n|-\n|April&nbsp;26\n|align=\"right\"|55\n|align=\"right\"|31\n|align=\"right\"|19\n|align=\"right\"|4\n|align=\"right\"|1\n|align=\"right\"|0\n|align=\"right\"|0\n|align=\"right\"|0\n|align=\"right\"|4\n|-\n|April&nbsp;27\n|align=\"right\"|216\n|align=\"right\"|68*\n|align=\"right\"|78\n|align=\"right\"|36\n|align=\"right\"|19\n|align=\"right\"|11\n|align=\"right\"|4\n|align=\"right\"|316\n|align=\"right\"|2,986+\n|-\n|April&nbsp;28\n|align=\"right\"|47\n|align=\"right\"|18\n|align=\"right\"|23\n|align=\"right\"|5\n|align=\"right\"|1\n|align=\"right\"|0\n|align=\"right\"|0\n|align=\"right\"|3\n|align=\"right\"|51\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| Total\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=#{{storm colour|unk}}  |'''360'''\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=#{{storm colour|storm}}|'''134'''*\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat1}} |'''140'''\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat2}} |'''49'''\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat3}} |'''22'''\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat4}} |'''11'''\n| align=\"center\" bgcolor=#{{storm colour|cat5}} |'''4'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''324'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''3,100+'''\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> One tornado touched down in [[Ontario, Canada]], on April 27 and was rated as an [[Fujita scale|F0]]. It is counted as an EF0 in this table.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0 0 0.5em 1em;float:right;\"\n|+ Outbreak death toll\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| State/Province\n! scope=\"col\"| Fatalities\n|-\n|[[Alabama]]\n|238\n|-\n|[[Arkansas]]\n|5\n|-\n|[[Georgia (U.S. State)|Georgia]]\n|14\n|-\n|[[Mississippi]]\n|31\n|-\n|[[Tennessee]]\n|32\n|-\n|[[Virginia]]\n|4\n|- style=\"background:#e6e9ff;\" \n||'''Totals'''\n||'''324'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{small|Only tornado-related deaths are included<br />(24 deaths were not caused by tornadoes)}}\n|}\n\n===Vilonia, Arkansas===\n[[File:Vilonia2011.jpg|thumb|left|255px|Remains of a mobile home that was destroyed by the Vilonia tornado.]] \n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF2\n| total fatalities = 4 fatalities, 16 injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nThe first tornado of the outbreak to cause more than one death was a long-tracked, high-end EF2 wedge tornado that struck the small town of [[Vilonia, Arkansas|Vilonia]] in [[Faulkner County, Arkansas]], around 7:30&nbsp;p.m. [[Central Time Zone|CDT]] (00:30 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]) on April 25.<ref name=\"NWSLittleRockApril27\">{{cite web|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Little Rock, Arkansas|date=June 7, 2011|accessdate=December 2, 2012|title=Heavy Rain/Severe Weather on April 23\u201327, 2011|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/lzk/?n=rain0411yr.htm}}</ref> A [[tornado warning]] was issued for the area roughly 30 minutes prior to the tornado's arrival, and the relatively low loss of life was attributed to this lead time.<ref name=\"TheCabin426\">{{cite web|author=Linda Hicks|publisher=[[Log Cabin Democrat]]|date=April 26, 2011|accessdate=April 27, 2011|title=Vilonia firefighter keep busy in cleanup efforts after storm|url=http://thecabin.net/news/local/2011-04-26/vilonia-firefighter-keep-busy-cleanup-efforts-after-storm}}</ref> A [[tornado emergency]] was declared at 7:24&nbsp;p.m. CDT (00:24 UTC) for the city shortly before the tornado struck.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Little Rock, Arkansas|date=April 25, 2011|accessdate=April 27, 2011|title=Tornado Emergency for Vilonia, Arkansas|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/vtec/#2011-O-NEW-KLZK-TO-W-0102|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110419050352/http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/vtec/|archivedate=April 19, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> Four people were killed in the town and many more were injured. The tornado touched down northwest of [[Ferndale, Arkansas|Ferndale]] in [[Pulaski County, Arkansas|Pulaski County]] at 6:48&nbsp;p.m. CDT (23:48 UTC), downing trees and transmission towers at EF1 intensity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=289605|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> It continued northeast of [[Natural Steps, Arkansas|Natural Steps]], severely damaging a small church and downing numerous trees, one of which landed on a house.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=289609|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> The tornado continued to knock down trees as it passed near [[Roland, Arkansas|Roland]], several of which landed on homes. The tornado reached EF2 strength as it crossed into Faulkner County and passed southeast of [[Mayflower, Arkansas|Mayflower]], downing numerous trees and power lines and damaging homes and outbuildings. Past Mayflower, it continued towards Vilonia and struck a mobile home park, where numerous mobile homes were destroyed and the four fatalities occurred. Two of the fatalities occurred when a couple attempted to take shelter in a cargo container, which was thrown {{convert|150|yd|m|}} and deposited near a pond. Several other people were injured in this area as well. The tornado maintained EF2 intensity as it moved directly through Vilonia, damaging numerous homes and businesses and flipping several semi-trucks. The [[American Red Cross]] indicated that approximately 34 site-built houses and 62 mobile homes were destroyed, 91 site-built homes and 41 mobile homes suffered major damage, 145 site-built houses and 43 mobile homes had minor damage, and 53 site-built houses and 38 mobile homes were affected in some other way in the Vilonia area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=289645|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> One of the mobile homes was picked up and flipped, and the home's two bathtubs were found over a hill about {{convert|40|yd|m|}} away. The lone occupant of the mobile home sustained major injuries.<ref>{{cite web|author=Linda Hicks|publisher=[[Arkansas Democrat-Gazette|ArkansasOnline]]|date=May 22, 2014|accessdate=June 20, 2014|title=Vilonia couple continue to recover from 2011 tornado|url=http://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2014/may/22/vilonia-couple-continue-recover-2011-tornado/}}</ref> After moving through Vilonia, the tornado weakened to EF1 strength as it moved into [[White County, Arkansas|White County]] and passed west of [[El Paso, Arkansas|El Paso]], where trees were blown over onto houses (damaging several roofs), barns and outbuildings were destroyed, an [[Recreational vehicle|RV]] and the trailer portion of a tractor-trailer were overturned, and hundreds of trees were downed. The tornado finally dissipated north of [[Joy, Arkansas|Joy]] at 7:59&nbsp;p.m. CDT (00:59 UTC), after having travelled just over {{convert|51|mi|km|}}. At its widest point, the tornado was {{convert|1.64|mi|km|}} wide.<ref name=\"TheCabin426\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=289615|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> Following the tornado, 85 members of the [[National Guard of the United States|U.S. National Guard]] were deployed to assist in search and rescue, debris clearing, security and traffic control.<ref>{{cite web|author=Lindsey Tugman |publisher=[[KTHV]] |date=April 26, 2011 |accessdate=April 27, 2011 |title=120 Guardsmen called to assist in Vilonia, Hot Springs Village |url=http://www.todaysthv.com/news/article/154941/2/120-Guardsmen-called-to-assist-in-Vilonia-Hot-Springs-Village |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429052340/http://www.todaysthv.com/news/article/154941/2/120-Guardsmen-called-to-assist-in-Vilonia-Hot-Springs-Village |archivedate=April 29, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nOn April 27, 2014, three years and two days after this tornado, [[April 27\u201330, 2014 tornado outbreak|a violent EF4 tornado]] touched down west of Ferndale and moved along almost the same path as this tornado, causing 16 fatalities and many injuries. However, it affected more of Mayflower than this tornado did and caused greater damage all along the path, especially in Vilonia, before lifting near El Paso.<ref name=\"NWSLittleRockApril27Vilonia\">{{cite web|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |work=National Weather Service in Little Rock, Arkansas |date=May 29, 2014 |accessdate=June 20, 2014 |title=Tornadoes/Flooding on April 27-28, 2014 |url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/lzk/?n=svr0414c.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502002121/http://www.srh.noaa.gov/lzk/?n=svr0414c.htm |archivedate=May 2, 2014 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Philadelphia\u2013Kemper County, Mississippi===\n{{Main|2011 Philadelphia, Mississippi tornado}}\n{{Infobox storm \n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF5\n| total fatalities = 3 fatalities, 8+ injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\n[[File:April 27, 2011 Mississippi tornado damage.jpg|thumb|right|A car that was thrown against a stand of trees by the Philadelphia tornado.]]\nThe first EF5 tornado of the outbreak touched down near the city of [[Philadelphia, Mississippi]], on April 27. The tornado touched down at 2:30&nbsp;p.m. CDT (19:30 UTC) and traveled for nearly {{convert|29|mi|km|}} through [[Neshoba County, Mississippi|Neshoba]], [[Kemper County, Mississippi|Kemper]], [[Winston County, Mississippi|Winston]], and [[Noxubee County, Mississippi|Noxubee Counties]], reaching a maximum width of a {{convert|1/2|mi|km|adj=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/mrx/?n=tor_outbreak_map|title=One Storm Amongst Many|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Morristown, Tennessee|date=April 27, 2012|accessdate=December 2, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Philadelphia, MS EF5 Survey\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/jan/?n=2011_04_25_27_neshoba_kemper_winston_noxubee|title=Neshoba/Kemper/Winston/Noxubee Counties Tornado|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Jackson, Mississippi|date=September 8, 2011|accessdate=December 2, 2012}}</ref> The tornado killed three people, injured eight others, and caused $1.1&nbsp;million in damage across its path.<ref name=\"Philadelphia, MS EF5 Survey\"/><ref>{{cite report|work=[[National Weather Service]] Office in Jackson, Mississippi|publisher=[[National Centers for Environmental Information]]|year=2011|accessdate=May 14, 2016|title=Mississippi Event Report: EF5 Tornado|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=309257}}\n*{{cite report|work=[[National Weather Service]] Office in Jackson, Mississippi|publisher=[[National Centers for Environmental Information]]|year=2011|accessdate=May 14, 2016|title=Mississippi Event Report: EF5 Tornado|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=309261}}\n*{{cite report|work=[[National Weather Service]] Office in Jackson, Mississippi|publisher=[[National Centers for Environmental Information]]|year=2011|accessdate=May 14, 2016|title=Mississippi Event Report: EF5 Tornado|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=309265}}\n*{{cite report|work=[[National Weather Service]] Office in Jackson, Mississippi|publisher=[[National Centers for Environmental Information]]|year=2011|accessdate=May 14, 2016|title=Mississippi Event Report: EF3 Tornado|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=309267}}</ref>\n\nThe supercell thunderstorm that produced this tornado formed around 1:00&nbsp;p.m. CDT south of [[Jackson, Mississippi]].<ref name=\"PhiladelphiaEF5_1\">{{cite report|author1=Eric Carpenter |author2=Greg Garrett |author3=Jared Allen |publisher=[[National Weather Service]] Office in Jackson, Mississippi |date=February 29, 2012 |accessdate=May 14, 2016 |title=A Storm-scale and Damage Survey Analysis of the East-Central Mississippi Violent Tornado of 27 April 2011 |url=http://www.nwas.org/committees/professionaldevelopment/NWAPD-2012-029_Carpenter_et_al.pdf |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130320054100/http://www.nwas.org/committees/professionaldevelopment/NWAPD-2012-029_Carpenter_et_al.pdf |archivedate=March 20, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Traveling briskly to the northeast, it warranted a severe thunderstorm warning within 25 minutes and was deemed potentially tornadic by 1:36&nbsp;p.m. CDT.<ref name=\"PhiladelphiaEF5_1\"/><ref>{{cite report|work=[[National Weather Service]] Office in Jackson, Mississippi|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet National Weather Service|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=May 14, 2016|title=Tornado Warning|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/vtec/#2011-O-NEW-KJAN-TO-W-0140/USCOMP-N0Q-201104271840}}</ref> A tornado finally touched down at 2:30&nbsp;p.m. CDT just east of the [[Philadelphia Municipal Airport]]. It quickly intensified and began producing EF5 damage by 2:38&nbsp;p.m. CDT; extreme ground scouring, up to {{convert|2|ft|m|}} deep in places, occurred in northeastern Neshoba County. After crossing into Kemper County, the tornado obliterated a mobile home, killing all three inside.<ref name=\"Philadelphia, MS EF5 Survey\"/> It reached EF5 strength a second time near the Kemper\u2013Winston county line where extreme ground scouring again took place and pavement was scoured.<ref name=\"Philadelphia, MS EF5 Survey\"/><ref name=\"PhiladelphiaEF5_1\"/> Extreme tree damage took place along the track and it ultimately dissipated at 3:00&nbsp;p.m. CDT about {{convert|6|mi|km|}} north of [[Mashulaville, Mississippi|Mashulaville]].<ref name=\"Philadelphia, MS EF5 Survey\"/>\n\nThis was the first tornado to cause F5/EF5 damage in [[Mississippi]] since the [[Candlestick Park tornado]] on March 3, 1966. Additionally, the formation of the [[Smithville, Mississippi|Smithville]] tornado later that day marked the first time since statistics have been kept that two EF5 tornadoes have been recorded in Mississippi on the same day. Prior to this, the last confirmed EF5 tornado was the [[Parkersburg Tornado|Parkersburg, Iowa tornado]] on May 25, 2008.<ref name=\"Philadelphia, MS EF5 Survey\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Cullman/Arab, Alabama===\n[[File:Cullman Alabama First Methodist Church Damage.jpg|thumb|left|255px|Damage to the First Methodist Church in downtown [[Cullman, Alabama]].]]\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF4\n| total fatalities = 6 fatalities, 48+ injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nRated EF4, this highly visible multiple-vortex tornado tracked directly through downtown Cullman.<ref name=\"Long Track Tornado Hits Cullman, Alabama\">{{cite news|url=http://okcstormwatcher.wordpress.com/2011/04/27/tornado-emergency-for-cullman-alabama/|publisher=OKC Storm Watcher|title=Long Track Tornado Hits Cullman, Alabama (4/27/2011)|accessdate=April 30, 2011|date=April 30, 2011}}</ref> The tornado touched down at 2:40&nbsp;p.m. CDT (19:40 UTC) on April 27 and tracked a {{convert|47|mi|km|adj=on}} damage path through [[Cullman County, Alabama|Cullman]], [[Morgan County, Alabama|Morgan]], and [[Marshall County, Alabama|Marshall Counties]], causing six deaths.<ref name=\"April 27, 2011 Cullman, Alabama EF4 Tornado\">{{cite news|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=4272011_cullman_county|title=Cullman (AL)/Morgan (AL)/Marshall (AL) EF4 Tornado|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service Huntsville, Alabama|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=March 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Cullman tornado first touched down on the north side of [[Lewis Smith Lake]] and caused light structural damage near [[Crane Hill, Alabama|Crane Hill]] before intensifying and tracking directly towards Cullman, snapping numerous trees and heavily damaging several homes.\n\nThe tornado became violent as it entered Cullman, being tracked and broadcast live via several tower cameras, including one operated by [[WBMA-LD|''ABC 33/40'']] for several minutes; that camera captured the destruction of a communications tower belonging to Cullman area [[Low-power broadcasting|low-power]] television station [[WCQT-LP]] as the tornado ripped through the city. Radio stations in downtown Cullman also reported on the tornado and some even captured it passing over until power was knocked out.<ref name=\"Long Track Tornado Hits Cullman, Alabama\"/> Downtown Cullman was badly damaged by the tornado, with the major damage being along a two-block area through the center of the downtown business district. Numerous well-built brick buildings and storefronts in downtown Cullman were heavily damaged or completely destroyed, along with churches. The courthouse and nearby emergency management building took a direct hit from the tornado, sustaining considerable damage, and two school buildings were heavily damaged as well. Many well-known businesses, such as Vincent's Furniture, ''[[The Cullman Times]]'', and the Busy Bee Cafe, were also severely damaged/destroyed. Many homes were damaged or destroyed in residential areas of the city, with extensive tree and power line damage noted as well. In all, a total of 867 residences and 94 businesses within the city of Cullman were damaged or destroyed.<ref name=\"Long Track Tornado Hits Cullman, Alabama\"/>\n\n[[File:Cullman2011EF4.JPG|thumb|Major structural damage to businesses in downtown Cullman.]]\nThe tornado, more or less, followed [[U.S. Route 278|U.S. Highway 278]] through the city, in which it created extensive damage along many major intersections, including those with [[Interstate 65 in Alabama|Interstate 65]], [[U.S. Route 31 in Alabama|U.S. Highway 31]], and [[Alabama State Route 157|Alabama State Routes 157]] and [[Alabama State Route 69|69]].<ref name=\"April 27, 2011 Cullman, Alabama EF4 Tornado\"/>\n\nThe tornado continued northeast, becoming large and wedge-shaped. It then passed just north of [[Fairview, Alabama|Fairview]], completely destroying homes and debarking numerous hardwood trees. Pieces of debris were found speared through vehicles in this area.<ref name=\"April 27, 2011 Cullman, Alabama EF4 Tornado\"/> The tornado then briefly passed through a section of [[Morgan County, Alabama|Morgan County]] near the town of [[Hulaco, Alabama|Hulaco]], destroying several older block-foundation homes and snapping numerous large trees off at the base. The tornado then crossed into [[Marshall County, Alabama|Marshall County]] and impacted the rural community of [[Ruth, Alabama|Ruth]], just north of [[Arab, Alabama|Arab]]. A large but poorly-anchored brick home was swept completely away in this area, with the debris scattered 100 yards from the foundation. Several large trees on the property were ripped out of the ground and missing, along with a trailer that was unable to be located at the time of the survey. Other homes and structures were impacted in the Ruth area, and a gas station was completely destroyed. A shed was destroyed with pieces of large farm machinery stored inside thrown up to 20 yards away, a storage trailer was tossed 100 yards and found impaled by planks of wood, and steel power poles in the area were bent over. Arab's power grid was completely crippled by the tornado's effects, and many roads in the area were obstructed by downed trees and power lines. The tornado damaged and destroyed several other homes, garages, and sheds north of [[Union Grove, Alabama|Union Grove]] before it crossed the [[Tennessee River]], snapping numerous trees in a forested area before dissipating.<ref name=\"April 27, 2011 Cullman, Alabama EF4 Tornado\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Hackleburg\u2013Phil Campbell\u2013Tanner\u2013Harvest, Alabama/Huntland, Tennessee===\n{{Main|2011 Hackleburg\u2013Phil Campbell tornado}}\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF5\n| total fatalities = 72 fatalities, 145+ injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\n[[File:Phil Campbell tornado damage2.jpg|thumb|EF5 damage in Phil Campbell, with homes swept away and grass scoured from hillsides.]]\nThis devastating, long-tracked, violent EF5 wedge tornado was the deadliest of the outbreak. It first touched down in [[Marion County, Alabama]] about {{convert|5|mi|km}} west-southwest of [[Hamilton, Alabama|Hamilton]] around 3:00&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2100 UTC) on April 27, leaving massive damage along its track. The storm would eventually reach the [[Hackleburg, Alabama|Hackleburg]] area, completely leveling many homes and businesses, including a large [[Wrangler (Jeans)|Wrangler, Inc.]] factory. Most of the structures in downtown Hackleburg were badly damaged and Hackleburg High School was destroyed. Well-built homes were wiped cleanly from their foundations, extensive wind-rowing of debris occurred, trees were completely debarked, and cars were thrown hundreds of yards. According to the [[American Red Cross]], 75 percent of the town was destroyed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2011/05/03/135936478/in-small-towns-hit-by-twisters-you-feel-ignored|title=In Small Towns Hit By Twisters, 'You Feel Ignored'|work=[[NPR|National Public Radio]]|publisher=[[Corporation for Public Broadcasting]]|date=May 3, 2011|accessdate=May 25, 2011|author=Tayna Ott}}</ref> While initially rated as an EF3, the rating was increased to EF5 after further analysis of the damage, making it the first F5/EF5 tornado in Alabama since the [[April 1998 Birmingham tornado|Birmingham tornado of April 8, 1998]].<ref name=\"Marion survey\">{{cite web|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=201104302306|title=Updated For Increase In Hackleburg Tornado Rating To EF-5|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Birmingham, Alabama|date=April 30, 2011|accessdate=May 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Waff Tower Cam.jpg|thumb|left|Hackleburg/Phil Campbell EF5 tornado capture on [[WAFF (TV)|WAFF]]'s tower cam before it crossed [[US-72]] in [[Limestone County, Alabama]].]]\nSoon after crossing into [[Franklin County, Alabama|Franklin County]],  the town of [[Phil Campbell, Alabama|Phil Campbell]] experienced significant devastation of the same magnitude as Hackleburg. Numerous homes, some of which were well-constructed, were swept away as the tornado tore through town. At least three churches along the path sustained significant damage, with one church in the town being completely destroyed and having only the foundation slab remaining. Mobile homes throughout the path were completely destroyed, and their mangled frames were tossed at least {{convert|25|to|50|yd|m}}. Cars were tossed and destroyed throughout the path of the tornado, with one car wrapped around a debarked tree. A {{convert|25|ft|m|adj=on}} section of pavement was torn from a road in this area as well. The most intense damage along the path occurred northeast of Phil Campbell in the rural community of Oak Grove, where vehicles were carried long distances and mangled beyond recognition, large trees were completely debarked, and large brick homes with extensive anchoring were obliterated with the debris wind-rowed hundreds of yards away. The tornado continued into [[Lawrence County, Alabama|Lawrence County]], impacting the [[Mount Hope, Lawrence County, Alabama|Mount Hope]] community, where significant devastation was incurred to single-family homes and a restaurant. Nothing but the foundation and a pile of debris remained at the restaurant site, and a small portion of the restaurant's foundation slab buckled.<ref name=\"Huntsville EF5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=franklin-al_lawrence_limestone_madison_franklin-tn_counties|title=Franklin (AL) / Lawrence / Morgan / Limestone / Madison / Franklin (TN) EF-5|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=May 1, 2011|accessdate=May 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:PhilCampbellPavementScouring.JPG|thumb|left|255px|Large area of pavement scoured from a road in Phil Campbell.]]\nThe tornado moved northeast, producing EF3 damage in and around [[Langtown, Alabama|Langtown]]. The tornado re-intensified to EF4 strength as it passed near [[Moulton, Alabama|Moulton]] and [[Trinity, Alabama|Trinity]], debarking trees, mangling, and leveling homes. It then continued through the northwest corner of [[Morgan County, Alabama|Morgan County]], crossed Wheeler Lake, and moved into [[Limestone County, Alabama|Limestone County]], coming within {{convert|2|mi|km}} of [[Browns Ferry Nuclear Power Plant]]. The tornado caused power outages in the area, and the plant had to be shut down. The tornado continued towards the small community of Tanner.<ref name=\"NWS-HUN-SWS-04282141\">{{cite web|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSHUN&e=201104290231|title=Preliminary Storm Survey Information From Limestone And Madison Counties|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"TFP-nuke\">{{cite news|author=Pam Sohn|title=TVA loses all power transmission lines in Alabama and Mississippi, Browns Ferry Nuclear plant forced into emergency shutdow|url=http://timesfreepress.com/news/2011/apr/28/tva-losses-all-power-transmission-lines-alabama-an/|accessdate=April 28, 2011|publisher=[[Chattanooga Times Free Press]]|date=April 28, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521065159/http://timesfreepress.com/news/2011/apr/28/tva-losses-all-power-transmission-lines-alabama-an/|archivedate=May 21, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref><ref name=\"HUN-132.1mi\">{{cite web|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSHUN&e=201105020259|title=Long Track EF-5 Tornado Confirmed Across The Tennessee Valley|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=May 2, 2011|accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref> [[Tanner, Alabama|Tanner]]  experienced a large swath of EF4 damage and a narrow corridor of \"high-end EF4 to near-EF5 damage\". The storm \"completely wiped clean\" several well constructed homes with anchor bolting.<ref name=\"NWS-HUN-SWS-04282141\"/> As the storm crossed [[U.S. Route 72|U.S. Highway 72]] in eastern Limestone County, the tornado destroyed a [[Doppler weather radar|Doppler radar]] operated by [[NBC]] affiliate [[WAFF (TV)|WAFF]] (channel 48) and continued into East Limestone, a heavily populated area of Limestone County where homes in subdivisions were damaged or destroyed at high-end EF3 strength. As the storm crossed into Madison County, it approached the densely populated suburban communities of [[Harvest, Alabama|Harvest]] and [[Toney, Alabama|Toney]], where it either damaged or destroyed hundreds of homes, especially in the Anderson Hills and Carter's Gin subdivisions. Many homes were reduced to rubble, and the damage in this area was rated mainly EF3 with a small pocket of EF4 damage in Harvest. The tornado completely destroyed a [[Piggly Wiggly]] grocery store in Harvest and severely damaged a convenience store and local bank, which was shut down for months following the event.<ref name=\"SWDJW-04272011ToneyHarvestDestruction\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.al.com/breaking/2011/04/at_least_7_dead_scores_injured.html|title=Harvest & Toney, AL Destruction|publisher=[[The Birmingham News|AL.com]]|date=July 9, 2011|accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> The storm progressed across Pulaski Pike in northwest Madison County, damaging many homes. In all, hundreds of homes received moderate to major damage along the path from Limestone to Madison County with many of these being total losses.<ref name=\"NWS-HUN-SWS-04282141\"/>\n\nThe tornado then moved into [[Tennessee]] and continued south of [[Huntland, Tennessee|Huntland]]. Isolated and minor EF0 to EF1 damage was noted through most of its path in Tennessee. Widespread damage to trees and outbuildings occurred in this area. The worst damage, however, was to a cinder block utility building and was rated lower-end EF3. Most of its roof was removed, with over half of its downwind wall pushed outward. The tornado eventually dissipated east of Huntland.<ref name=\"HUN-132.1mi\"/>\n\nIn total, this tornado killed 72 people, all in Alabama.<ref name=\"spc fatal\"/> This made it the deadliest single tornado ever to strike the state of Alabama as well as (at the time) the deadliest in the United States since the 1955 [[Udall, Kansas]] tornado that killed 80 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crh.noaa.gov/ict/udall/udall.php|title=The Udall Kansas Tornado: May 25, 1955|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=August 31, 2010|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.noaa.gov/faq/tornado/killers.html|title=The 25 Deadliest U.S. Tornadoes|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=Storm Prediction Center|accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref> In addition to being the deadliest, this tornado also had the longest track of any tornado in the outbreak, with its path extending {{convert|132.1|mi|km}} across Northern Alabama and into Tennessee.<ref name=\"HUN-132.1mi\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Reform\u2013Oakman\u2013Cordova\u2013Blountsville, Alabama===\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF4\n| total fatalities = 13 fatalities, 54+ injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\n[[File:Cordovafromwest.jpg|thumb|right|Aerial view of the damage path through Cordova from the west (looking east).]]\nThe tornado touched down at 3:40 PM CDT in northeastern [[Pickens County, Alabama]], damaging a few chicken homes at EF1 strength. The tornado caused roof damage to houses and destroyed a few outbuildings before moving into [[Tuscaloosa County, Alabama|Tuscaloosa County]] and briefly into [[Fayette County, Alabama|Fayette County]], causing major EF2 tree damage and minor structural damage. The tornado then moved back into Tuscaloosa County, causing mostly minor tree and structural damage at EF1 strength before rapidly intensifying and crossing into Fayette County once again. There, it completely destroyed at least one mobile home, with the frame being separated and the remaining debris being thrown a considerable distance. The tornado appeared to strengthen even further and several mobile homes were completely obliterated with debris thrown a considerable distance and frames twisted and thrown. Damage was rated EF3 in this area. Many trees were downed as well before the tornado moved into [[Walker County, Alabama|Walker County]]. It then weakened to EF1 strength and caused mostly minor damage to trees and mobile homes. South of [[Oakman, Alabama|Oakman]], numerous trees were snapped and uprooted, a cell phone tower was knocked down, and mobile homes were destroyed at EF2 intensity. It then rolled vehicles and destroyed a cinder block house to the southeast of Oakman, with damage rated EF3 at that location. The tornado weakened considerably as it approached [[Interstate 22|Corridor X]] of the [[Appalachian Development Highway System]], with only minor EF0 tree damage, before it strengthened significantly as it entered the town of [[Cordova, Alabama|Cordova]] as a {{convert|0.5|mi|km|adj=on}} wide EF3.<ref name=\"Cordova tornado\">{{cite web|title=Cordova (Pickens, Tuscaloosa, Fayette, Walker and Blount Counties) EF-4 Tornado April 27, 2011|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/bmx/?n=event_04272011cordova|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Birmingham, Alabama|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:CordovaDamagefromGround.jpg|thumb|right|Major damage in a residential area of Cordova.]]\nIn Cordova, numerous homes and manufactured houses were either damaged or destroyed in this area along with many trees being downed. Some unanchored homes in town were swept from their foundations. Buildings in downtown Cordova had already been damaged by an EF3 tornado earlier that morning and received further damage from this tornado. East of Cordova, the tornado crossed the [[Mulberry Fork of the Black Warrior River]] three times (along with the [[Sipsey Fork of the Black Warrior River|Sipsey Fork]] once, just north of its confluence with the Mulberry Fork). It intensified further into a violent EF4 in northeastern Walker County, as it completely leveled a site-built home and obliterated two nearby mobile homes. One of the mobile home undercarriages was tossed at least {{convert|500|yd|m|}}. A 5-ton bulldozer was flipped over, a pickup truck was tossed {{convert|200|yd|m|}}, and a dump truck was tossed {{convert|50|yd|m|}} and destroyed. A two-ton trailer was thrown {{convert|1|mi|km|}} and left a {{convert|2.5|ft|m|adj=on}} deep crater where it impacted the ground. Two double-wide mobile homes were tossed at least {{convert|100|yd|m|}}, and a third mobile home was tossed {{convert|100|yd|m|}} up a {{convert|50|foot|m|}} embankment and destroyed along this segment of the path as well. South of [[Sipsey, Alabama|Sipsey]], additional homes and mobile homes were destroyed at EF2 to EF3 strength and numerous trees were snapped.<ref name=\"Cordova tornado\"/>\n\nThe tornado then crossed the Mulberry Fork for the fourth time and moved into [[Cullman County, Alabama|Cullman County]]. South of [[Arkadelphia, Alabama|Arkadelphia]], a second area of EF4 damage was observed, as a cinder block construction home was leveled and a car was thrown {{convert|130|yd|m|}}. Nearby, an underground storm shelter collapsed onto the occupants sheltering inside as the tornado passed overhead.<ref name=\"Cordova tornado\"/> The tornado then crossed the Mulberry Fork again, moving into [[Blount County, Alabama|Blount County]], where it caused EF1 roof damage to a home and snapped hundreds of trees. It then crossed [[Interstate 65 in Alabama|Interstate 65]] before crossing the Mulberry Fork into Cullman County southwest of [[Garden City, Alabama|Garden City]], snapping numerous additional trees at EF1 strength. It quickly crossed the river again (the seventh crossing), moving back into Blount County. As it continued to the south-southwest of Garden City, it straddled the Mulberry Fork before finally moving solidly into Blount County and toward [[Blountsville, Alabama|Blountsville]]. On the southeast side of Blountsville, the tornado downed many trees and caused high-end EF2 damage to well-built brick and slab foundation homes, one of which had some exterior walls collapse. The storm continued to the northeast and out of Blountsville, where two additional homes sustained high-end EF3 damage. A large portion of one of the homes was wiped off of its foundation; however, its garage sustained only minor roof damage. At the second of these two homes, a dump truck was thrown {{convert|30|ft|m|}}.<ref name=\"Cordova tornado\"/> The tornado then moved into [[Marshall County, Alabama|Marshall County]], causing significant damage to a house and downing numerous trees. A shed suffered roof damage and an industrial plant was completely destroyed at EF2 strength as well. The tornado then moved into a wooded area, weakened, and eventually lifted south-southwest of [[Guntersville, Alabama|Guntersville]] at 5:56&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2256 UTC). Thousands of trees were downed along the tornado's path.<ref name=\"Marshall County survey\">{{cite web|title=Marshall County (The End of the Long Track Tornado \u2013 Ending East of Hwy 79 and South of Hwy 431) EF-2|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=4272011_marshall_longtrackend|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=October 2, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThis tornado was on the ground for two hours and sixteen minutes, tracking for {{convert|127.8|mi|km}} across seven counties. It was rated as a low-end EF4 with winds of {{convert|170|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}. In total, 13 people were killed and 54 others were injured.<ref name=\"Cordova tornado\"/><ref name=\"Marshall County survey\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Smithville, Mississippi/Shottsville, Alabama===\n{{Main|2011 Smithville, Mississippi tornado}}\n\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF5\n| total fatalities = 23 fatalities, 137 injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nThis extremely violent EF5 wedge tornado, with estimated winds of up to {{convert|205|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, struck the town of [[Smithville, Mississippi]], at 3:47&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2047 UTC) on April 27, resulting in catastrophic damage and numerous fatalities.<ref name=\"NWSMemphisSmithvilleEF5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/meg/?n=apr2011toroutbreaksmithville|title=Smithville, MS EF-5 Tornado|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Memphis, Tennessee|date=May 30, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> The tornado began {{convert|3|mi|km|}} west-southwest of Smithville along the [[Tennessee\u2013Tombigbee Waterway]] near the [[Glover Wilkins Lock]] at 3:42&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2042 UTC), snapping numerous trees near the Smithville Recreation Area. The tornado then rapidly intensified as it approached town, reaching EF5 intensity. As the storm crossed Davis Road South, the ground was deeply scoured in a nearby field.<ref name=\"Smith. Damage Imagery\">{{cite web|url=http://ngs.woc.noaa.gov/storms/apr11_tornado/|title=April 2011 Tornado Response Imagery|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Geodetic Survey|year=2011|accessdate=June 20, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131229064349/http://ngs.woc.noaa.gov/storms/apr11_tornado/|archive-date=December 29, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The tornado swept away numerous homes and structures as it moved northeast, following [[Mississippi Highway 25|Highway 25]]. A semi-truck was thrown a considerable distance and destroyed in this area, and at one residence that was swept away, part of the concrete foundation slab was pulled up and dislodged slightly.<ref name=\"NWSMemphisSmithvilleEF5\"/><ref name=\"Smith. Damage Imagery\"/> Multiple well-anchored brick homes were completely swept away, and a large brick funeral home was reduced to a bare slab as the tornado exited at the northeast side of town, with the debris scattered and wind-rowed into an adjacent wooded area. Nearby granite tombstones were blown over in the opposite direction of the tornado's passage. Overall, the tornado destroyed 117 structures in Smithville and damaged 50 others, killing 16 people.<ref name=\"Smithville NCDC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=303562|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|author=National Climatic Data Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|year=2011|accessdate=June 13, 2014}}</ref> The tornado weakened as it continued through rural areas northeast of town and moved into [[Itawamba County, Mississippi|Itawamba County]], where it downed numerous trees and power lines and caused roof damage to a house before exiting the county.<ref name=\"Smith. Damage Imagery\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=303563|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|author=National Climatic Data Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|year=2011|accessdate=June 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe tornado continued across the [[Alabama]] state line into [[Marion County, Alabama|Marion County]], where it caused EF1-strength damage near [[Bexar, Alabama|Bexar]]. Continuing northeast, the tornado re-intensified as it struck the rural community of [[Shottsville, Alabama|Shottsville]] at high-end EF3 intensity, where homes and mobile homes were destroyed and seven people were killed, and it produced additional high-end EF3 damage as it continued north of [[Hamilton, Alabama|Hamilton]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=4272011_franklin_county_hodges|title=Franklin County Alabama (Hodges Area) EF-2|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=June 5, 2012|accessdate=July 20, 2014}}</ref> More structures were impacted as the tornado approached and crossed into [[Franklin County, Alabama|Franklin County]]. The tornado then dissipated near the town of [[Hodges, Alabama|Hodges]] at 4:23&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2123 UTC). The damage path was {{convert|37.3|mi|km}} long and {{convert|3/4|mi|km|}} wide at its widest point, and it killed a total of 23 people along its path. 137 other people were injured.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/bmx/?n=event_04272011shotsville|title=Shottsville (Marion County) EF-3 Tornado April 27, 2011|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Birmingham, Alabama|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Pisgah\u2013Flat Rock\u2013Higdon, Alabama/Trenton, Georgia===\n[[File:Trenton2011.JPG|thumb|left|255px|Aerial view of damage in Trenton.]]\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF4\n| total fatalities = 14 fatalities, 50+ injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nThis multiple-vortex EF4 tornado devastated portions of [[Jackson County, Alabama|Jackson]] and [[DeKalb County, Alabama|DeKalb]] counties in Alabama, as well as [[Dade County, Georgia|Dade]] and [[Walker County, Georgia|Walker]] counties in Georgia along a {{convert|47|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} path, killing 14 people and injuring at least 50 others.<ref name=\"NOAA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=04272011_jackson_northern-dekalb |title=Eastern Jackson (AL) / Northern De kalb (AL) - EF-4 (Section to Flat Rock to GA) |date=February 15, 2012 |website=NWS Huntsville, AL |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=June 15, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Storm Events Database\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=304631 |title=Storm Events Database |website=NCDC |publisher=NCDC |accessdate=June 15, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ncdc.noaa.gov\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=304667 |title=Storm Events Database |website=NCDC |publisher=NCDC |accessdate=June 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe tornado touched down north of [[Section, Alabama|Section]], initially producing EF0 to EF1 tree damage. The tornado rapidly intensified to low-end EF4 strength as it passed northwest of [[Pisgah, Alabama|Pisgah]] and [[Rosalie, Alabama|Rosalie]], destroying numerous mobile homes and block foundation homes, scattering the debris hundreds of yards and killing three people. Thousands of trees were snapped and debarked, vehicles were thrown up to 50 yards in different directions, and barns and chicken houses were heavily damaged, along with the roof of a church.<ref name=\"NOAA\"/> As it passed near [[Flat Rock, Alabama|Flat Rock]] and [[Higdon, Alabama|Higdon]], the tornado reached high-end EF4 strength, mowing down thousands of trees in this rural area. As the tornado struck a farm, a home and two chicken houses were completely obliterated and swept away. A heavy propane tank was lofted and thrown 100 yards from one of the chicken houses, and 19 cattle on the property were killed. Remarkably, a family of four taking shelter inside the house were completely unharmed.<ref name=\"NOAA\"/> The tornado maintained EF4 strength as it tore through the rural community of Shiloh, sweeping away numerous mobile homes and block foundation homes and killing 5 people at that location. Thousands of trees were snapped, a log cabin was destroyed, livestock was killed, chicken houses were flattened, and a van was lofted and dropped into a field 400 yards away from where it originated.<ref name=\"NOAA\"/> The tornado then crossed into Georgia and struck [[Trenton, Georgia|Trenton]] as an EF3, killing two people. Dozens of homes in Trenton were completely destroyed, 18 others sustained major damage, and tens of thousands of trees were downed in the area. A grocery store, two apartment complexes, and a funeral home were destroyed as well.<ref name=\"Storm Events Database\"/>\n\nThe tornado weakened to EF2 strength as it struck [[Flintstone, Georgia|Flintstone]] further to the northeast, but still resulted in major damage. Numerous trees and power lines were downed, 7 homes were destroyed, 26 sustained major damage, and 35 sustained minor damage in the Flintstone area. The tornado continued northeast, weakening to EF0 strength before finally dissipating near [[Fort Oglethorpe, Georgia|Fort Oglethorpe]].<ref name=\"ncdc.noaa.gov\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Tuscaloosa/Birmingham, Alabama===\n{{Main|2011 Tuscaloosa\u2013Birmingham tornado}}\n[[File:Tornado Track in Tuscaloosa, Alabama.jpg|thumb|left|170px|Satellite image of the tornado's track through Tuscaloosa.]]\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF4\n| total fatalities = 64 fatalities, ~1,500 injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nA large multiple-vortex [[wedge tornado]] touched down in rural [[Greene County, Alabama]], and tracked across neighboring [[Tuscaloosa County, Alabama|Tuscaloosa County]], including the southern and eastern portions of [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]] at around 5:10&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2210 UTC) on April 27.<ref name=\"massive\">{{cite news|first1=Enjoli|last1=Francis|first2=Jeremy|last2=Hubbard|first3=Leezel|last3=Tanglao|publisher=[[ABC News]]|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/massive-tornado-hits-alabama-storms-leave-16-dead/story?id=13465028|title=Storms, Tornadoes Leave Dozens Dead in Alabama, Mississippi, Georgia and Tennessee|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=April 28, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110428040702/http://abcnews.go.com/US/massive-tornado-hits-alabama-storms-leave-16-dead/story?id=13465028|archivedate=April 28, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref><ref name=\"NWSBir.Tusc.Survey\">{{cite web|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Birmingham, Alabama|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/bmx/?n=event_04272011tuscbirm|title=Tuscaloosa-Birmingham EF-4 Tornado April 27, 2011|year=2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> Debris from the tornado was reported to be falling from the sky across [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]] over {{convert|20|mi|km}} away in [[Jefferson County, Alabama|Jefferson County]]. Skycams operated by Tuscaloosa television station [[WVUA-CD|WVUA-CA]] (channel 7) as well as Birmingham [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] affiliate [[WBRC]] (channel 6), [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] affiliate [[WBMA-LD]]/[[WCFT-TV]]/[[WJSU-TV]] (channels 58, 33, and 40), and [[CBS]] affiliate [[WIAT]] (channel 42) captured live footage of the tornado as it struck Tuscaloosa; WIAT received awards, including a regional [[Edward R. Murrow Award (Radio Television Digital News Association)|Edward R. Murrow Award]] for \"Outstanding Live Coverage\" of the event).<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[WOFL]] |url=http://www.myfoxorlando.com/video?clipId=7236537&autostart=true |title=VIDEO: Alabama tornado |date=April 28, 2011 |accessdate=July 15, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225183242/http://www.myfoxorlando.com/video?clipId=7236537&autostart=true |archivedate=December 25, 2013 |df= }}</ref> As the tornado traveled east to 35th Street and Kauloosa Avenue, the Tuscaloosa Environmental Services and [[Cintas]] facilities suffered severe damage. Numerous homes and apartment buildings in the Rosedale and Forest Lake neighborhoods, as well as a P&P Grocery store in Rosedale, were devastated. Several stores and restaurants in a business district at the intersection of McFarland Boulevard and 15th Street, near the DCH Regional Medical Center, were reduced to rubble. Buildings on 35th Street, between [[Interstate 359]] and Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard, were also completely destroyed. The Alberta City neighborhood in eastern Tuscaloosa sustained catastrophic damage as numerous homes, apartment buildings, and a shopping center were completely leveled. Additional high-end EF4 damage occurred in the Tuscaloosa suburb of [[Holt, Alabama|Holt]] further to the northeast, as several homes were leveled or swept away in that area. The tornado then exited the Tuscaloosa area and moved through dense forest towards Birmingham, downing and debarking thousands of trees.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Tuscaloosa News|url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20110427/NEWS/110429711?Title=AFTERMATH--Accounts-of-the-Tuscaloosa-tornado|title=THE AFTERMATH: Staff accounts of the tornado|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[University of Alabama]] shut down its campus briefly during the course of the storm itself, resuming regular activities within minutes. Upon realizing the extent of the storm damage immediately off-campus, including areas of off-campus student housing, the university shut down all academic and extracurricular activities for the remainder of the day, and then, still later, for the remaining ten days of the academic semester. All final exams were cancelled, with all registered students receiving a final grade based on their grade as of the day of the storm. Spring commencement ceremonies were postponed until August 6. The University itself was undamaged by the storm, though six students enrolled at the University were later discovered to have perished.<ref>{{cite web|title=Closings|url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20110428/NEWS/110429643|publisher=Tuscaloosa News|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Radar image of the 2011 Tuscaloosa tornado April 27, 2011 2210Z.png|thumb|250px|Radar and velocity image of the supercell that produced the tornado at 22:10&nbsp;UTC (5:12&nbsp;p.m. CDT) as it struck Tuscaloosa, with a [[debris ball]] clearly visible.]]\n[[File:Tuscaloosa Apartment Complex.JPG|thumb|left|The demolished Chastain Manor apartment complex in Tuscaloosa.]]\nMany stations, including WIAT, WBMA/WCFT/WJSU, [[WTVY (TV)|WTVY]] (channel 4) in [[Dothan, Alabama|Dothan]] and [[WSFA]] (channel 12) in [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], showed television cameras capturing the event as the tornado moved east-northeast across the western and northern suburbs of Birmingham around 6:00&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2300 UTC). Several suburbs in the area were severely damaged by the massive tornado as it tore through the west side of Birmingham, resulting in fatalities. The suburbs of [[Concord, Alabama|Concord]], [[Pleasant Grove, Alabama|Pleasant Grove]], and [[McDonald Chapel, Alabama|McDonald Chapel]] were devastated by the tornado as it moved northeast, flattening entire neighborhoods. As the tornado entered the Birmingham city limits, it devastated the [[Pratt City, Alabama|Pratt City]] neighborhood, destroying numerous homes and apartment buildings. The tornado then struck the suburb of [[Fultondale, Alabama|Fultondale]], causing EF2 damage to homes and businesses before dissipating east of Fultondale.<ref name=\"NWSBir.Tusc.Survey\"/><ref>{{cite web|first1=Tim|last1=Ballisty|first2=Chris|last2=Dolce|first3=Jonathan|last3=Erdman|publisher=[[Weather Channel|Weather.com]]|url=http://www.weather.com/outlook/weather-news/news/articles/severe-weather-tracker-april22-26_2011-04-22|title=Severe Weather: Track the Storms|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=April 27, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110510131036/http://www.weather.com/outlook/weather-news/news/articles/severe-weather-tracker-april22-26_2011-04-22|archivedate=May 10, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> Surveys indicated high-end EF4 damage from the tornado in Birmingham's western suburbs.<ref name=\"NWSBir.Tusc.Survey\"/>\n\nThe [[National Weather Service]] determined the path length of this violent tornado to be {{convert|80.7|mi|km}} with a maximum damage path width of {{convert|1.5|mi|km}}. The tornado's most intense damage indicated peak winds of around {{convert|190|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}; therefore, it was given a final rating of EF4. Reports from Tuscaloosa indicated 44 people were killed, with an additional 20 deaths in Birmingham.<ref name=\"NWSBir.Tusc.Survey\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=City says 44 deaths attributed to tornado|url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20110708/NEWS/110709754|publisher=Tuscaloosa News|date=June 8, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> Overall this tornado killed 64 people and injured more than 1500.<ref name=\"spc fatal\"/><ref name=\"NWSBir.Tusc.Survey\"/> [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] and [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Michelle Obama]] visited Tuscaloosa on April 29, taking a ground tour of some of the affected areas. Obama was quoted as saying that he had \"never seen devastation like this.\" He stated further that he had already declared a federal state of emergency in Alabama.<ref name=\"nprttown\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2011/04/29/135842102/obama-in-tuscaloosa-ive-never-seen-devastation-like-this|title=Obama In Tuscaloosa: 'I've Never Seen Devastation Like This'|author=Eyder Peralta|date=April 29, 2011|work=National Public Radio|publisher=Corporation for Public Broadcasting|accessdate=April 29, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110502172806/http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2011/04/29/135842102/obama-in-tuscaloosa-ive-never-seen-devastation-like-this|archivedate= May 2, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Fackler\u2013Stevenson\u2013Bridgeport, Alabama/Haletown, Tennessee===\n[[File:Bridgeport, AL April 27 tornado damage.jpg|thumb|left|Concrete steps that were ripped from the foundation of a house, with a small concrete porch slab pulled up in the background.]]\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF4\n| total fatalities = 1 fatality\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nThis EF4 tornado, with winds of up to {{convert|180|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, touched down just northeast of the community of [[Fackler, Alabama|Fackler]] at 5:05&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2205 UTC) on April 27, initially causing minor damage to mobile homes and downing trees. The tornado then moved northeast toward [[Stevenson, Alabama|Stevenson]], where large trees were downed, several roofs were damaged, a trailer was tipped over, and a shed was partially destroyed. It then reached EF3 intensity, and 24 metal high-tension truss towers were twisted and flattened northeast of [[Stevenson Airport]]. In this area, a mobile home was obliterated and a site-built house was collapsed. Two other homes sustained structural damage, two mobile homes were rolled on their side, and a metal barn was destroyed as well. The tornado then continued to the northeast and reached EF4 strength, with the most significant damage being located near the intersection of County Roads 255 and 256. Here, a home was reduced to its foundation, a concrete slab at the front of the home was pulled up, and a set of concrete stairs was ripped from the foundation. A compact car was thrown about {{convert|50|yd|m|}} as well.<ref name=\"Fackler tornado\">{{cite web|title=Jackson County (Bridgeport Area) EF-4|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=04272011_jackson|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=June 26, 2012|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"FacklerNCDC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=301882|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nContinuing, the tornado reduced two more well-built and well-anchored homes to their block foundations and threw another car approximately {{convert|50|yd|m|}}. Several large trees were snapped off just above the ground, a third home was left with no walls standing, and a mobile home was completely demolished and strewn along County Road 256 as well. The tornado continued northeastward, destroying a cinder block garage and damaging a mobile home along 6th Street, just southeast of [[Bridgeport, Alabama|Bridgeport]]. It then crossed the [[Tennessee River]], producing significant tree damage before moving into [[Marion County, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"Fackler tornado\"/><ref name=\"FacklerNCDC\"/> The tornado entered [[Tennessee]] along Lakeview Drive near [[Moore Crossing, Tennessee|Moore Crossing]] and [[Nickajack Dam]]. It then proceeded to cross [[Nickajack Lake]] three times near [[Interstate 24]] at EF2 strength, downing numerous trees before dissipating in a bend of the Tennessee River northeast of [[Haletown, Tennessee|Haletown]] at 5:31&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2231 UTC). The tornado travelled {{convert|30.24|mi|km|}} through Jackson and Marion Counties and had a peak width of {{convert|1320|yd|m|}}. One person was killed by the tornado in Jackson County.<ref name=\"Fackler tornado\"/><ref name=\"FacklerNCDC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=343727|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Sawyerville\u2013Eoline, Alabama===\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF3\n| total fatalities = 7 fatalities, 52+ injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nThis strong, long-tracked EF3 wedge tornado touched down in extreme southwest [[Greene County, Alabama|Greene County]] to the west-southwest of [[Tishabee, Alabama|Tishabee]], near the [[Sumter County, Alabama|Sumter County]] border, at 5:30&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2230 UTC) and moved northeast. After having touched down in a rural area on the east side of the [[Tombigbee River]], the tornado quickly intensified to high-end EF2 strength along County Road 69. Moving northeast, the tornado damaged a barn and destroyed two small churches and at least four mobile homes. While crossing [[U.S. Route 43|U.S. 43]], the tornado destroyed a large metal outbuilding, caused substantial roof and wall damage to several brick buildings and homes. Hundreds of trees were downed in this area as well. Two people sustained minor injuries in Greene County as the tornado continued along a primarily rural path northeast, moving across the [[Black Warrior River]] and into [[Hale County, Alabama|Hale County]].<ref name=\"Sawyerville/Eoline tornado\">{{cite web|title=Sawyerville-Eoline (Greene, Hale and Bibb Counties) EF-3 Tornado April 27, 2011|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/bmx/?n=event_04272011sawyerville|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Birmingham, Alabama|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=April 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"GreeneCo NCDC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=314725|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|author=National Climatic Data Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|year=2011|accessdate=April 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe tornado entered Hale County west of [[Sawyerville, Alabama|Sawyerville]], continuing to move through sparsely populated rural areas. North of Sawyerville, the tornado strengthened to EF3 intensity as it was crossing [[Alabama State Route 14|Alabama State Highway 14]]. Reaching estimated maximum winds of {{convert|145|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, the tornado continued on its northeast track, crossing County Roads 18 and 21, [[Alabama State Route 69|Alabama State Highway 69]], and County Road 29 as it moved south and east of the small communities of [[Harper Hill, Alabama|Harper Hill]] and [[Ingram, Alabama|Ingram]]. The tornado caused extensive structural damage through this area, consisting of many mobile homes and site-built homes being either heavily damaged or destroyed. A church in the area was heavily damaged, vehicles were tossed around and destroyed, and thousands of trees were uprooted as well.<ref name=\"Sawyerville/Eoline tornado\"/><ref name=\"HaleCoEF3 NCDC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=314742|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|author=National Climatic Data Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|year=2011|accessdate=April 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:EolineFireDept.jpg|thumb|The destroyed Eoline Volunteer Fire Department building.]]\nLeaving behind six fatalities and forty more injuries, the tornado maintained its intensity as it moved into the [[Talladega National Forest]]. It downed a significant number of trees before moving into [[Bibb County, Alabama|Bibb County]] north of [[Alabama State Route 25|Alabama State Highway 25]].<ref name=\"Sawyerville/Eoline tornado\"/><ref name=\"HaleCoEF3 NCDC\"/> In Bibb County, the tornado continued moving northeastward through the Talladega National Forest at EF3 intensity, with thousands more trees being knocked down and partially debarked. Almost immediately after exiting the national forest, the tornado directly impacted the small community of [[Eoline, Alabama|Eoline]] along [[U.S. Route 82|U.S. Highway 82]], northwest of [[Brent, Alabama|Brent]] and [[Centerville, Alabama|Centerville]]. Around one dozen mobile homes and single-family site-built homes were destroyed, while many more sustained anywhere from minor to major damage. Additionally, the Eoline Volunteer Fire Department and another business were both destroyed. One fatality occurred in Eoline, in a vehicle near the fire department building, along with ten other injuries.<ref name=\"Sawyerville/Eoline tornado\"/><ref name=\"BibbCoEF3 NCDC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=314799|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|author=National Climatic Data Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|year=2011|accessdate=April 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nNortheast of Eoline, the tornado weakened to EF2 intensity, continuing to cause significant damage as it crossed County Road 9, [[Alabama State Route 5|Alabama State Highway 5]], and County Road 26, south of [[West Blocton, Alabama|West Blocton]]. Several mobile homes and site-built homes were either destroyed or sustained major damage. Along the path, thousands of trees were downed. The tornado continued to weaken as it moved to the east of West Blocton, continuing to knock down trees. More trees were downed as the tornado crossed the [[Cahaba River]] and lifted just northeast of [[Marvel, Alabama|Marvel]] at 6:55&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2355 UTC), not far from the [[Shelby County, Alabama|Shelby County]] border.<ref name=\"Sawyerville/Eoline tornado\"/><ref name=\"BibbCoEF3 NCDC\"/>\n\nThe tornado was rated as an EF3, with maximum sustained winds of {{convert|145|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}. It remained on the ground for almost an hour and a half, traversing {{convert|72.13|mi|km|}}, being, at times, about {{convert|1|mi|km|}} wide. In total, seven people were killed and an additional 52 were injured.<ref name=\"Sawyerville/Eoline tornado\"/><ref name=\"GreeneCo NCDC\"/><ref name=\"HaleCoEF3 NCDC\"/><ref name=\"BibbCoEF3 NCDC\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Raleigh\u2013Rose Hill\u2013Enterprise, Mississippi/Yantley\u2013Uniontown, Alabama===\n{{Infobox storm \n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF4\n| total fatalities = 7 fatalities, 17 injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\n[[File:Smith Jasper Clarke Counties tornado 2011-04-27.jpg|thumb|The EF4 Enterprise tornado, as it was in southeast Mississippi.<ref name=\"Raleigh, MS tornado\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/jan/?n=2011_04_25_27_svr_smith_jasper_clarke|title=Smith/Jasper/Clarke CountiesTornado|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Jackson, Mississippi|date=September 14, 2011|accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref>]]\nThis extremely long-tracked, violent EF4 tornado touched down near [[Raleigh, Mississippi]], in [[Smith County, Mississippi|Smith County]] at 5:42&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2242 UTC), and continued into the [[Uniontown, Alabama]] area before dissipating. The tornado initially downed trees, blew skirting from mobile homes, and tore shingles from roofs. The tornado intensified as it moved northeast across Smith County and produced up to EF2 and EF3 damage. One mobile home was picked up, bounced a couple times, and thrown into a tree line, where it was torn apart and debris was scattered up to a mile away, including the frame. The tornado mowed down a stand of pine trees and destroyed two frame houses, with major damage to the interior walls, and the exterior walls completely destroyed. Many power poles were snapped, a mobile home was annihilated, and a large shop building was completely destroyed as well. It then moved into [[Jasper County, Mississippi|Jasper County]] and snapped and debarked many pine trees. The first area of EF4 damage was observed near [[Louin, Mississippi|Louin]] as a frame home and several mobile homes were completely destroyed, with parts of the mobile homes being thrown long distances, and some of the frame home foundation being swept clean. The tornado caused significant damage to a poultry farm and cattle ranch before it weakened briefly. It then destroyed two mobile homes and caused extensive tree and power line damage. The tornado then produced a relatively narrow path of EF1-strength tree and power line damage for several miles, until re-intensifying near to EF3 strength near [[Rose Hill, Jasper County, Mississippi|Rose Hill]].<ref name=\"Raleigh, MS tornado\"/>\n\nSoutheast of Rose Hill, the tornado removed most of the roof of a frame home and caused heavy damage to the exterior walls, took a large section of roof off another frame home, completely destroyed a large mobile home, and caused extensive tree damage. The tornado then weakened again and entered [[Clarke County, Mississippi|Clarke County]] as an EF0 while only downing a few trees. The tornado strengthened again and downed trees and power lines as it crossed [[Interstate 59]]. Several other homes and mobile homes were destroyed as the tornado moved along the south side of [[Enterprise, Clarke County, Mississippi|Enterprise]]. At the same time, [[Sean Casey (filmmaker)|Sean Casey]] of Team TIV shot the tornado with his new 3D camera as it was crossing I-59, making this the first tornado ever shot in 3D. Another area of EF4 damage was observed east of Enterprise as a new home undergoing completion was leveled, with the debris swept off the foundation. Many more frame homes were heavily damaged nearby. Many mobile homes were destroyed and trees were downed in this area as well. It then weakened slightly to EF3 strength and produced heavy damage to more houses and mobile homes near [[Snell, Mississippi|Snell]] and [[Energy, Mississippi|Energy]]. It also downed many more trees and power lines before moving into [[Choctaw County, Alabama]] southwest of [[Yantley, Alabama|Yantley]]. The tornado killed seven people and injured fourteen others on its {{convert|65|mi|km|adj=on}} portion of the path that was in [[Mississippi]].<ref name=\"Raleigh, MS tornado\"/>\n\nIn Choctaw County, the tornado traveled {{convert|27.5|mi|km|}} as it caused extensive damage to homes (one of which was destroyed at EF3 strength), and numerous other structures. Several mobile homes were destroyed and many trees were either snapped or completely uprooted. The tornado then moved into [[Sumter County, Alabama|Sumter County]].<ref name=\"Yantley survey\">{{cite web|title=April 25\u201328, 2011 Tornado Outbreak Information|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/mob/?n=20110427_tor|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Mobile, Alabama|date=January 17, 2013|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> In Sumter County, the tornado caused significant damage to homes and mobile homes before it crossed the [[Tombigbee River]] and moved into [[Marengo County, Alabama|Marengo County]]. It continued causing significant tree damage as well as destroying several homes and outbuildings along a {{convert|26.7|mi|km|adj=on}} path in this county. The tornado then entered [[Perry County, Alabama|Perry County]], the final portion of the path, where it damaged two outbuildings and a grain silo as well as causing significant tree damage before lifting just north of [[Uniontown, Alabama|Uniontown]] at 8:35&nbsp;p.m. CDT (0135 UTC). The damage in Sumter, Marengo, and Perry Counties was rated EF2.<ref name=\"Uniontown tornado\">{{cite web|title=Pin Hook-Faunsdale (Sumter, Marengo and Perry Counties) EF-2 Tornado April 27, 2011|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/bmx/?n=event_04272011pinhook|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Birmingham, Alabama|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThis tornado was on the ground for nearly three hours, having traveled {{convert|122.04|mi|km|}} across seven counties in two states. Seven people were killed and another 17 were injured.<ref name=\"Raleigh, MS tornado\"/><ref name=\"Yantley survey\"/><ref name=\"Uniontown tornado\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Fyffe\u2013Rainsville\u2013Sylvania\u2013Ider, Alabama===\n[[File:Destroyed bus in Rainsville.JPG|thumb|left|School bus stripped down to its chassis in Rainsville.]]\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF5\n| total fatalities = 25 fatalities, unknown injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nThis violent multiple-vortex tornado, rated EF5, began in the Lakeview community northeast of [[Geraldine, Alabama]], at 6:19&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2319 UTC), during the late afternoon of April 27. The tornado tracked northeastward for {{convert|36.63|mi|km|}} generally parallel to and just east of [[Alabama State Route 75|Highway 75]] through [[Fyffe, Alabama|Fyffe]], [[Rainsville, Alabama|Rainsville]], and [[Sylvania, Alabama|Sylvania]] and into [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], killing 25 people.<ref name=\"Rainsville, AL Tornado Survey\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hun/?n=4272011_dekalb_county|title=Dekalb (AL) \u2013 Lakeview to Rainsville to Cartersville|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama|date=February 15, 2012|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe tornado touched down in the Lakeview community, initially causing structural damage to small buildings and snapping trees. The tornado grew in intensity as it struck [[Fyffe, Alabama|Fyffe]], where more significant damage occurred. Past Fyffe, the tornado became violent, and its width increased from around {{convert|50|yd|m|}} to {{convert|0.5|mi|m|}} as it entered eastern [[Rainsville, Alabama|Rainsville]], reaching EF5 strength and destroying numerous homes and businesses. A [[Huddle House]] restaurant, the Rainsville Civic Center, and a credit union were destroyed. Vehicles were also thrown, including a school bus that was completely stripped down to its chassis.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2011/apr/29/nation/la-na-rainsville-alabama-tornadoes-20110430|title=In Rainsville, tragedy and amazing tales of survival|last1=Bermudez|first1=Esmeralda|date=April 29, 2011|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> Numerous homes in the Rainsville area were swept completely away, with debris strewn up to a mile from the foundations. Some of these homes were connected to their foundations with anchor bolts and foundation straps. Trees were debarked and mobile homes were completely destroyed as well.<ref name=\"Rainsville, AL Tornado Survey\"/> Damage was particularly intense just northeast of Rainsville, and one well-built stone house in this area was completely obliterated, with the debris strewn well away from the structure. A large supporting cement and stone pillar was ripped completely out of the ground at this residence, pulling up a section of concrete foundation in the process. Scouring and pock-marking of the ground was noted in this area. Numerous homes were swept away along Lingerfelt Rd as well. At one house that was swept away in this area, supporting concrete anchors were ripped out of the ground, a concrete porch was ripped off with pieces strewn up to {{convert|150|yd|m|}} away, a pick-up truck from the home was found mangled in pieces over {{convert|250|yd|m|}} away, and a safe weighing {{convert|800|lb|kg|}} was pulled off its anchorage and thrown into a wooded area {{convert|600|ft|m|}} away. When found, the safe's door had been ripped open and completely off.<ref name=\"Rainsville, AL Tornado Survey\"/> An underground storm shelter in this area had much of its dirt covering scoured away, the occupants of which reported that structure heaved upwards slightly as the tornado passed overhead. Pavement was scoured from several roads in the area, and a concrete porch was torn away and broken in half at another residence that was swept away.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ams.confex.com/ams/26SLS/webprogram/Handout/Paper212695/sels12b.pdf|title=Extreme Damage Incidents In The 27 April 2011 Tornado Superoutbreak|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration/[[University of Alabama in Huntsville]]/[[Universities Space Research Association]] (jointly produced article)|work=National Weather Service in Huntsville, Alabama/Birmingham, Alabama (both offices)|author1=Eugene W. McCaul, Jr.|author2=Kevin R. Knupp|author3=Chris Darden|author4=Kevin Laws|year=2011|accessdate=July 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe tornado continued across the eastern fringes of [[Sylvania, Alabama|Sylvania]], where a church was completely destroyed, a section of sidewalk was pulled up, and additional homes were swept away and scattered, though it was revealed that these homes were pushed off of their foundations with limited anchorage. A high-end EF4 rating was applied in this area as a result.<ref name=\"Rainsville, AL Tornado Survey\"/> The tornado continued to level additional homes as it passed near [[Henagar, Alabama|Henagar]] and [[Ider, Alabama|Ider]]. It crossed into [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] near [[Fox Mountain, Georgia|Fox Mountain]] as an EF1 with winds of {{convert|110|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}. It tracked {{convert|3|mi|km|}} into Georgia before lifting outside of [[Rising Fawn, Georgia|Rising Fawn]] at 6:55&nbsp;p.m. CDT/7:55&nbsp;p.m. EDT (2355 UTC). Damage in Georgia was limited to trees and power lines and minor structural damage to a few homes. This tornado came from the same supercell that produced the EF4 that hit the town of [[Ringgold, Georgia]] about 30 minutes later.<ref name=\"Rainsville, AL Tornado Survey\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=304706|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|author=National Climatic Data Center|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|year=2011|accessdate=May 22, 2016}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Shoal Creek Valley\u2013Ohatchee\u2013Piedmont, Alabama/Cave Spring, Georgia===\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF4\n| total fatalities = 22 fatalities, 85 injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\n[[File:Shoal Creek Valley Alabama Tornado April 27, 2011.jpg|thumb|The Shoal Creek Valley/Ohatchee EF4 tornado.]]\nAfter the Tuscaloosa/Birmingham tornado lifted, the same supercell produced another tornado, at 6:28&nbsp;p.m. CDT (2328 UTC) near [[Argo, Alabama]], in eastern [[Jefferson County, Alabama|Jefferson County]]. It went on to devastate the rural community of Shoal Creek Valley, located between [[Ashville, Alabama|Ashville]] and [[Ragland, Alabama|Ragland]] in [[St. Clair County, Alabama]].<ref name=\"Shoal Creek-Ohatchee survey\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/bmx/?n=event_04272011ohatchee|title=Argo-Shoal Creek-Ohatchee-Forney (Jefferson, St. Clair, Calhoun, Etowah, and Cherokee Counties) EF-4 Tornado April 27, 2011|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Birmingham, Alabama|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=December 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter touching down southwest of Argo, the tornado continued northeast of [[Odenville, Alabama|Odenville]], producing EF0 to EF1 tree damage. Further east, the tornado intensified to EF3 strength and entered the rural community of Shoal Creek Valley, following along County Road 22/Shoal Creek Road for approximately {{convert|12.5|mi|km}}, with the path and width varying greatly along the road. Many homes were left with only interior walls standing in this area. Some section of this path segment had damage that was much worse on one side of the road than the other, while other areas showed equal devastation on both sides of the road. The tornado reached mid-range EF4 intensity towards the end of the valley as it approached [[Neely Henry Lake]]. Additional homes were destroyed in this area, one was swept away, and thousands of trees were mowed down and debarked. The tornado maintained EF4 strength as it crossed the lake and tore across the north edge of [[Ohatchee, Alabama|Ohatchee]], completely leveling or sweeping away numerous waterfront homes. Damage ranged from downed trees and roof damage to total destruction as the tornado roared through this area at {{convert|50|-|60|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, packing winds of over {{convert|180|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}. The official count of homes destroyed or heavily damaged in Shoal Creek Valley and Ohatchee was 256. Most phone lines, power lines and poles were destroyed, and water lines were severed by uprooted trees. Entire homes were leveled, and in some cases completely removed by the storm, leaving only brick steps, a fireplace and chimney, or a slab behind. Barns, vehicles, tractors and heavy farming equipment were shredded and thrown up to {{convert|0.5|mi|km}} away from where they originated. Livestock were thrown and killed, and the initial human death toll of 13 would eventually rise to 15 in the area.<ref name=\"Shoal Creek-Ohatchee survey\"/> The tornado caused mainly EF3 damage to homes as it passed north of [[Wellington, Alabama|Wellington]], though a small pocket of EF4 damage occurred in the small rural community of [[Webster's Chapel, Alabama|Webster's Chapel]], where a church and several homes were completely leveled or swept away, trees were reduced to stumps, and many other homes were left with only interior walls standing.<ref name=\"Shoal Creek-Ohatchee survey\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/StormDamage/DamageViewer/|title=NWS Damage Assessment Toolkit|work=noaa.gov}}</ref> The Silver Lakes Golf Course also sustained major damage in this area, where at least 50,000 trees were flattened and buildings were damaged or destroyed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gadsdentimes.com/article/20110604/NEWS/110609901?tc=ar|title=Tornado-damaged Silver Lakes faces uncertain future|work=GadsdenTimes.com}}</ref> Continuing northeast, the tornado produced high-end EF3 damage north of [[Piedmont, Alabama|Piedmont]], destroying mobile homes, snapping numerous trees, and leveling a house. Additional homes were leveled at high-end EF3 intensity near [[The Indian Mountain Tract]] before it continued across rural areas into [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref name=\"Shoal Creek-Ohatchee survey\"/> Many outbuildings and homes were destroyed, and many trees were downed across [[Polk County, Georgia|Polk]], [[Floyd County, Georgia|Floyd]], and [[Bartow County, Georgia|Bartow]] counties before the tornado dissipated. Severe damage was noted near [[Cave Spring, Georgia|Cave Spring]] where chicken houses and homes were damaged or destroyed, and several people were injured. The damage in Georgia was rated EF2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/ffc/?n=20110427_svrstorms#polk|title=Polk, Floyd, and Bartow Counties|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Peachtree City, Georgia|date=May 10, 2011|accessdate=December 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThis tornado's final death toll, combining fatalities in both St. Clair and [[Calhoun County, Alabama|Calhoun]] counties in Alabama, would eventually come to 22.<ref name=\"spc fatal\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Ringgold, Georgia/Southeast Tennessee===\n[[File:Ringgold tornado damage.jpg|thumb|left|EF4 damage in a subdivision at the north edge of Ringgold, Georgia. Seven fatalities occurred at this location.]]\n{{Infobox storm\n| name = \n| fujitascale = EF4\n| total fatalities = 20 fatalities, 335 injuries\n| enhanced = yes\n}}\nA violent multiple-vortex tornado struck portions of extreme northern Georgia and southeast Tennessee during the mid-evening hours of April 27. It touched down along Davis Ridge Road in [[Catoosa County, Georgia]], and moved through the town of [[Ringgold, Georgia|Ringgold]] at EF3 strength, destroying numerous homes and businesses.<ref name=\"NWSRinggoldEF4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/ffc/?n=20110427_svrstorms#catoosa|title=Catoosa County|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Peachtree City, Georgia|date=May 10, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> A [[Baymont Inn & Suites]], located near [[Interstate 75]] was partially destroyed by the tornado, along with a [[McDonald's]], a [[Taco Bell]], and several gas stations located on Highway 151 in Ringgold at the Interstate 75 interchange (exit 348). The Catoosa County Department of Family and Children Services and other businesses on Nashville Street in downtown Ringgold were also heavily damaged. The Kellerhals Center for Visual Arts Education at Ringgold High School was destroyed (RHS itself had minor damage), and Ringgold Middle School was heavily damaged.<ref name=\"NWSRinggoldEF4\"/><ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[The Daily Citizen (Dalton)|Dalton Daily Citizen]]|url=http://daltondailycitizen.com/local/x58991204/Ringgold-devastated-after-tornado-touchdown|title=Ringgold devastated after tornado touchdown|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=April 30, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120707190019/http://daltondailycitizen.com/local/x58991204/Ringgold-devastated-after-tornado-touchdown|archivedate=July 7, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Past downtown Ringgold, the tornado reached EF4 intensity as it tore through a subdivision along Cherokee Valley Road at the north edge of town. Twelve homes were completely obliterated and swept away at that location (though they were not well-built). Several trees were denuded and debarked in this area as well. There were 74 destroyed homes and/or businesses, 60 with major damage, and 118 with minor damage for a total of 252 affected structures in the Ringgold area. Eight people were killed, mainly at the subdivision along Cherokee Valley Road.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=305268 |title=Storm Events Databse |website=NCDC |publisher=NCDC |accessdate=June 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Apison, TN tornado damage.PNG|thumb|right|EF4 damage to a brick home in Apison, Tennessee.]]\nThe storm then crossed the Tennessee state line at 8:28&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]] (0028 UTC), and moved into [[Hamilton County, Tennessee]], striking the small town of [[Apison, Tennessee|Apison]] at high-end EF4 strength, where large homes were leveled or swept away, 150 others were damaged, and thousands of trees were snapped and uprooted.<ref name=\"NWSApisonEF4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/mrx/?n=hamiltonbradleycollegedaleef4|title=Hamilton County \u2013 Bradley County \u2013 Collegedale EF4 Tornado Track and Photos|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Morristown, Tennessee|date=August 23, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=296789 |title=Storm Events Databse |website=NCDC |publisher=NCDC |accessdate=June 15, 2014}}</ref> The tornado then crossed into Bradley County at low-end EF4 strength, moving across the southern and eastern fringes of [[Cleveland, Tennessee|Cleveland]] and affecting mainly residential areas, though a few businesses were damaged or destroyed as well. Subdivisions in the southern part of the city sustained major damage, with numerous houses destroyed and a few that were leveled.<ref name=\"NWSApisonEF4\"/> Four people were killed in Cleveland, and many others were injured.<ref name=\"NWSApisonEF4\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=300457 |title=Storm Events Databse |website=NCDC |publisher=NCDC |accessdate=June 15, 2014}}</ref> Several trees were felled in Polk County (as the tornado had weakened to EF1-strength), before the tornado crossed into McMinn County.<ref name=\"NWSApisonEF4\"/> The tornado re-strengthened to an EF2 and destroyed two houses and a mobile home before lifting south of [[Athens, Tennessee|Athens]].<ref>{{cite web|title=NCDC Storm Events Database|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=353334|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Climatic Data Center|year=2011|accessdate=January 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe tornado killed 20 people and injured hundreds more along its {{convert|57|mi|km|adj=on}} path across Catoosa, Hamilton, Bradley, Polk and McMinn counties. The tornado was given a rating of EF4 with winds ranging from {{convert|175|-|190|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}. The damage path of the tornado was between {{convert|1/3|and|1/2|mi|km}} wide. This tornado was only the eighth in Georgia to be categorized as an F4/EF4 on the ([[Enhanced Fujita scale|Enhanced]]) [[Fujita scale]] since 1950, when official tornado records begin.<ref name=\"NWSRinggoldEF4\"/><ref name=\"NWSApisonEF4\"/><ref name=\"EF4\">{{cite news|publisher=OKC Storm Watcher|url=http://okcstormwatcher.wordpress.com/2011/04/29/ringgold-ga-tornado-confirmed-as-an-ef-4-tornado/|title=Ringgold, GA Tornado Confirmed as an EF-4 Tornado (4/27/2011)|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=April 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAll roads in and out of Ringgold were closed until the morning of April 29; after roads leading to the affected areas were re-opened, residents and business owners were allowed to return, being allowed entry only by providing identification, and informing police a reason why they were entering into the area, in order to curb looting in the storm-damaged areas.<ref name=\"Ringgold\">{{cite news|publisher=[[WXIA-TV]]|url=http://marietta.11alive.com/news/news/ringgold-residents-return-utter-devastation/59674|title=Ringgold residents return to 'utter devastation'|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=April 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Non-tornadic effects==\n{{see also|2011 Mississippi River floods}}\n[[File:Pcpnweekending04292011.jpg|thumb|right|Rainfall totals within the United States for the week ending during the morning of April 29, 2011, which shows the extent of the heavy rain event this cyclone contributed towards.]]\nThis storm system prolonged an ongoing heavy rain event, which began across Arkansas and Missouri on April 22.<ref name=\"SS11\"/> Weekly rainfall totals reached {{convert|19.73|in|mm}} {{convert|6|mi|km|}} east-northeast of [[Springdale, Arkansas]], {{convert|16.20|in|mm}} {{convert|4|mi|km|}} northwest of [[Poplar Bluff, Missouri]], and {{convert|14.96|in|mm}} at [[Westville, Oklahoma]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/winter_storm_summaries/2011/storm11/stormsum_21.html|author=DavidHamrick|publisher=Weather Prediction Center|accessdate=May 1, 2011|date=April 28, 2011|title=Storm Summary 21 for Central and Eastern U.S. Heavy Rain Event}}</ref> On April 25, 2011, thunderstorms with high winds swept through parts of southern and southeastern Ohio. Straight-line winds estimated at {{convert|80|mph|km/h}} uprooted trees, damaged roofs, and downed power lines through [[Perry County, Ohio]], and [[Athens County, Ohio]]. Strong thunderstorms and heavy downpours which led to flooding were also reported in areas across Upstate New York with heavy flooding in the [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]] area. The rain also saturated hundreds of lakes in the [[Adirondack mountains]]. [[Interstate 81]] was briefly shut down in the downtown area at traffic hour and the [[State University of New York Upstate Medical University]] also closed briefly due to flooding in the lobby.<ref>{{cite news|last=McChensey|first=Charles|title=Severe storms, flash floods strike Central New York|url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2011/04/severe_storms_flash_floods_str.html|publisher=[[The Post-Standard|Syracuse.com/The Post-Standard]]|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=April 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nFarther south, flash flooding late on April 26 resulted in two fatalities in [[Monroe, Louisiana]] after an apartment complex was swamped. The flooding there was considered to be worse than the flooding after [[Hurricane Gustav]] in [[2008 Atlantic hurricane season|2008]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |work=National Weather Service in Shreveport, Louisiana |title=The Tornado Outbreak of April 25\u201327, 2011 |url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/shv/events/select.php?date=04262011_1 |date=May 9, 2011 |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303205221/http://www.srh.noaa.gov/shv/events/select.php?date=04262011_1 |archivedate=March 3, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In central and northern Arkansas, up to {{convert|10.44|in|mm|}} of rain was reported during that week. The resulting flash flooding in central Arkansas also resulted in five people losing their lives. Many roads were closed due to the flooding there. The flooding was mitigated somewhat by a significant [[drought]] that had existed before the storm.<ref>{{cite news|agency=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|work=National Weather Service in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=Heavy Rain/Severe Weather on April 23\u201327, 2011 (Pg1)|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/lzk/?n=rain0411yr.htm|publisher=National Weather Service|date=May 14, 2011|accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSevere thunderstorms were reported as far north as [[Northern Ontario]] on the evening of April 26. Heavy rains and minor flooding were also reported in Northern Ontario from April 26\u201328.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[Sault Star]]|url=http://www.saultstar.com/2011/04/28/old-hospital-site-floods-updated-at-136-pm|title=Old hospital site floods|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120806190258/http://www.saultstar.com/2011/04/28/old-hospital-site-floods-updated-at-136-pm|archive-date=August 6, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[Sudbury Star]]|url=http://www.thesudburystar.com/2011/04/27/rain-soaks-sudbury|title=Rain soaks Sudbury|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222082441/http://www.thesudburystar.com/2011/04/27/rain-soaks-sudbury|archive-date=December 22, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=Sudbury Star|url=http://www.thesudburystar.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=3100195|title=Keep eye out for possible flooding, city advises|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322094650/http://www.thesudburystar.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=3100195|archive-date=March 22, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[North Bay Nugget]]|url=http://www.nugget.ca/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=3100171|title=Ice is off, and a flood warning issued|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001001921/http://www.nugget.ca/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=3100171|archive-date=October 1, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Windstorms were also reported in [[Southern Ontario]] and Southern [[Quebec]] which resulted in several injuries and one death, damages and power outages.<ref name=\"ottawacitizen.com\">{{cite news|publisher=[[Ottawa Citizen]] |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/Three+women+seriously+hurt+spring+windstorm+whips+through+Ottawa/4691025/story.html |title=Three women seriously hurt as spring wind storm whips through Ottawa |date=April 29, 2011 |accessdate=July 15, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110502213722/http://www.ottawacitizen.com/news/Three%2Bwomen%2Bseriously%2Bhurt%2Bspring%2Bwindstorm%2Bwhips%2Bthrough%2BOttawa/4691025/story.html |archivedate=May 2, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"theweathernetwork.com\">{{cite news|publisher=[[The Weather Network]] ([[Canada]]) |url=http://www.theweathernetwork.com/news/storm_watch_stories3&stormfile=assessing_the_damage_in_onta_280411?ref=ccbox_weather_category1 |title=Wednesday's damage in Ontario being investigated |date=April 29, 2011 |accessdate=April 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402135837/http://www.theweathernetwork.com/news/storm_watch_stories3%26stormfile%3Dassessing_the_damage_in_onta_280411?ref=ccbox_weather_category1 |archivedate=April 2, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref name=\"Fierce winds whip through Ontario\">{{cite news|publisher=The Weather Network (Canada) |url=http://www.theweathernetwork.com/news/storm_watch_stories3&stormfile=winds_whip_through_ontario_280411?ref=ccbox_weather_topstories |title=Fierce winds whip through Ontario |date=April 29, 2011 |accessdate=April 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110502204825/http://www.theweathernetwork.com/news/storm_watch_stories3%26stormfile%3Dwinds_whip_through_ontario_280411?ref=ccbox_weather_topstories |archivedate=May 2, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref name=\"JMontreal\">{{cite web|url=http://lejournaldemontreal.canoe.ca/actualites/faitsdiversetjudiciaires/archives/2011/04/20110428-162908.html|title=Les vents violents font un mort en Ontario|work=Actualit\u00e9s|publisher=[[Journal de Montr\u00e9al]]|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=May 8, 2011|language=fr|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130115090443/http://lejournaldemontreal.canoe.ca/actualites/faitsdiversetjudiciaires/archives/2011/04/20110428-162908.html|archivedate=January 15, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Zone-911\">{{cite web|url=http://zone911.fm93.com/actualites/accidents/item/12689-des-vents-violents-causent-des-d%C3%A9sagr%C3%A9ments-dans-la-r%C3%A9gion-de-montr%C3%A9al |title=Des vents violents causent des d\u00e9sagr\u00e9ments dans la r\u00e9gion de Montr\u00e9al |author=Fran\u00e7ois Houde |date=April 29, 2011 |publisher=Zone911.com |accessdate=May 8, 2011 |language=fr |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323170111/http://zone911.fm93.com/actualites/accidents/item/12689-des-vents-violents-causent-des-d%C3%A9sagr%C3%A9ments-dans-la-r%C3%A9gion-de-montr%C3%A9al |archivedate=March 23, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nOther fatalities due to straight-line winds occurred in [[McComb, Mississippi]] early on April 26<ref name=\"Apr25SPC\"/> and also in [[Moody, Alabama]], [[Vestavia Hills, Alabama]], and [[Franklin, Tennessee]] early on April 27 from the squall line with embedded tornadoes.<ref name=\"Storm Reports April 27\"/><ref name=\"Storm Reports April 26\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\nAlabama Governor [[Robert J. Bentley]] declared a state of emergency in the state of Alabama on April 27, due to storm damage from severe thunderstorms earlier that day as well as forthcoming severe weather later that day. States of emergency were also declared in Arkansas, [[Kentucky]], Mississippi, Missouri, [[Tennessee]], and Oklahoma because of the flooding and tornadoes.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[Travel Weekly]]|url=http://www.travelweekly.co.uk/Articles/2011/04/28/36968/state-of-emergency-declared-in-seven-us-states.html|title=State of emergency declared in seven US states|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> Following the tornado outbreak on the evening of April 27, [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] granted a federal emergency declaration for the state of Alabama, giving federal assistance, including search and rescue assets, to the affected region.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[White House|The White House]]|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2011/04/27/president-obama-signs-alabama-emergency-declaration|title=President Obama Signs Alabama Emergency Declaration|date=April 27, 2011|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nMore than 2,000 [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] troops were deployed to Alabama, assisting local and state first responders in search and rescue efforts.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=CNN|url=http://whitehouse.blogs.cnn.com/2011/04/28/white-house-mobilizes-response-in-wake-of-deadly-storms/|title=White House mobilizes response in wake of deadly storms|author=Lesa Jansen|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}</ref> President Obama visited the affected areas of Alabama on April 29.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-13233106|title=Barack Obama pledges to help US tornadoes recovery|date=April 29, 2011|work=[[BBC News Online]]|publisher=[[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]]|accessdate=April 29, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429033454/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-13233106|archivedate=April 29, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> Also on April 29, he approved a federal disaster declaration for seven Mississippi counties: [[Clarke County, Mississippi|Clarke]], [[Greene County, Mississippi|Greene]], [[Hinds County, Mississippi|Hinds]], [[Jasper County, Mississippi|Jasper]], [[Kemper County, Mississippi|Kemper]], [[Lafayette County, Mississippi|Lafayette]], and [[Monroe County, Mississippi|Monroe]].<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[Hattiesburg American]]|url=http://www.hattiesburgamerican.com/article/20110429/ONLINEONLY/110429017|title=Mississippi receives federal disaster declaration|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2013}}{{Dead link|date=July 2016}}</ref> By the morning of April 30, the Alabama Emergency Management Agency had confirmed at least 45 storm fatalities in Tuscaloosa, but this was later corrected downward to 44. The tornado killed 64 people along its entire path.<ref name=\"alemapressrelease1\"/>\n\n===Electricity outage===\nStorms through the area severely damaged [[Tennessee Valley Authority]] (TVA)'s [[electric power transmission|power grid]] for transmitting electricity throughout the region. More than 300 power transmission towers, {{convert|120|ft|m}} to {{convert|150|ft|m}} tall, were destroyed in the storms, some \"twisted like bow ties\" according to National Weather Service meteorologist Eric Holweg. The towers supported some 90 transmission lines, a mixture of 500[[volt|kV]] and 161kV lines. Those lines provided power from TVA to 128 regional distributors.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesfreepress.com/news/2011/may/03/tva-expects-damaged-transmission-power-lines-repai/|title=TVA expects damaged transmission power lines repaired by end of summer|date=May 3, 2011|accessdate=May 5, 2011|author=Pam Sohn|publisher=[[Chattanooga Times Free Press]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524041741/http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/2011/may/03/tva-expects-damaged-transmission-power-lines-repai/|archivedate=May 24, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref><ref name=\"bowTieTower\">{{cite news|url=http://timesfreepress.com/news/2011/may/03/90-high-voltage-power-towers-twisted-bow-ties/|title=High-voltage power towers 'twisted like bow ties'|date=May 3, 2011|accessdate=May 5, 2011|author=Pam Sohn|publisher=Chattanooga Times Free Press|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524041626/http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/2011/may/03/90-high-voltage-power-towers-twisted-bow-ties/|archivedate=May 24, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Electric line tower.jpg|thumb|Transmission tower bent near [[Huntsville, Alabama]].]]\nTVA lost the ability to transmit power from both [[Browns Ferry Nuclear Power Plant]] and [[Widows Creek Power Plant|Widows Creek Fossil Plant]] after the storms on April 27, requiring both to be shut down. The nuclear plant's [[Shutdown (nuclear reactor)|cold shutdown]] was supported by diesel generators for four days until a second 161kV line could be restored to the plant. The loss of redundant off-site power required a \"notification of unusual event\", the lowest of four levels of concern dictated by the [[Nuclear Regulatory Commission|NRC]]. Some 60 percent of the sirens for warning residents of worse problems around Browns Ferry were disabled by the storms, and the plant had to arrange plans to use cars with loudspeakers to warn residents in case of another problem.<ref name=\"TFP-nuke\"/><ref name=\"bowTieTower\"/> The Nuclear Regulatory Commission stated at a press conference: \"The plants' conditions are stable and are being placed in a cooled-down condition.\"<ref name=UPI-nuke>{{cite news|title=NRC: 'Bama nuke plant shut down safely|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2011/04/28/NRC-Bama-nuke-plant-shut-down-safely/UPI-64291304024604/|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=April 28, 2011|newspaper=[[United Press International|UPI]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesfreepress.com/news/2011/apr/30/nuclear-sirens-conk-out-storm/|title=Nuclear sirens conk out in storm|publisher=Chattanooga Times Free Press|date=April 30, 2011|accessdate=May 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Huntsville, Alabama|Huntsville]] was the largest city with no electricity from TVA.<ref name=\"bowTieTower\"/> All the traffic lights were off, a dusk-to-dawn curfew was imposed, students were sent home from [[United States Space Camp]], and the [[Panoply Arts Festival]] was canceled.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wsoctv.com/news/27722984/detail.html |title=Classmates Recount Terrifying Night Of Tornadoes At Space Camp |publisher=[[WSOC-TV]] |date=April 29, 2011 |accessdate=May 5, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110509034424/http://www.wsoctv.com/news/27722984/detail.html |archivedate=May 9, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.peninsuladailynews.com/article/20110429/news/304299984/port-angeles-man-witnesses-alabama-twister|title=Port Angeles man witnesses Alabama twister|author=Rob Ollikainen|publisher=[[Peninsula Daily News]]|date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=May 5, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.al.com/entertainment-times/2011/04/panoply_arts_festival_canceled.html|title=Panoply Arts Festival canceled, food vendors helping city|publisher=[[The Huntsville Times]]|date=April 29, 2011|accessdate=May 7, 2011|author=Sarah Cure}}</ref> Power was restored gradually to Huntsville, beginning with 3 percent on the morning of May 1.<ref name=\"3percent\">{{cite news|url=http://www.madisoncountyrecord.com/2011/05/01/some-power-restored-to-huntsville-area/|title=Some power restored to Huntsville area|publisher=Madison County Record|date=May 1, 2011|accessdate=May 5, 2011}}</ref> Only localized outages remained eight days after the storm.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.al.com/breaking/2011/05/huntsville_utilities_has_power.html|title=Huntsville Utilities has power back to most customers, some still waiting|publisher=AL.com|date=May 5, 2011|accessdate=May 5, 2011|author=Brian Lawson}}</ref> In addition to traffic and safety issues, the outage caused difficulties with water treatment and distribution and retail of all kinds, including [[gasoline]] and food purchases.<ref name=\"3percent\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.al.com/spotnews/2011/04/alabama_tornadoes_small_store.html|title=Alabama tornadoes: Small store at Warrior thrives as people search for gas, food and refreshment|publisher=AL.com|work=Birmingham News|date=May 5, 2011|accessdate=April 28, 2011|author=Lisa Osburn}}</ref>\n\nOntario electricity outages were minor, mostly caused by the windstorms of April 28. Although they affected thousands of people at different times throughout the day, all power was restored by the end of the day.<ref name=\"ottawacitizen.com\"/><ref name=\"theweathernetwork.com\"/><ref name=\"Fierce winds whip through Ontario\"/><ref name=\"JMontreal\"/><ref name=\"Zone-911\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Weather}}\n* [[List of North American tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n* [[List of F5 and EF5 tornadoes]]\n* [[Tornadoes of 2011]]\n* [[List of disasters in the United States by death toll]]\n* [[Tornado records]]\n* [[Tri-State Tornado]] \u2013 Deadliest tornado in North America, and made March 18, 1925 the deadliest tornado day recorded in United States.\n* [[1932 Deep South tornado outbreak]] \u2013 Deadliest tornado outbreak in Alabama history, including an F4 tornado that tracked through Tuscaloosa.\n* [[1936 Tupelo\u2013Gainesville tornado outbreak]] \u2013 Infamous tornado outbreak occurring on April 5\u20136, 1936. Deadliest U.S. tornado outbreak since the March 1925 (Tri-State Tornado) outbreak, thus surpassing the March 1932, April 1974, and April 2011 outbreaks in total fatalities.\n* [[April 1956 Birmingham tornado]] \u2013 F4 tornado that hit the northern Birmingham suburbs on April 15, 1956.\n* [[1974 Super Outbreak]] \u2013 Infamous tornado outbreak that occurred on April 3\u20134, 1974, similar in severity to the 2011 Super Outbreak; though the 2011 event surpassed the 1974 Super Outbreak as the largest recorded outbreak.\n* [[April 1977 Birmingham tornado]] \u2013 F5 tornado that hit the northern Birmingham suburbs on April 4, 1977.\n* [[1994 Palm Sunday tornado outbreak]] \u2013 March 27, 1994 outbreak that produced an F4 tornado in St. Clair, Calhoun and Cherokee Counties in north-central Alabama.\n* [[April 1998 Birmingham tornado]] \u2013 F5 tornado that struck western parts of Birmingham on April 8, 1998.\n* [[December 2000 Tuscaloosa tornado]] \u2013 F4 tornado that hit southeast suburbs of Tuscaloosa on December 16, 2000.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal |last = Chiu |first = Samantha |title = Mesoscale and Stormscale Ingredients of Tornadic Supercells Producing Long-track Tornadoes in the 2011 Alabama Super Outbreak |journal = M.S. Thesis |publisher = University of Illinois |location = Urbana-Champaign |year = 2013 |doi = |hdl = 2142/45431 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|April 25\u201328, 2011 tornado outbreak}}\n* [http://hook-echo.com/2011/04/28/april-27-2011-tornado-outbreak-tuscaloosa-and-birmingham-alabama Hook\u2013Echo.com Tornado Outbreak Overview]\n* [http://www.stormtimemachine.com/ Time lapse visualization of the April 25\u201328 tornado outbreak]\n* [http://www.tornadohistoryproject.com/custom/3391989 Interactive map of all the tornado paths during the April 25\u201328 outbreak]\n\n'''Emergency Tornado Aid'''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724043339/http://american.redcross.org/site/PageServer?pagename=ntld_main&gclid=COy-qNqUxagCFcq8KgodHyY8tw National Red Cross]\n* [http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/article/20110428/MULTIMEDIA/110429676 Tuscaloosa News People Finder] \u2013 Set up by local newspaper to aid in finding loved ones and friends missing in the tornado.\n\n'''Memorials'''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110807043225/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/44045587/ns/us_news-life/ University of Alabama Holds Memorial Ceremony Honoring Students who Died in Disaster as well as First Responders]\n\n'''Pictures from Tuscaloosa, Alabama'''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150624015151/http://www.marcokaschuba.com/tuscaloosa_tornado/index.php#001 Tornado Damage in Tuscaloosa, Alabama]\n\n'''Video'''\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hR83MBQNGqw Overhead view of Cullman, Alabama damage]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J8uSIQLftME Detailed Radar loop of Northern Alabama, Eastern Mississippi, and Southern Tennessee]\n\n{{2011 Super Outbreak}}\n{{2011 tornado outbreaks}}\n{{Alabama tornado events}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2011-04-27 Super Outbreak}}\n[[Category:F5 tornadoes by date]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Texas]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes of 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 natural disasters in the United States|Tornado,2011-04-27]]\n[[Category:Tuscaloosa, Alabama]]\n[[Category:History of Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:2011 in Alabama]]\n[[Category:2011 in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:2011 in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:2011 in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:2011 in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:2011 in Maryland]]\n[[Category:2011 in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:2011 in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:2011 in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:2011 in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:2011 in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:2011 in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:2011 in Texas]]\n[[Category:2011 in Virginia]]\n[[Category:2011 disasters in Canada|Tornado,2011-04-27]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Canada by date]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:April 2011 events in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2011 events in the United States|Super Outbreak]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Ontario]]\n", "name_user": "IsMyNameTooLong", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011_Super_Outbreak"}
{"title_page": "Cool S", "text_new": "{{short description|Graffiti symbol}}\n{{multiple image\n| image1 = \"Cool S\".svg\n| width1 = 67\n| image_gap = 12| image2 = \"Cool S\" Drawing Instructions.svg\n| width2 = 201\n| footer = A drawing of the \"Cool S\" and the corresponding four-step guide to drawing one\n| align = \n| direction = \n| total_width = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| caption2 = \n}}\nThe \"'''Cool S'''\", also known as the \"'''St\u00fcssy S'''\", \"'''Super S'''\", \"'''Superman S'''\", \"'''Pointy S'''\", \"'''Slayer S'''\", \"'''Graffiti S'''\", \"'''The S Factor'''\",<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.drawingnow.com/drawings/100332/how-to-make-one-graffiti-s/|title=how to make one graffiti S|website=DrawingNow DrawingNow|language=en|access-date=May 14, 2018}}</ref> \"'''Universal S'''\", and many other names, is a [[graffiti]] sign in [[popular culture]] that is typically [[doodle]]d on children's notebooks or graffitied on walls. The exact origin of the \"Cool S\" is unknown.<ref name=\":0\" /> It may have begun as a [[geometric]] [[puzzle]] or [[pattern]] dating back centuries,<ref>{{cite book|last=Wilson|first=Frederick Newton|title=Mechanical Graphics|date=1890|publisher=The Princeton Press|location=Princeton, N.J.|page=[https://archive.org/details/mechanicalgraphi00will/page/12 12]|url=https://archive.org/details/mechanicalgraphi00will|access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref> or it may have appeared around the 1980s or 1990s as a part of graffiti culture. Contrary to popular belief, the symbol has no ties to either the American clothing brand [[St\u00fcssy]] or to the character [[Superman]].\n\n==Shape==\nThe \"Cool S\" consists of 14 line segments, forming a stylized, pointed [[S (letter)|S]]-shape. It has also been compared to the [[infinity]] symbol.<ref name=Ranker>{{cite web|url=https://www.ranker.com/list/story-behind-that-s-thing/anna-lindwasser|title=Here's The Story Behind That Cool 'S' Thing You Used To Draw In Class|last=Lindwasser|first=Anna|website=Ranker|access-date=August 11, 2019}}</ref> The \"tails\" (pointy ends) of the S appear to link underneath so that it loops around on itself in the same way as the [[infinity symbol]] does.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nyulocal.com/local-investigates-the-mysterious-s-symbol-9254626b8225#.9jqdl0p67|title=Local Investigates: The Mysterious S Symbol|date=February 12, 2014|work=[[NYU Local]]|access-date=January 29, 2017}}</ref> The \"Cool S\" has no [[reflection symmetry]], but has 2-fold [[rotational symmetry]]. As illustrated, a common way to draw the shape begins with two sets of three parallel, vertical lines, one above the other.\n\n==Origin==\nThe origin of the \"Cool S\" is unclear.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.printmag.com/imprint/solve-the-mystery-of-the-pointy-s/|title=Solve the Mystery of the Pointy S|last=Neelon|first=Caleb|date=November 23, 2010|work=[[Print (magazine)|Print Magazine]]|access-date=January 29, 2017}}</ref> The name \"[[Superman]] S\" comes from a belief that it was a symbol for Superman, whose costume features a stylized \"S\" in a diamond shape, but that shape is quite different. Although frequently referred to as the \"[[St\u00fcssy]] S\", Emmy Coats (who has worked alongside [[Shawn Stussy]] since 1985) has stated that it was never a symbol of the Californian surf company.<ref name=\"Vice\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_se/article/that-s-thing-everyone-drew-in-school-what-is-it|title=That 'S' Thing Everyone Drew in School, What Is It?|last=Morgans|first=Julian|date=July 23, 2016|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|access-date=March 21, 2019|quote=No, this is not an original Stussy Logo [...] I personally get asked this a lot, but people have been drawing this S long before Stussy was established. People have just assumed it was Stussy and it's sort of spread from there. It's actually quite amusing.}}</ref>\n\nPaul Cobley, Professor in Language and Media at [[Middlesex University]] in [[London]], [[England]], gives another explanation: \"That is, it's fun to draw.\"<ref name=\"Vice\"/>\n\nAs recently as 2020 during the global Coronavirus pandemic, people were discussing the Cool S.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Henohenomoheji]]\n* [[Emoticon]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Drawing]]\n[[Category:Graffiti and unauthorised signage]]\n[[Category:Topology]]\n[[Category:Youth culture]]\n\n\n{{graffiti-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Graffiti symbol}}\n{{multiple image\n| image1 = \"Cool S\".svg\n| width1 = 67\n| image_gap = 12| image2 = \"Cool S\" Drawing Instructions.svg\n| width2 = 201\n| footer = A drawing of the \"Cool S\" and the corresponding four-step guide to drawing one\n| align = \n| direction = \n| total_width = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| caption2 = \n}}\nThe \"'''Cool S'''\", also known as the \"'''St\u00fcssy S'''\", \"'''Super S'''\", \"'''Superman S'''\", \"'''Pointy S'''\", \"'''Slayer S'''\", \"'''Graffiti S'''\", \"'''The S Factor'''\",<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.drawingnow.com/drawings/100332/how-to-make-one-graffiti-s/|title=how to make one graffiti S|website=DrawingNow DrawingNow|language=en|access-date=May 14, 2018}}</ref> \"'''Universal S'''\", and many other names, is a [[graffiti]] sign in [[popular culture]] that is typically [[doodle]]d on children's notebooks or graffitied on walls. The exact origin of the \"Cool S\" is unknown.<ref name=\":0\" /> It may have begun as a [[geometric]] [[puzzle]] or [[pattern]] dating back centuries,<ref>{{cite book|last=Wilson|first=Frederick Newton|title=Mechanical Graphics|date=1890|publisher=The Princeton Press|location=Princeton, N.J.|page=[https://archive.org/details/mechanicalgraphi00will/page/12 12]|url=https://archive.org/details/mechanicalgraphi00will|access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref> or it may have appeared around the 1980s or 1990s as a part of graffiti culture. Contrary to popular belief, the symbol has no ties to either the American clothing brand [[St\u00fcssy]] or to the character [[Superman]].\n\n==Shape==\nThe \"Cool S\" consists of 14 line segments, forming a stylized, pointed [[S (letter)|S]]-shape. It has also been compared to the [[infinity]] symbol.<ref name=Ranker>{{cite web|url=https://www.ranker.com/list/story-behind-that-s-thing/anna-lindwasser|title=Here's The Story Behind That Cool 'S' Thing You Used To Draw In Class|last=Lindwasser|first=Anna|website=Ranker|access-date=August 11, 2019}}</ref> The \"tails\" (pointy ends) of the S appear to link underneath so that it loops around on itself in the same way as the [[infinity symbol]] does.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nyulocal.com/local-investigates-the-mysterious-s-symbol-9254626b8225#.9jqdl0p67|title=Local Investigates: The Mysterious S Symbol|date=February 12, 2014|work=[[NYU Local]]|access-date=January 29, 2017}}</ref> The \"Cool S\" has no [[reflection symmetry]], but has 2-fold [[rotational symmetry]]. As illustrated, a common way to draw the shape begins with two sets of three parallel, vertical lines, one above the other.\n\n==Origin==\nThe origin of the \"Cool S\" is unclear.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.printmag.com/imprint/solve-the-mystery-of-the-pointy-s/|title=Solve the Mystery of the Pointy S|last=Neelon|first=Caleb|date=November 23, 2010|work=[[Print (magazine)|Print Magazine]]|access-date=January 29, 2017}}</ref> The name \"[[Superman]] S\" comes from a belief that it was a symbol for Superman, whose costume features a stylized \"S\" in a diamond shape, but that shape is quite different. Although frequently referred to as the \"[[St\u00fcssy]] S\", Emmy Coats (who has worked alongside [[Shawn Stussy]] since 1985) has stated that it was never a symbol of the Californian surf company.<ref name=\"Vice\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_se/article/that-s-thing-everyone-drew-in-school-what-is-it|title=That 'S' Thing Everyone Drew in School, What Is It?|last=Morgans|first=Julian|date=July 23, 2016|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|access-date=March 21, 2019|quote=No, this is not an original Stussy Logo [...] I personally get asked this a lot, but people have been drawing this S long before Stussy was established. People have just assumed it was Stussy and it's sort of spread from there. It's actually quite amusing.}}</ref>\n\nPaul Cobley, Professor in Language and Media at [[Middlesex University]] in [[London]], [[England]], gives another explanation: \"That is, it's fun to draw.\"<ref name=\"Vice\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Henohenomoheji]]\n* [[Emoticon]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Drawing]]\n[[Category:Graffiti and unauthorised signage]]\n[[Category:Topology]]\n[[Category:Youth culture]]\n\n\n{{graffiti-stub}}\n", "name_user": "160.39.22.31", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cool_S"}
